<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     02-23 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0889</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs Slay Sikhs As Punjab Violence Takes New Turn</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATHUNANGAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The turban of Darshan Singh, a
12-year-old Sikh, was half burned from the heat of the mud oven
where he hid to escape death.
   But the killers _ Sikhs themselves _ yanked him out, and he died
in a burst of gunfire. The boy, his elder brother and their father
all died in the courtyard of the village of Fattu Bheela, home of
2,000 Sikhs.
   It was one more case of Sikhs killing Sikhs. Never before in the
radicals' six-year campaign for an independent homeland have the
killers turned their guns so relentlessly on people of their own
minority faith.
   Of the 283 deaths blamed on Sikh militants this year in the
Sikh-dominated northern state of Punjab, at least 169 victims were
Sikhs. On Friday and Saturday, 31 people died in attacks, at least
20 of them Sikhs.
   ``The militants want the message to go deep _ that they will not
only kill those who oppose them, but even those who refuse to
support them,'' said the Amritsar district police superintendent,
Mohammed Izhar Alam.
   Harbhajan Kaur, Darshan's mother, told of the attack last week
in the village 18 miles north of Amritsar, the Sikh holy city and
heart of the radical campaign.
   She said she was wounded but because of fear, no neighbor came
to help.
   ``I was laying in my courtyard the whole night, bleeding,'' she
said from her hospital bed.
   The Sikh campaign began with attacks on Hindus, India's
religious majority but a minority in Punjab. Last year, most of the
1,000 victims of Sikh radicals were Hindus.
   The radicals allege economic and cultural domination by Hindus
and want an independent homeland for their 16 million people. But
theories vary considerably on Sikh guns are now aiming at Sikhs.
   ``Most of the men killed are either former terrorists or
harborers and their families who now refuse to give shelter to the
militants,'' said S.S. Virk, deputy director general of the
paramilitary Central Reserve Police Force.
   The killers themselves claim all Sikh victims are police
informers or enemies of the 500-year-old faith, founded as an
alternative to the beliefs of warring Moslems and Hindus.
   ``We shed the blood of only enemies, not of innocents or passive
people,'' said Giani Jagir Singh, spokesman for the Panthic
Committee, an umbrella group that controls the Sikh movement.
   ``Write it down,'' he commanded during an interview in a bare,
windowless room in the Sikhs' Golden Temple. ``I have led half a
dozen attacks myself and in every case, we killed only police
informers.''
   Why are Sikh women and children also killed?
   ``Have you heard of an old Punjabi saying _ when you grind wheat
to get flour, some millets also get crushed?'' said Singh, 45, a
large man with flowing beard.
   Dewan Singh, a police detective in Amritsar, said in most cases
the killers wipe out all witnesses because they are recognized by
the victims' families. In 19 of the 25 cases he analyzed, the
victims knew the killers.
   In each of the 19 cases, police found half-emptied glasses of
milk or sarbat, sweetened water with lemon, which were believed
served to the assailants.
   Rarely did the killers have to force their entry, Dewan Singh
said.
   Such was the case with the family of Darbar Kaur, 50, in the
village of Khera Bala-Chak near Kathunangal.
   ``Five Sikh boys came and asked for my younger son, Surjeet. He
opened the door and asked his wife to heat up some milk for the
visitors,'' Mrs. Kaur said.
   ``After a few minutes they fired at Surjeet,'' She said.
Surjeet, her husband, another son, and a 4-year-old granddaughter
were killed, while Mrs. Kaur and her daughter-in-law hid behind a
bolted kitchen door.
   Surjeet had been arrested in July for illegally possessing a
firearm and was believed to be a member of the radical group Babbar
Khalsa. He was freed on bail Jan. 1.
   ``He was not a police informer, but he was required under bail
provision to report to the police station once a week,'' said
Kathunangal police officer Subba Singh. ``So his former associates
drew the conclusion that Surjeet had turned informer.''
   Singh, responsible for maintaining order in 70 villages with a
population of 200,000, said Surjeet was afraid he might be killed.
But he said the police don't have the resources to protect everyone.
   The killers often leave behind a note written on the stationery
of Khalistan, the name of their unborn Sikh nation. The letters
sometimes even carry reference numbers, such as the A-159 on one
left where 12-year-old Darshan Singh died.
   ``They are our death warrants. `A' Stands for Akal (the immortal
throne of the Sikh faith) and the police informer to be killed was
159 on our list,'' explained Giani Jagir Singh, the militant
spokesman.
   He left no doubt that more death warrants could be expected.
   ``If any of the men on the hit list die a natural death, we will
consider it as a great insult to our faith,'' he said.
</TEXT>
