<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Shay     02-23 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Shay,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Composer And Coach Of Greats Al Jolson, Jimmy Durante Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer Larry Shay, onetime
musical coach of such greats as Al Jolson and Jimmy Durante, and
best known for the song ``When You're Smiling,'' died Monday of
lung cancer. He was 90.
   Shay's work was recorded by a number of performers including
Judy Garland, Bing Crosby, Perry Como, Andy Williams, Louis
Armstrong, Nat King Cole, Dean Martin, Doris Day and Guy Lombardo.
   He was Metro Goldwyn Mayer's movie musical director in the early
1930s.
   The composer died at Hoag Memorial Hospital at 1:20 a.m., said a
hospital records secretary who did not want her name used. She did
not know how long he had been hospitalized. Shay also suffered from
emphysema.
   Despite his illness, Shay continued to perform in a local band
for the past decade, family members said.
   His career started during World War I, when Shay put together a
band and show group for soldiers.
   In the '20s, he lived in New York, coaching stars such as
Durante, Jolson and Sophie Tucker.
   In addition to his stint in the movie industry in the early
'30s, he served as program director for NBC radio in the late '30s.
   Among his hits were ``That's Georgia,'' ``Kentucky, Sure As
You're Born,'' ``When You're Smiling,'' ``Knee Deep In Daisies,''
and ``Tie Me To Your Apron Strings Again.''
   He is survived by his wife, Doris; a daughter; a son; seven
granchildren; and three great-grandchildren.
   Private funeral services were planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
