   Outspoken former Gov. Dick Lamm is back in the
public eye, this time as a twice-weekly commentator for a Denver
television station.
   ``You can make fun of television. I sometimes do,'' Lamm said in
a recent interview. But he quickly added that polls show more than
70 percent of the public's political information comes from TV.
   ``It's sad but true, we've gone from town hall America to
airwaves America,'' he said. ``How many senators are more powerful
than John Chancellor?''
   Denver's KMGH-TV, which is running Lamm's commentaries during
its news programs on Tuesdays and Thursdays, says that if Lamm gets
too controversial, it will add a ``counterpoint'' speaker for
balance.
   ``All they told me is there are seven words you can't use on
television. I didn't even ask what they are,'' Lamm said.
   Lamm, a Democrat, has made a cause of pointing out the
pessimistic aspects of the high cost of medical care, earning
himself the nickname ``Governor Gloom.''
   Lamm also is a professor at the University of Denver, and says
he may run for the U.S. Senate in two years.
