<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isabel Bishop, 85, a artist known for her work
depicting the everyday activities of American women, died Friday of
Parkinson's disease. Miss Bishop studied at the Arts Students
League with Kenneth Hayes Miller and Guy Pene du Bois. She began a
series of Union Square paintings after leaving the League in 1924.
Miss Bishop joined Manhattan's Midtown Gallery and the National
Academy of Design and remained affiliated until her death.
   Bishop was known for her work depicting the everyday activities
of American women and for showing life as it existed around Union
Square in 1930.
