<HEAD>Three Disney Movies in Top 5, `Moonstruck' Gets Oscar Nominations
Boost</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Broadcast News...', to CORRECT that `Last
Emperor' in 9th place, `Broadcast News' in 10th, sted the other way
around. Picks up 11th graf, `Here are..'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' and two other Disney
Studios pictures remained in the box office Top 5 while the offbeat
romantic film ``Moonstruck'' capitalized on its Oscar nominations
to secure the No. 3 spot.
   ``Moonstruck'' seemed to lure moviegoers with its nominations,
but weekend receipts don't reflect an interest surge in other Oscar
contenders, including No. 9 ``The Last Emperor'' and No. 10
``Broadcast News.''
   ``The Last Emperor'' got the most Academy Award nominations last
week with nine, ``Broadcast News'' got seven and ``Moonstruck'' got
six.
   Disney-Touchstone awoke to a sixth week atop the box office heap
with ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' featuring best actor Academy Award
nominee Robin Williams as a raucous Saigon disc jockey, ringing in
nearly $7 million.
   Second in the studio's one-two turnstile punch was ``Shoot to
Kill,'' featuring Sidney Poitier in his first movie in nine years,
taking in $4.8 million in its second week of release.
   ``Moonstruck'' was a close third with $4.7 million last weekend
and ``Action Jackson'' took in $3.6 million in its second week to
place fourth.
   Meanwhile, the No. 5 spot was occupied by Disney-Touchstone's
``Three Men And A Baby'' which kept turnstiles spinning in its 12th
week of release with a $3.5 million take. The movie has made $136
million so far.
   The three Disney-Touchstone films have raked in $220 million for
the studio and its Buena Vista Pictures distribution arm, whose
senior vice president Dick Cook said simply: ``We are delighted
with these latest box office figures.''
   Universal's creepy ``The Serpent and the Rainbow'' brought in
$2.3 million for a drop to sixth in its second week of release. The
Kevin Bacon film ``She's Having a Baby'' was seventh with $2.1
million and Justine Bateman's ``Satisfaction'' was eighth with $1.7
million.
   ``The Last Emperor'' was ninth with $1.71 million in receipts
and ``Broadcast News,'' which got William Hurt, Holly Hunter and
Albert Brooks acting Oscar nominations, was 10th with $1.63 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs.
   1. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney-Touchstone, $6.88 million,
1,598 screens, $4,308 per screen, $71.4 million, eight weeks, $21
million.
   2. ``Shoot to Kill,'' Disney-Touchstone, $4.84 million, 1,519
screens, $3,191 per screen, $11.93 million, two weeks.
   3. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $4.73 million, 1,163 screens, $4,057
per screen, $36.5 million, nine weeks, $17 million.
   4. ``Action Jackson,'' Lorimar, $3.61 million, 1,250 screens,
$2,888 per screen, $10 million, two weeks.
   5. ``Three Men And A Baby,'' Disney-Touchstone, $3.53 million,
1,689 screens, $2,095 per screen, $136.58 million, 12 weeks, $18
million.
   6. ``The Serpent and the Rainbow,'' Universal, $2.3 million,
1,211 screens, $1,905 per screen, $14.5 million, two weeks, $8
million.
   7. ``She's Having a Baby,'' Paramount, $2.1 million, 1,133
screens, $1,858 per screen, $10.55 million, two weeks, n-a.
   8. ``Satisfaction,'' Twentieth Century Fox, $1.79 million, 1,018
screens, $1,763 per screen, $5.11 million, two weeks, n-a.
   9. ``The Last Emperor,'' Columbia, $1.71 million, 375 screens,
$4,560 per screen, $16 million, 13 weeks, $25 million.
   10. ``Broadcast News,'' Twentieth Century Fox, $1.63 million,
798 screens, $2,065 per screen, $40.67 million, nine weeks, $15
million.
