<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Toner-Monopoly     02-23 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toner-Monopoly,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ITC Reverses Judge, Says Canon Innocent Of Monopoly Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An administrative law judge was wrong when he
ruled last year that Canon USA Inc. illegally monopolized the
domestic market for dry ink used in some office copying machines,
the U.S. International Trade Commission says.
   The commission, in a 6-0 ruling Monday, overturned Judge John J.
Mathias and terminated the investigation.
   Mathias had ruled in November that Canon, a copy machine giant,
had violated U.S. trade laws by unfairly disparaging independent
toner distributors. Aunyx Corp., a small toner producer based in
Hingham, Mass., had charged that Canon representatives were telling
customers that toner from competitors was ``pirate'' merchandise.
   ITC attorney Edwin J. Madaj Jr. said an opinion detailing why
the commission overturned the judge's decision will not be
available for at least several days. He declined to outline the
commission's reasoning.
   ``Naturally we're very disappointed,'' said Lorraine Hanley,
vice president for dealer sales at Aunyx. ``We don't know why the
commission voted this way.''
   Canon lawyers argued that corporate representatives did not make
disparaging remarks about independent competitors, and if they did,
``it was very minor stuff, the kind of competitive talk that is
normal in any industry where there are competitors,'' said
Washington attorney Harvey M. Applebaum.
   ``We have always said that we would be completely vindicated as
this case evolved,'' Canon USA President Fujio Mitarai said in a
statement from corporate headquarters in Lake Success, N.Y. ``This
decision makes clear that we were right on the law, on the facts
and in the way we market our products.''
   Aunyx has estimated that the toner market for copiers in
question is worth about $250 million annually, but Applebaum said
``that sounds to me very exaggerated.''
   The companies competed for sale of toner for certain types of
Canon copiers, mostly low- and medium-volume office machines.
   Aunyx President Robert Langone said last year that Canon had
about 99 percent of that market while Aunyx and other independent
toner dealers take between 20 percent and 50 percent of the toner
markets of other copying giants like Xerox and IBM.
   The Massachusetts company, which once had 85 employees, is down
to fewer than 30, Ms. Hanley said.
   Bart S. Fisher, an attorney representing Aunyx, said he would
appeal the ITC ruling to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   A separate $300 million antitrust suit filed by Aunyx against
Canon is pending in U.S. District Court in Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     02-23 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Saying Bienvenue To American Farm Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers hear a lot about the European Economic
Community's barriers to U.S. agricultural exports, but there is a
brighter side too.
   The Europeans, particularly French consumers, are developing as
an even larger market for U.S. food products.
   Overall, the 12-nation bloc took $6.8 billion of the $27.9
billion in U.S. farm exports in the 1987 fiscal year that ended
last Sept. 30, up 5 percent from 1986. A further gain to around $7
billion is expected this year.
   Despite the increase and prospects for further growth, U.S. farm
exports are still far below the record levels of the early 1980s.
Thus, every possibility is examined eagerly by USDA trade experts.
   The EEC ranks second only to Asia as a regional market for
American farmers. Japan, with U.S. farm imports of $5.55 billion
last year, is the largest single-country foreign market.
   A recent USDA report says, ``The time is right for U.S.
exporters to consider the French food market.''
   Last year France imported $495 million worth of agricultural
products from the United States, up from $435 million in 1986 and
$403 million in 1985. In the heyday of the early '80s, France
bought a peak of $625 million worth of U.S. food and raw
commodities.
   France is the largest country in Western Europe, with a
population of 55 million and an area of 213,000 square miles _
about four-fifths the size of Texas, says the report by the
department's Economic Research Service.
   ``Changing lifestyles _ more working women, urban rather than
rural life, eating lunch at work, and a greater standard of living
_ have led to changes in the food habits of the French people,''
the report said. ``They are consuming more processed products, like
canned food and precooked dishes.''
   For example, the report said, France's per capita consumption of
fresh vegetables held steady from 1967 to 1982 but the average use
of frozen vegetables rose from 0.5 pounds per capita to 6.6 pounds.
The consumption of canned vegetables jumped to 44 pounds per person
in 1982 from 24.9 pounds in 1967.
   ``According to the French Food Industry Association ANIA, there
have been dramatic changes in consumer spending patterns since
1960,'' the report said. ``The association's data show that the
French buy more pastries, cooked and preserved meats, cheese, ice
cream, cooked dishes, confectionery products and non-alcoholic
beverages as a percentage of their total budget.''
   Meanwhile, the report added, the share of family spending on
wine, bread, fruits and vegetables, and butter, has decreased.
   The analysis, prepared by Mark D. Newman and Victor H. Miesel
Jr., was included in the current National Food Review, a quarterly
magazine issued by the USDA agency.
   American goods compete with agricultural products from other EEC
member countries, which are generally admitted freely into France.
   ``However, specific products of high quality with unique
characteristics can find a place on the French market regardless of
barriers, exchange rates and competitive pressures,'' the report
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has bought an addition 405,000 metric
tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices for delivery in the 1987-88
marketing year, according to the Agriculture Department.
   The sales, equal to almost 14.9 million bushels, were handled by
five companies: Cargill Inc., 135,000 tons; Nichimen America Inc.,
35,000; Bunge Corp., 35,000; Continental Grain Co., 100,000; and
Artfer Inc., 100,000.
   William L. Davis, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said Monday the sales
were part of an authorized 1.2 million tons of wheat announced Feb.
5 under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Although no selling prices or other details were announced,
recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $2.76
per bushel, indicating a U.S. farm value of about $41 million.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   China bought more than 4 million tons of wheat under previous
EEP arrangements, which allow exporters to sell commodities at
reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Davis said the bonuses due the five companies averaged $40.38
per ton, or about $1.10 per bushel of wheat. The bonuses will be
paid in the form of surplus commodities owned by the department's
Commodity Credit Corp.
   China has 495,000 tons remaining for use under the EEP
initiative announced on Feb. 5, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inventories of frozen beef are down 2 percent
from a year ago, but the supply of frozen pork is up 31 percent, an
Agriculture Department report shows.
   As of Jan. 31, the beef stockpile was about 313 million pounds,
down from 320.6 million a year earlier, the report showed Monday.
Frozen pork, at 285.6 million pounds, was up from 217.7 million.
</TEXT>
