<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BudgetReport     02-23 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget Report,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Social Security Mailouts Affected January Surplus, December
Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government enjoyed a rare budget surplus
last month because Social Security checks for January were mailed
before the new year began.
   The Treasury Department said Monday that the surplus between
government spending and revenues jumped to $16.09 billion in
January, a sharp turnaround following a December deficit of $24.22
billion.
   Both months were influenced by Social Security, the government's
biggest benefits program. The government ended up making two
payments in December, the regular one and the January payment,
which was mailed on Dec. 31 because of the New Year's holiday.
   In January, government revenue totaled $81.79 billion, down 4.3
percent from December. Government spending was almost half the
December total, dropping to $65.71 billion in January, compared
with $109.74 billion the month before.
   The surplus was the first since September and only the second in
the past 16 months.
   For the first four months of the fiscal year, which began Oct.
1, the deficit totals $65.81 billion, down 0.7 percent from the
same period in the 1987 fiscal year.
   For the first four months of this fiscal year, government
revenues have totaled $286.66 billion, 5.5 percent higher than a
year ago. Government spending totaled $352.46 billion, an increase
of 4.2 percent over the same period a year ago.
   For all of 1988, the Reagan administration is projecting the
budget deficit will fall to $146.74 billion, down 2.5 percent from
last year's deficit of $150.4 billion.
   The Congressional Budget Office, using less optimistic
assumptions about economic growth this year, projects a 1988 budget
deficit of $157 billion, substantially above the target of $144
billion set in the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law.
   President Reagan sent Congress his budget recommendations for
1989 last Thursday, predicting a 1989 deficit of $129.5 billion.
   The largest spending categories in January were, as usual, the
military, followed by Social Security, other programs in the
Department of Health and Human Services and interest on the
national debt.
   Military spending totaled $19.23 billion last month and $93.52
billion for the fiscal year so far, up 6.5 percent from the same
period a year ago.
   Spending for Social Security totaled just $652 million last
month and $70.14 billion for the past four months, up 4.6 percent
from a year ago.
   The other Health and Human Services programs, including Medicare
and Medicaid, spent $50.51 billion in January and $49.93 billion so
far this budget year, a 1.1 percent increase over 1987.
   Interest on the $2.2 trillion national debt totaled $14.67
billion last month and $75.77 billion so far this fiscal year, an
increase of 9.8 percent over the same period last year.
   For the 1988 fiscal year, interest payments on the debt are
expected to total $210.06 billion, accounting for 20 percent of
total federal spending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
