<DOCNO> AP880223-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SuperTuesdayPolls     02-23 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Tuesday Polls,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Jackson, Gore Ahead in South but Dukakis Favored
Nationwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson and Sen. Albert Gore were the
Democratic leaders in the Southern and border states that vote on
Super Tuesday, according to a poll published today, with
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis very close behind.
   But Dukakis was the favorite among Democratic voters nationwide,
according to the CBS-New York Times poll. The survey found 21
percent of registered Democratic primary voters queried nationwide
said Dukakis was their choice for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   In the Southern and border states, which hold primaries or
caucuses March 8, Jackson had 19 percent, Gore had 16 percent and
Dukakis 13 percent. With a 4 percentage-point margin of error, that
pointed to a close race. Rep. Richard Gephardt had 11 percent and
former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart, 10 percent. The survey also
included South Carolina, which holds its primary March 5.
   In the nationwide sampling, Jackson, with 13 percent, was second
behind Dukakis, the poll found. Gephardt had 12 percent and Hart 10
percent, with a margin of error of 3 points. Twenty-three percent
of both samplings didn't answer or said they didn't know.
   On the Republican side, the CBS-Times poll found Vice President
George Bush leading strongly both in the South and nationwide.
   Bush garnered the backing of 51 percent of the registered
Republicans in Super Tuesday states to 20 percent for Sen. Bob
Dole. In the nationwide sampling, the poll found 42 percent opting
for Bush and 27 percent for Dole.
   The telephone poll of 933 Democrats and 684 Republicans
nationwide taken Feb. 17-21 had a margin of error of plus or minus
three percentage points on the Democratic side and four percent for
the GOP race, the Times said.
   The newspaper said 575 Democrats and 375 Republicans were
surveyed in the Super Tuesday states and South Carolina. The
CBS-Times Super Tuesday figures have a margin of error of four
percentage points for the Democrats and five points for the
Republicans.
   Another survey, this one in the 14 Southern or border states
that hold primries or caucuses on Super Tuesday, suggested Bush
holds a 2-1 lead over Dole. On the Democratic side, Jesse Jackson
and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis were running roughly even,
the Scripps Howard News Service survey suggested.
   Bush led Dole by a 51-26 margin, with former television
evangelist Pat Robertson was third with 11 percent. Rep. Jack Kemp
of New York trailed with 3 percent and 9 percent were undecided,
the poll indicated.
   The pollsters contacted 423 likely Republican voters Feb. 17-19,
and the margin of error was 5 percentage points, the news service
said.
   Among Democrats, Jackson had 22 percent and Dukakis 19 percent _
within the poll's 4 percentage-point margin of error. Gore and
Gephardt each had 14 percent, with 21 percent undecided.
   Hart had 6 percent, the Scripps Howard poll indicated, and Simon
had 5 percent. On the Democratic side, 597 voters were surveyed.
   The survey involved voters in Alabama, Arkansas, Florida,
Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, Missouri,
North Carolina, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas and Virginia, all of
which hold primaries or caucuses on March 8.
   Six other states will also vote on Super Tuesday.
   The survey was done in conjunction with the Birmingham (Ala.)
Post-Herald, The Commercial Appeal of Memphis and The Knoxville
(Tenn.) News Sentinel.
</TEXT>
