<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Falwell-Cancellation     02-23 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Falwell-Cancellation,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Station Stops Falwell's Program For Unpaid Bills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Swaggart, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two independent television stations say Jerry
Falwell owes them thousands of dollars from his TV ministry, but a
spokesman for the evangelist says checks are in the mail.
   Mike Liff, general manager of WPGH-TV, said he was pulling
Falwell's weekly ``Old Time Gospel Hour'' from the station's
schedule because of unpaid bills ``in the neighborhood of $50,000.''
   ``He's flying around in his private plane and he hasn't paid us
since October,'' Liff said Monday.
   Falwell also owes an undisclosed amount of money to WPTT-TV,
according to general manager Chuck Hobbs. The station, which
carries Falwell's daily program, temporarily dropped the show four
years ago for nonpayment, Hobbs said.
   Oma Bradner, who handles Falwell's television accounts for the
Sam K. Pate advertising agency, said late Monday a check was mailed
to both stations on Friday. He said he didn't know the amount of
either check but said ``it was a pretty good bit.''
   Falwell's spokesman, Mark DeMoss, said the checks were delayed
because ``audience support for the program in the Pittsburgh area
has been slow for the last few months.''
   ``I can understand they're upset but I would also hope they
would continue to carry the program,'' DeMoss said. ``I know they
made some strong remarks. But they'll be glad to know we're flying
around in the private jet a whole lot less this year than last.''
   Liff said he's also bothered by the fact that such shows can be
an important source of revenue to television evangelists, who must
pay stations to carry their programs because they do not sell
advertising on them.
   ``We are the vehicle that broadcasts these shows to people who
send in a whole lot of money, possibly at the expense of their own
well-being. That's my problem,'' he said.
   WPGH continued to run Falwell's show without being paid
``because we didn't have a viable alternative,'' Liff said.
   ``There's very little this station could run at 11 p.m. on
Sunday night that's going to make us money.''
</TEXT>
