<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GatewayStates     02-23 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gateway States,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Pouring Cash Into Pre-Super Tuesday Contests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Presidential Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential contender Bob Dole and
Democrat Michael Dukakis have invested the most cash in efforts to
get a boost from the so-called gateway states leading into the
Super Tuesday series of primaries, financial records show.
   These states have been somewhat overshadowed by the 20-state
showdown that will occur on Super Tuesday, but the campaigns
generally agree that whoever does well in the gateway states will
have the look of a winner going into the critical March 8 contests.
   The gateway contests, occurring between now and Super Tuesday's
mega-primary on March 8, are in South Dakota, Minnesota, Maine,
South Carolina and Wyoming.
   Dole, the senator from Kansas, spent more than twice as much as
Bush and their Republican rival Pat Robertson in the gateway
states, according to campaign financial statements filed over the
weekend with the Federal Election Commission.
   Dukakis leads the Democrats in spending for both Super Tuesday
and the gateway contests, the records show. He also had the biggest
bank account at the beginning of this month, $4 million, while the
next nearest Democrat, Sen. Al Gore Jr. of Tennessee, had $2
million.
   The new reports reflect spending through the end of January,
while not reflecting the sizeable expenditures this month on the
Iowa and New Hampshire contests or the subsequent spending toward
Super Tuesday and the gateways.
   By the end of January, the reports show, Dole spent a total of
$786,529 in the gateway contests, compared to Bush's $389,150,
Robertson's $373,105 and Rep. Jack Kemp's $183,831.
   Dole's biggest spending was in Minnesota, $367,097, compared to
Bush's $20,927, Robertson's $75,391, and Kemp's $67,994. The state
holds its caucuses Tuesday.
   Robertson has selected South Carolina as his must-win state, and
had spent $224,234 there by the end of January, compared to Bush's
$126,151, Dole's $110,775 and Kemp's $35,681.
   Kemp's political director, Charlie Black, said Monday that his
candidate will make a big push in South Carolina to come in ahead
of Robertson. Kemp plans a TV campaign there of $250,000 to
$300,000, Black said.
   Bush, the overall fund-raising leader took a conservative
approach to spending in January, spending the least among GOP
contenders during the month, $3.7 million. Robertson spent the most
at $7.9 million.
   Among the Democrats, Dukakis had spent $423,606 on the gateway
states. His nearest competitors were Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois,
$89,202, and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, $75,462.
   They were followed by Sen. Al Gore Jr. of Tennessee, whose
gateway total through January was $40,681. Gore has focused
virtually all of his attention on the Super Tuesday states,
particularly the 14 in the South.
   Simon had said last week that he needed to win either South
Dakota or Minnesota to continue his campaign. He has since backed
off of that statement, citing an infusion of campaign contributions
that can keep him alive beyond those contests.
   Simon spent $66,313 in Minnesota through January, compared to
Dukakis, who spent the most there among Democrats, $266,418. Simon
had spent only $13,705 in South Dakota, while Dukakis again led the
field in that state, with $80,989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
