<DOCNO> AP880223-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gephardt     02-23 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Keeps Up Trade Talk Despite His Amendment's Likely
Scrapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Rep.
Richard Gephardt is still talking tough on trade, despite the
fading prospects of the trade amendment that bears his name.
   ``I want to turn it in the other direction,'' the Missouri
congressman said as he opened a two-day campaign swing here.
``First, we've got to change our trade policies so other countries
treat us like we treat them.''
   As an example, Gephardt pointed to the fact a car manufactured
in South Korea can be sold in the United States at a low price,
while tariffs and taxes in South Korea would push the cost of a
mid-sized American car in South Korea to $48,000.
   Gephardt recently made commercials suggesting that South
Korean-made Hyundais sell for $48,000 here unless South Korea mends
its ways. The commercials, coupled with a populist push, were
credited with helping him win the Iowa caucuses two weeks ago.
   ``If they bring their products here and sell them with ease, I
want to be able to take our products there and sell them with
ease,'' he said. ``I will demand equal trade.''
   He added the United States should not back away from such a
policy.
   ``Why are we selling ourselves short?'' he asked. ``Why don't we
stand up for what's right? When we stand up, (foreign markets) open
up.''
   Gephardt is the author of an amendment to a massive trade bill
that would call for mandatory sanctions against countries with big
trade surpluses with the United States if six months of talks fail
to resolve differences.
   But House conferees working on the measure, which has been
languishing, have said they will soon scrap the Gephardt amendment
in order to get the measure through. One conferee, a fellow
Democrat, called the provision ``bad policy.''
   As a courtesy to their colleague Gephardt, the trade bill
negotiators were expected to wait until after the Super Tuesday
primaries to give his provision the heave-ho.
   Gephardt also repeated his calls for a national energy policy
including a fee on imported oil.
   ``We import as much oil today as we did in 1973,'' he said. ``We
don't have a courageous leadership or energy policy. Why don't we
stand up for America for once and have an energy policy that is
good for the United States?''
   On the issue of defense, Gephardt called for a central
procurement system for defense purchases and said he favored the
Midgetman over the MX missile.
</TEXT>
