<DOCNO> AP880223-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 3rdLd-Writethru a0687 02-23 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0687,0886</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz, Shevardnadze Tell Negotiators To Step Up Pace on Arms
Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOS37,38</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Shultz departure for Belgium, insert 1 graf
after 9th graf pvs, ``Both men...'' Pickup 10th graf pvs,
``American officials...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Soviet Union told their
negotiators Monday to draft anti-cheating and other key provisions
of a new arms agreement within a month so the treaty can be signed
this spring.
   Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov said the Soviets will begin
withdrawing shorter-range SS-12 missiles from East Germany and
Czechoslovakia late this month as a ``display of goodwill.'' The
missiles must be eliminated under the intermediate-range arms pact
signed in December.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz reported progress on human
rights and emigration, and professed not ``the slightest doubt''
that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev will make good on his
pledge to pull Soviet military forces out of Afghanistan.
   A joint statement said progress was made toward banning chemical
weapons and verifying nuclear test limits set by unratified 1974
and 1976 treaties. A report by the official news agency Tass,
however, quoted Gorbachev as telling Shultz the U.S. stand on a
chemical weapons ban ``hampers the working out of an international
convention.''
   Addressing a news conference about arms negotiations, Shultz
said it was ``extremely important'' to accelerate work in Geneva if
President Reagan and Gorbachev are to sign the treaty at their
fourth summit, planned for May or June in Moscow.
   He spoke after two days of talks with Gorbachev and Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Shultz said anti-cheating measures especially were ``an
extremely important thing to get nailed down'' in a pact on
strategic, or long-range, nuclear weapons.
   Shevardnadze told his own news conference later the meetings
produced headway toward agreement to cut strategic nuclear weapons,
which he said ``can be accomplished'' before the summit.
   Both men said their Geneva negotiators were instructed to work
out the key elements in time for their next meeting, March 22-23 in
Washington.
   Shultz left on Tuesday for Brussels, Belgium, the Soviet news
agency Tass said, where he was to brief NATO allies on his visit.
   American officials said they hoped the new instructions would
speed the negotiations.
   ``It's not a breakthrough; it's not dramatic; it may not make a
headline,'' a senior U.S. official said privately, but the sides
now have established that ``verification is the name of the game.''
   Shultz said U.S. and Soviet negotiators were ordered to prepare
three documents dealing with:
   _Inspection of the projected 30-50 percent reduction in overall
numbers of long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear-armed
submarines.
   _How the banned weapons can be eliminated or converted into
other nuclear arms that would remain legal.
   _Agreement, in a memorandum of understanding, to exchange
information about strategic weapons as another way to prevent
cheating.
   According to the secretary, negotiators will try to resolve
``some misunderstandings'' about the U.S. program to develop a
defense system in space. The Soviets contend some tests
contemplated in the ``Star Wars'' program would violate the 1972
anti-ballistic missile treaty.
   Yazov said at an anniversary ceremony for the Soviet army and
navy: ``The Soviet missiles and launchers that are going to be
withdrawn will be sent immediately to the sites where it is planned
to liquidate them after the ratification of the treaty.'' Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze were in the audience.
   East Germany's official news agency ADN reported last week that
Soviet SS-12s in Waren northwest of Berlin had been dismantled, put
in crates and were ready for transport back to the Soviet Union.
   Shultz told his news conference a series of human rights
meetings was agreed upon, the first to set for March 16. Jurists,
psychiatrists and other experts will attend, Shultz said, but he
did not announce where it would be held.
   The secretary, who gave human rights ``the pride of place'' on
his agenda here, said Shevardnadze promised``flexibility'' in rules
that require applicants for emigration to have close relatives
abroad.
   ``That has been straightened out, at least for the balance of
this year,'' he told reporters, adding that Shevardnadze told him
``categorically'' the only barrier to emigration is past work
involving state secrets.
   Kremlin officials have given such assurances before. Shultz said
the sides still were ``exploring'' the point at which involvement
in classified work would cease to count against an applicant.
   After asserting belief in Gorbachev's intentions about
Afghanistan, Shultz said of withdrawal: ``The question is how, and
that is what the negotiations are about.''
   His reference was to U.N.-sponsored talks between Afghanistan
and Pakistan that resume next week in Geneva. Key issues remaining
are a timetable for the pullout and whether an interim government
should be in place while it occurs.
   Gorbachev offered to begin the the withdrawal May 15 and
complete it within 10 months if agreement is reached in Geneva by
March 15. Shultz said he wants the estimated 115,000 troops out by
the end of the year, and ``I think there is a very good chance of
that happening.''
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and
remained to help the Communist government fight Moslem insurgents.
</TEXT>
