<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--WindmillDestroyed     02-23 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Windmill Destroyed,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Windmill Burns to the Ground; Arson Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A century-old windmill once saved from
demolition by donations burned to the ground in a suspicious blaze,
authorities said.
   The structure erupted in a fireball and collapsed Monday night,
fire officials said.
   The blaze was ``definitely suspicious,'' said Firefighter Nick
Ventrella.
   The 26-foot windmill, believed built between 1860 and 1870, was
set for demolition when the private property it was on was bought
about a year ago, said Pat Juviler, director of the Alley Pond
Environmental Center and chairwoman of the Committee to Save the
Windmill.
   It was moved to the center in a park in Queens, and about to be
restored, she said.
   She said nearly $60,000 had already been raised for the move and
the restoration, and that the state had pledged $40,000 more for
the project.
   She said the project will go on with a scheduled fund-raising
dinner in April.
</TEXT>
