<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NSA-Odom     02-23 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NSA-Odom,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: NSA Chief Odom Plans To Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Security Agency Director Lt. Gen.
William E. Odom says he had decided to leave the
intelligence-gathering agency even before there were questions
about whether he would be allowed to extend his tenure.
   ``I've served my tour,'' Odom said Monday in a telephone
interview with The Washington Post. ``I've extended four months
beyond what the normal (three-year) turnover is. I have 34 years of
active (military) duty. It's time to move on to another career.''
   The Post reported today that Odom, 55, asked for the resignation
to be effective Aug. 1. A Soviet scholar, Odom told the newspaper
he wanted to write ``a couple of books fairly quickly, and some
articles.''
   The New York Times reported in today's editions that the Joint
Chiefs of Staff earlier had unanimously recommended against
extending Odom's tenure beyond the typical three years accorded his
predecessors.
   Odom said he initially had hoped to stay at the NSA another
year, but had made his decision to leave late last year, before the
question of his future reached Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci,
the Times said.
   ``I've really kicked this agency into line,'' Odom told the
Times.
   The resignation request was submitted to the secretary of the
Army about 10 days ago and must be approved by the Army chief,
Carlucci and the White House, the newspapers said.
   The NSA, based at Fort Meade in suburban Maryland, assists the
Defense Department in gathering national security information, and
operates facilities designed to collect intelligence and protect
communications and computer security within the government.
   Before assuming his current position in 1985, Odom had been the
Army's assistant chief of staff for intelligence since 1981.
   Pentagon spokeswoman Capt. Mary Laluntas had no information late
Monday on the reported resignation request. Odom's home telephone
listing is unpublished and he could not be reached for comment late
Monday.
</TEXT>
