<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-23 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply, Stock Prices Continue Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped in Tokyo trading today and stock
prices advanced for the ninth straight day.
   After opening at 129.27 yen, the dollar fell by midday to 128.65
and closed the day at 128.50, down 1.45 yen from Monday`s close of
129.95.
   The dollar's fall was attributed to overnight setbacks in New
York and London and strong selling pressure from foreign banks,
dealers said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices closed higher at the
end of Tuesday's session, led by large-capital issues such as
steels and heavy industrials.
   The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 24,949.45 points, up 102.74
points, or 0.04 percent. Volume in the first section was a
moderately heavy 850 million shares, up from 830 million shares
Monday.
   ``There's nothing really big out there to push prices up or
down, but it`s got to run out of steam sometime,'' said Ron Napier,
vice president of Salomon Brothers, referring to the longest
consecutive advance in stock prices since August.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a news conference today
that the higher prices on the stock exchange are the result of
Japan's sound economic fundamentals and optimism about a bright
economic future.
</TEXT>
