<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0728EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Rains     02-23 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Rains,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fearing New Mudslides, Shantytown Dwellers Flee Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slum dwellers gathered possessions
from condemned homes and rescue workers searched mud and rubble for
victims of four days of floods and mudslides in Rio that have
killed at least 75 people.
   Civil defense spokewoman Sonia Hadid said Monday that many poor
people, who perch homes on the steep hillsides that jut up through
this city of 5.6 million, were refusing to obey orders to abandon
their shacks.
   ``They prefer to risk their lives than abandon their worldly
goods,'' she said. Officials warned that torrential rains that let
up Monday had loosened boulders and earth and said they expected
more mudslides.
   ``Get out while there's still time,'' Mayor Roberto Saturnino
Braga told slum dwellers as civil defense officials condemned whole
hillside communities.
   Flash floods and mudslides have punished Rio de Janeiro state
since Feb. 2, killing at least 268 people and leaving more than
13,000 homeless.
   Rains devastated the nearby mountain resort of Petropolis during
the first 10 days, briefly let up for Carnival, then returned late
Friday to plague Rio.
   The Weather Bureau said an Antarctic cold front over Rio dumped
5.1 inches of rain on Saturday alone. Normal rainfall for the month
is 5.5 inches.
   Roads turned into raging rivers that tossed cars and carried
away shanties, rubbish and stones. The rains washed out city
streets, power lines, knocked down large trees and filled homes
with mud.
   In the wealthy Santa Teresa hillside district, a massive
mudslide tumbled onto a three-story hospital wing, killing at least
11 elderly patients and staff. More victims were expected to be
pulled from the thick mud.
   In the working-class Abolicao district, firefighters continued
their search for at least one more resident of a three-story
building of six apartments built on a hillside that fell face
forward late Sunday.
   Officials said 12 bodies were pulled from the concrete and
twisted metal, while 16 dwellers were pulled out alive.
   Three television networks broadcast appeals for donations of
food, clothes, medicines and mattresses to aid the nearly 9,500
city residents rendered homeless by the inundation.
   The homeless were being housed in schools, churches and public
buildings that have been converted into shelters.
   Ms. Hadid, the civil defense spokeswoman, said the death toll of
75 included only bodies that had reached the morgue.
   ``The final total certainly will be higher,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
