<HEAD>State Phones May Have Been Used to Aid Gore Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Commissioner Ward ``Butch''
Burnette said 32 calls from his department's phones to supporters
of the presidential campaign of U.S. Sen. Albert Gore Jr. were made
to discuss official business, not the Democrat's race.
   Burnette, Gore's Kentucky campaign chairman, and two of his
aides involved in the campaign said the campaign may have come up,
though.
   Burnette said six calls to Gore headquarters in Arlington, Va.,
were made to clarify news reports published locally Jan. 19 about
the Tennessee senator's agriculture platform. The calls were made,
however, Jan. 12-14, according to The Courier-Journal.
   The newspaper reported in today's editions that more than 70
calls were made in December and January from state-government
telephones to offices and supporters of Gore.
   The total cost of the 73 calls was $58.97, not including tax.
   The day he was named Gore's state chairman, Burnette said, he
issued a memo to employees telling them not to use state facilities
on Gore's behalf.
</TEXT>
