<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MercyKilling     02-23 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mercy Killing,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Files Motion to Quash Mercy-Killing Subpoena</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association, stressing that
it opposes euthanasia, says First Amendment rights should outweigh
an order that it identify the author of a mercy-killing essay.
   Citing the U.S. Constitution and a state free-press law, the AMA
filed a motion Monday in Cook County Circuit Court to quash a
subpoena from the state's attorney's office seeking the author's
name.
   The essay, titled ``It's Over, Debbie,'' was written by a
resident physician who described injecting a fatal dose of morphine
into a 20-year-old woman dying of ovarian cancer. It was published
in the Journal of the American Medical Association's Jan. 8 edition.
   ``JAMA's confidential sources are protected by the First
Amendment and by the Illinois Reporters Privilege Act,'' AMA
general counsel Kirk Johnson wrote in a statement accompanying the
motion.
   ``As described in our motion, the debate and controversy which
the publication has generated is exactly what the First Amendment
is all about.
   ``The AMA supports the privilege asserted by Dr. George
Lundberg,'' the journal's editor-in-chief, ``to protect JAMA's
confidential sources, not withstanding that the AMA opposes the
practice of euthanasia and that AMA believes the action described
in the essay in unethical,'' Johnson wrote.
   ``Physicians and their organizations also have an ethical duty,
however, embodied in the Hippocratic oath, to teach education and
inform their fellow physicians,'' he wrote. ``It is to fulfill this
latter obligation that the AMA publishes JAMA and gives it
editorial independence.''
   Attorney Newton Minow, a former chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission who is helping Johnson represent the AMA,
said he did not know whether the essay's author was aware of the
controversy.
   Lundberg has said he published the essay to spark debate over
the issue of mercy killing.
   ``I expected a major reaction, but I didn't realize the extent
to which the country was ready for an extraordinary response,''
Lundberg said.
   ``We have clearly touched many raw nerves, and many people have
been thinking about many of the diverse issues involved.''
   He has said he believes the essay describes an actual event. But
on Monday, he said ``the account does have enough vagueness to
welcome critical analysis as to whether it happened, or happened in
this way.''
   Officials in the state's attorney's office have repeatedly
declined to discuss the matter, as is routine during a continuing
investigation.
   ``We're not confirming or denying that we're even looking into
this,'' spokesman Terry Levin said Monday.
   Johnson said a subpoena was served a week ago today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0530EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Banks     02-23 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Banks,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine General Charles Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Marine Corps Brig. Gen. Charles
Banks, who was awarded the Navy Cross for heroism in the Korean
War, died of cancer. He was 73.
   Banks, who died Monday at St. Francis Memorial Hospital, also
served in World War II. His combat service in that conflict
included a tour with Edson's Raiders on Guadalcanal.
   Banks was awarded the Navy Cross for extreme bravery during the
Marine breakout from the Chosin Reservoir.
   Banks, whose decorations also included the Silver Star, retired
from the Marines in 1959 and entered business. At the time of his
death, he was vice president of the Harper Group, a San
Francisco-based freight-forwarding company.
   Survivors include his wife, Jane, of Belvedere and their
daughter, Alexandra Kennedy of Soquel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
