<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Textbooks-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0449 02-23 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textbooks-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0449,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Supreme Court Textbook Ruling To Let Schools Teach,
Superintendent Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-9, `The president ...' with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with plaintiffs reax; picks up 10th graf pvs, `State Attorney ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court's rejection of a
suit challenging what a Tennessee fundamentalist group calls
godless textbooks will enable schools to get on with teaching
children, an education official says.
   ``We've been relieved of a lot of pressure, pressure that's been
on our shoulders since 1983,'' Robert Cooper, Hawkins County school
superintendent, said Monday.
   The lawsuit was filed that year by seven born-again Christian
families, who objected on religious grounds to the list of required
reading textbooks for grades 1-8. The books included passages in
``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``Cinderella,'' works by science fiction
writer Isaac Asimov, Hans Christian Andersen and anthropologist
Margaret Mead.
   After a trial, U.S. District Judge Thomas Hull ruled in 1986
that the families' religious freedom had been violated, awarded
them $50,000 in damages and allowed their children to avoid the
reading classes.
   But the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed that ruling
and threw out the families' lawsuit.
   On Monday, the high court dismissed the families' appeal of that
decision.
   ``At this time we have no alternative other than to accept the
Supreme Court ruling,'' said Vicki Frost, one of the plaintiffs.
   Her husband, Roger, said the high court's action left
fundamentalists across the country persecuted.
   Farley Meade, another plaintiff, said: ``There are a lot of poor
Christian parents who can't send their children to religious
schools. To me that's a sad day for religious freedom in America.''
   The president of the organization that financed the lawsuit
called the Supreme Court action ``the most coercive ruling in the
history of religious liberty litigation.''
   ``We are confident that this dreadful ruling will eventually be
overturned,'' said Beverly LaHaye, president of Concerned Women of
America, in a statement issued in Washington, D.C.
   State Attorney General W.J. Michael Cody praised the court
action, saying, ``Any alternative disposition would have been the
cause of chaos in the school system.''
   Cooper said the protracted case did not particularly disturb the
county's 6,800 public school students ``but as far as
administrative personnel, school board members and even some
teachers, it was very disruptive.'' He said making copies of
records and testifying in court took time that could have been
better used in teaching.
   The seven children involved in the lawsuit have long since
transferred from to private schools, he said, adding that about
4,700 children in grades 1-8 were affected by the lawsuit.
   Robert Sharp, legal counsel for the state Education Department,
said the case never interfered with the state's selection of
approved textbooks or otherwise changed operation of the department.
   ``The one issue that could have caused turmoil was ... whether
there would be other parents who would seek to `opt out' of reading
programs in other schools,'' he said. ``None did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
