<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0520EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea-PlaneAttack     02-23 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Plane Attack,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Command Charges North Korea With Plane Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military commander today charged
North Korea with destroying a civilian airliner to wreck the 1988
Olympic Games and accused communist officials of being
``criminals.''
   Rear Admiral William T. Pendley of the United Nations Command
traded accusations and taunts with North Korean military
representatives over the destruction of the plane. The two sides
also accused each other of fomenting tension and preparing for war.
   ``I want you to tell those who are responsible for killing 115
innocent civilians that their objective, to discourage the
community of nations from coming to the Seoul Olympics, will not be
met,'' Pendley said.
   Maj. Gen. Li Tae Ho, the chief North Korean delegate, said the
communist country had nothing to do with the attack. He charged
that South Korean military authorities destroyed the plane as part
of a scheme to retain power and to discredit the north. ``You are
stirring up confrontation and leading the situation on the
peninsula to the brink of war,'' Li warned.
   The United States, South Korea and other nations have charged
that North Korea was behind the Nov. 29 bombing of a Korean Air
Boeing 707 over the Andaman Sea with the loss of all 115 people on
board. North Korea has denied it had anything to do with the
attack. The wreckage of the plane was never found.
   The charges were made at the first meeting of the Military
Armistice Commission since the loss of the plane. The panel polices
the cease-fire that ended the Korean War between north and south in
1953.
   The United Nations Command delegation presented a videotape of a
televised confession made last month in Seoul by Kim Hyon Hui who
said she was a North Korean agent and that she destroyed the plane
with a bomb as part of attempts to disrupt the Olympic Games that
start in Seoul in September.
   Ms. Kim rode on an early leg of the KAL flight and she and a
male companion took poison when they were detained in Bahrain. The
man later died.
   Li and other North Korean and Chinese officials did not watch
the tape and studiously stared at the ceiling or out of windows.
   Pendley said the confession was damning evidence that the north
could not refute. ``You thought you had committed the perfect
crime, but, like all criminals, you made a mistake,'' he said.
   North Korea has been demanding to co-host the Olympic Games. The
International Olympic Committee and South Korea have rejected the
demand.
   The North Korean delegation replied with a rambling accusation
charging that the South Korean government bombed the plane to
frighten people into voting for the government in the Dec. 16
elections.
   Pendley rejected the North Korean accusations and repeated a
demand that those responsible for the attack be punished and North
Korea apologize for the incident. ``You should honestly admit this
terrible act,'' he said.
   North Korea called the Military Armistice Commission meeting to
demand the United States and South Korea abandon plans for annual
``Team Spirit'' military exercises involving 200,000 men next month.
   It was the first Military Armistice Commission meeting since
October.
   The North Korean delegates charged the exercises were
preparations for an American nuclear attack and warned that the
divided peninsula was being pushed toward war. ``You have nuclear
war plans worked out,'' Li charged.
   Pendley dismissed the North Korean accusations and said the
exercises were lawful military activities intended to guarantee the
safety of South Korea. He said the United Nations Command had no
intention of starting a war and posed no threat to North Korea or
peace in the region.
   ``Team Spirit exercises will continue as long as the threat of
aggression exists,'' he said.
   The United States maintains 40,000 troops in South Korea and
heads the United Nations Command, which represents the 16 nations
that fought under UN auspices against North Korea and China during
the Korean War.
</TEXT>
