<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChessKids     02-23 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chess Kids,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kasparov Meets, Defeats Kids in Bronx</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Kasparov leaned on the table, staring at
the chess board. He scratched his head, studied some more and
accepted a draw.
   Eleven-year-old Josh Waitzkin smiled and shook the world
champion's hand. This memory would last.
   ``Well done,'' wrote Kasparov as he autographed the boy's score
sheet, which Josh will frame.
   It was a heady day for all concerned Monday as Kasparov, the
24-year-old Soviet hero, spent his first full day in the United
States. And 59 even younger chess buffs got a chance to face the
champ in a simultaneous exhibition in a Bronx elementary school
gymnasium.
   ``I was surprised at how long I stayed in _ 42 moves is a lot
against the world champion,'' said Benjamin Shuldiner, a freckled
10-year-old who was checkmated two hours.
   Kasparov, dapper in a gray-and-tan sweater, tan slacks and green
scarf, arrived at the inner-city school smiling and joking, taking
time to embrace curious students and pose for pictures.
   Asked how he expected to do against the children _ a routine
exhibition for any grandmaster _ he laughed.
   ``It is not a serious competition, it is a joke,'' he said in
accented English. ``It's a special exhibition for children. ...
   ``I will be happy if I am upset. If I am upset, they will be
every happy, this is the main goal of the `simul,' to make people
happy.''
   His opponents managed two draws.
   When Kasparov left, he resembled an American sports hero,
working his way through a knot of admirers, signing autographs,
posing for more pictures, shaking hands and ducking into a
limousine.
   ``It's a great day for chess,'' said the champion. ``This is the
beginning of the promotion of chess in the U.S.A.''
   Kasparov said such exhibitions to spark children's interest in
the game are ``a very important tradition'' in chess.
   ``I think it is the duty of the world champion,'' he said. ``If
we get a lot of boys and girls into chess, we can hope that in the
nearest future we will find a new wave of talent.''
   He'll spend five days in New York, playing two more exhibitions
and meeting Mayor Edward Koch on Thursday.
   ``I have just seen the city from the window,'' he said. ``I'll
try to find some time to see something amazing.''
   He spent Sunday evening at the Manhattan Chess Club, where he
played 24 games of speed chess, winning all but one, which he drew.
   ``He played blitz chess,'' said club president Doug Bellizzi.
``Offhand, not serious games, with some very strong players. I saw
two brilliant combinations. This is Mozart, this is Beethoven.''
   Or, as 14-year-old K.K. Karanja said, ``it's like playing Larry
Bird or Michael Jordan one-on-one.''
   Karanja, however, a former national elementary school champion,
managed one of the two draws allowed by Kasparov on Monday. In most
of the games, Kasparov moved instantly, working his way around the
large square of tables. At times _ against Waitzkin, for instance _
he had to stop and think.
   ``I was pretty confident the whole way. I played a few
inaccuracies,'' said Waitzkin, a student at Manhattan's exclusive
Dalton School.
   Classes of students were led through the gym for a glimpse of
Kasparov.
   Kasparov's opponents ranged in age from 7 to 15, and came from
such disadvantaged neighborhoods as the south Bronx, Harlem, East
New York and Brownsville, as well as more affluent areas of
Manhattan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
