<HEAD>Gallaudet University Provost Named President Of American College</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catherine W. Ingold, the provost of Gallaudet
University in Washington, D.C., has been named president of the
American College in Paris.
   The board of trustees chose Ms. Ingold on Monday to replace
Daniel J. Socolow, president for the past five years. She starts
this summer.
   Ms. Ingold, 38, studied at the University of Paris and received
a doctorate in French from the University of Virginia in 1979. She
joined the staff of Gallaudet University, a university for the
deaf, in 1973, and became provost in 1986.
   The American College, founded in 1962, is a fully accredited
four-year American University, with 1,000 students, half of them
U.S. nationals.
   Pierre Salinger, the veteran ABC News correspondent who is
chairman of the American College board of trustees, said 125
candidates were considered during a six-month search.
</TEXT>
