<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     02-23 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ventura Freeway's dubious claim to fame
as the world's busiest piece of road is not only dubious _ it's
false, say transportation officials. And some smog-choked motorists
are unhappy about it.
   ``How did this happen? I appreciated its reputation even as I
was caught in its snarls,'' said Steve Gediman, 26. ``It was
worthwhile just sitting there because I was sort of participating
in a global event.''
    The stretch of freeway, also known as Route 101, through the
San Fernando Valley may never have been the busiest, despite a
listing that says so in the Guinness Book of World Records,
California Department of Transportation officials admitted Monday.
   That's because counting monitors on two other freeway stretches
were out of commission for nearly five years and human guesses
calculating traffic flow there were much too low, said Nick Jones,
an associate transportation engineer.
   Aficionados of Los Angeles' fabled congestion should not
despair, however. The busiest portion of freeway in the world has
been determined to be the Santa Monica Freeway not far away, Jones
said. Coming in second is the San Diego Freeway.
   With the monitors fixed, new calculations show an average of
315,000 cars traveled on one stretch of the Santa Monica Freeway
every day during 1987, while 300,000 cars a day were logged on a
portion of the San Diego Freeway, compared with only 277,000 on the
Ventura.
   ``Any time you get over 250,000 cars per day, what's the
difference?'' Jones asked.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ron Sexton's reward for winning a school
contest was nothing to snort at.
   Sexton, a history teacher and wrestling coach at Wilmington High
School, came in first in a school project to raise money for
Children's Hospital in Columbus. His payoff _ he had to kiss a pig.
   He put his mouth where his money was in what was dubbed the
``Squeal of Fortune'' contest, laying a kiss on the snout of a sow
during a pep rally last Friday while the students and faculty of
the high school watched.
   Sexton won a contest in which students and teachers put money in
gallon milk jugs as their way of choosing someone for the porcine
pucker. There were 45 teachers up for votes, which cost 25 cents to
cast, according to home economics teacher Bonnie Hansen.
   The contest raised $246.40.
</TEXT>
