<HEAD>Winds Rake Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gale warnings continued today over parts of the Great Lakes and
New England, after high winds in the Midwest and Rockies cracked
windows, knocked down electrical poles and fanned wildfires.
   Advisories for blowing and drifting snow were posted over upper
Michigan, where snowshowers were scattered early today.
   Light snow also fell over western Minnesota, the eastern
Dakotas, and from eastern Montana across eastern Wyoming into
north-central Colorado.
   Rain fell from north-central Kentucky across Ohio and northern
New York state.
   Gale warnings were posted today over lakes Huron and Erie, and
in much of New England.
   Ninety windows cracked or shattered in Chicago's Sears Tower
early Monday when winds gusting to 56 mph flung gravel and debris
against the world's tallest building, a Sears spokesman said. No
injuries were reported.
   Broken glass forced authorities to block traffic during the
morning rush hour on the four streets surrounding the 110-story
building, police said.
   Gusts up to 120 mph were clocked at Mines Peak, Colo., early
Monday. Power outages were reported in southwestern Missouri and at
Fort Smith, Ark., where gusts reached 52 mph.
   A 64-year-old man died Monday when the truck he was driving went
off a road to avoid a fallen tree near Garwood, Mo., police said.
   Firefighters in Missouri responded to about a dozen wind-fanned
grass fires Monday, including one that destroyed a farm building
just east of Springfield, authorities said.
   Elsewhere, damage was estimated at more than $1 million Monday
from a wildfire whipped by winds of up to 70 mph, that blackened
2,400 acres of southwestern Montana on Sunday, destroying 39
buildings, including four homes, before being brought under
control. No one was injured, officials said.
   A snowstorm Monday helped douse a 200-acre blaze near Boulder,
Colo., and 90 mph gusts that fanned the fire Sunday subsided.
   Today's forecast called for scattered snow showers in upper
Michigan and northern New England; rain across central and southern
New England, eastern New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, the upper
Ohio and Tennessee valleys; strong, winds over the northern Plains,
the upper Mississippi Valley, along the Great Lakes and across
northern New England.
   Highs should reach the single digits and teens from the eastern
Dakotas across Minnesota, northern Wisconsin and upper Michigan;
20s and 30s across northern New England, much of the Great Lakes
region, the lower Ohio and central Mississippi valleys, the
remainder of the northern Plains, and the northern Rockies; 40s and
50s from central New England across northern Virginia, the upper
Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, Arkansas, Oklahoma, the southern
Rockies, and the Pacific Northwest; near 80 over the desert
Southwest; 60s and 70s over the remainder of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees below zero at International Falls, Minn., to 71 degrees at
both Homestead and Miami, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 fair; Boston 44 windy; Buffalo 34 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 42 fair; Cincinnati 33 snow; Cleveland 37 showers;
Detroit 37 partly cloudy; Miami 71 cloudy; New York 40 fair;
Philadelphia 44 fair; Pittsburgh 46 showers; Portland, Maine 36
fair; Washington 48 windy.
   _Central: Bismarck 13 windy; Chicago 32 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 53 windy; Denver 25 partly cloudy; Des Moines 22
fair; Indianapolis 36 cloudy; Kansas City 31 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 14 partly cloudy; Nashville 57 windy; New Orleans 60 partly
cloudy; St. Louis 39 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 43 fair; Anchorage 20 cloudy; Las Vegas 46
fair; Los Angeles 51 foggy; Phoenix 59 fair; Salt Lake City 30
fair; San Diego 56 cloudy; San Francisco 47 cloudy; Seattle 40 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 rain; Toronto 36 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
