<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeroinSeizure     02-23 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heroin Seizure,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Make Big Heroin Bust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pit bull terrier unhappy with the smell coming
from shipping crates full of Oriental statues led U.S. Customs
officials to up to $1.8 billion worth of heroin at O'Hare
International Airport, authorities said.
   ``It was the largest inland port seizure of heroin in United
States history,'' U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas said Monday after
authorities announced the arrest of six people on drug charges.
   Spike, a pit bull terrier trained to locate drugs by the U.S.
Customs Service, sniffed suspiciously at the seven shipping crates
destined for New York from Bangkok, Thailand, on British Airways on
Feb. 5, said his handler, customs officer Jeff Gabel.
   Gabel alerted superiors, and the statues were uncrated and put
through X-ray machines and other scans. Inside, authorities found
165 pounds of high-quality Asian heroin worth up to $1.8 billion.
   Agents opened the crates, cracked the statues and removed most
of the heroin. Then they repaired the figures, put them back into
the crates and followed the shipping orders that said the crates
should be sent to a house in Norridge, near O'Hare, said Barry
Elden of the U.S. attorney's office in Chicago.
   Agents watched as four people rented a truck and drove the
statues to New York, Elden said.
   Six suspects were arrested in New York on Sunday and charged
with conspiracy to possess with intent to distribute heroin, Elden
said.
   The suspects, who were held without bond, were identified as
Prasit Maneerat of Bangkok; Chang Zhu-Yu and Kaw Ting-Ti, both of
Ocean, N.Y.; Chen Woi-Kong of New York; Eng Chuck Jor of Yonkers,
N.Y.; and Tang Chi-Lap of Brooklyn, N.Y.
   The latest seizure and recent record seizures of cocaine and
hashish indicate that Chicago has become a major shipment point for
drugs, Valukas said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0649EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HaitiDrugs     02-23 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti Drugs,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress to Look Into Haiti Drug Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress plans to hold hearings regarding
allegations that Haiti's top military officers have been smuggling
cocaine into the United States, according to a published report.
   The San Francisco Examiner reported in today's editions that
Alfred Cumming, a legislative aide to Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said
the hearings are scheduled to start in mid-March.
   Cumming said the hearings, to be headed by Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del., or Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass, will be in response to concern
``about the allegations of Haitian cocaine trafficking.''
   The hearings will investigate reports that Haiti, with the
participation of top military officials, has become a major
shipment and refueling point for drugs and guns since February
1986, when former Haitian president Jean-Claude Duvalier was
replaced by a military junta.
   A federal source, familiar with a current probe by the U.S.
attorney's office in Miami, said that Haiti was ``probably another
example of a military that is up to its earlobes in drug
operations,'' the newspaper said.
   For the last year, a federal grand jury has been focusing on
police chief Col. Jean-Claude Paul, whose ranch and airstrip 90
miles from Port-au-Prince has been used by cocaine smugglers, said
U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency investigators.
   The Examiner reported that a congressional source who has been
briefed on the federal probe said an indictment against Paul and
several relatives and associates is imminent.
</TEXT>
