<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Narrowly Lower, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in light European trading early
today as markets waited for clearer signals of how the U.S. economy
was performing.
   Gold prices also declined.
   The dollar was trading at lower levels against all major foreign
currencies at midmorning, but was fluctuating within a narrow range.
   Many traders stayed on the sidelines ahead of Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan's scheduled testimony later in the day
before the U.S. House Banking Committee, traders said.
   They said the testimony might provide a better insight into U.S.
monetary policy, which could give the dollar some direction.
   Also, the markets were awaiting a new batch of U.S. economic
reports due later this week, including the government's latest
revised estimate of fourth-quarter economic growth.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe compared with late rates
Monday:
   _ 1.6922 West German marks, down from 1.6955
   _ 1.3882 Swiss francs, down from 1.3930
   _ 5.7255 French francs, down from 5.7500
   _ 1.8983 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9040
   _ 1,246.50 Italian lire, down from 1,252.25
   _ 1.2713 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2738
   The British pound rose to $1.7665 from $1.7630.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 128.50 Japanese yen, down from
Monday's close of 129.95 yen. In London trading later today, the
U.S. currency traded at 128.70 yen.
   London's major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $443.95 a troy ounce, down from $446 late Monday. A
trader said the market was extremely thin.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $443.50, down from $446.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $446.80, down
from $447.12.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.38, down from
$6.41 late Monday.
</TEXT>
