<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Waldheim 1stLd-Writethru a0479 02-23 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Waldheim, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Controversy Clouds Anniversary Of Nazi Annexation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 2nd graf, ``German troops...until
1955.'' to ADD background on commemoration. Pickup 3rd graf pvs,
``Austrian television...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's plan to have President
Kurt Waldheim address a ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of
Austria's annexation by Nazi Germany is becoming a major point of
dispute.
   German troops marched into the country nearly 50 years ago,
officially linking this Alpine nation with Adolf Hitler's Third
Reich. Austria did not become independent again until 1955.
   Austrians are marking the annexation _ called the Anschluss in
German _ as a time of reflection on a troubled period when throngs
cheered Hitler, Jews were harassed and resistance fighters executed.
   Austrian television and radio, along with many of the country's
newspapers, are giving much attention to the March 11
commemoration. The issue is especially sensitive because of the
widely held opinion in Austria that the country was a ``victim'' of
the Third Reich.
   Now, with Waldheim under fire for his role as a first lieutenant
in the German army in the Balkans during World War II, it is
increasingly uncertain what the bickering coalition government will
do on the March 11 anniversary.
   Many Austrian Socialists have made it clear they are against the
ceremony during which the 69-year-old Waldheim is scheduled to
deliver a speech.
   ``I have misgivings about this event,'' Fred Sinowatz, the
Socialist Party chief and former chancellor, told reporters at a
news conference Monday after a meeting of the party's leadership
suggested that Waldheim should step down.
   The Socialists, senior partner in the government, adopted a
resolution saying a report on Waldheim's wartime record released
earlier this month has ``badly shaken the president's moral
authority at home and abroad.''
   ``It has become obvious that ... Waldheim ... cannot realize the
most important aims he has set for himself, that is to promote
domestic peace in Austria and to increase Austria's prestige in the
world,'' the resolution said.
   The leadership at the meeting, which included Chancellor Franz
Vranitzky, stopped short of asking for Waldheim's resignation.
   The report on Waldheim's wartime record presented no evidence
that would clearly back allegations that he committed wartime
atrocities, but it left open the question of whether he was guilty
of any crime.
   The report, written by an international panel of historians,
said he was ``in close proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the
Balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt ot prevent
them.
   It also said Waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to
make it seem harmless once he could no longer hide it.
   Waldheim has denied any wrongdoing.
   Instead of a commemoration ceremony, Sinowatz called for
reflection of ``what happened on March 11, 1938, and what must be
done so that such a thing never happens again.''
   But Deputy Chancellor Alois Mock, a leader of the conservative
People's Party, the junior member in the coalition government,
rejected the idea of scrapping the ceremony and the Waldheim speech
in Vienna's Hofburg Palace.
   ``That's a suggestion that will never be accepted by the
People's Party,'' said Mock, Waldheim's most vigilant public
defender, at a separate news conference Monday where he spoke on
behalf of the party.
   Fritz Koenig, another People's Party leader, urged a suspension
of the political debate until after the nation commemorates the
anniversary.
   ``I think that after the ceremonies on March 11, there must be a
discussion on how to achieve greater cooperation ... among the
federal president, the government and the Parliament,'' Koenig said
on behalf of the party.
   Newspapers are giving the dispute prominent play:
   ``With increasing frequency, there are suggestions that the
government should simply call off the planned commemoration
ceremonies for March 11,'' the conservative Die Presse said in its
lead story Monday.
   A day earlier, Economics Minister Robert Graf, a People's Party
member, became the latest of several politicians to make such a
suggestion.
   He told a roundtable TV discussion that he had made the
suggestion ``out of concern about further polarization.''
   ``On Account of Waldheim, the 1938 Commemorations are on Shaky
Ground,'' the socialist AZ tabloid of Vienna said in a front-page
headling on Monday.
   The Socialists and the People's Party made plans for the Hofburg
ceremony before the historians' report on Waldheim's wartime past
was issued.
   Waldheim was the conservative candidate in the presidential
election. He became president with 53.6 percent of the votes in a
June 8, 1986 runoff. His term is scheduled to end in 1992.
   In Austria the president is head of state, a largerly ceremonial
position. Vranitzky runs the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
