<HEAD>Two Israeli Soldiers Reported Killed in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 6th graf ``The Israeli...'' to say Israeli army made no
immediate comment on report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas using rocket-propelled
grenades ambushed an Israeli armored patrol in south Lebanon,
killing two soldiers and wounding several others, security sources
said today.
   The sources, speaking on condition they not be identified
further, said the patrol of one tank and an armored personnel
carrier was ambushed near the village of Braachit at sundown Monday.
   ``Both vehicles were raked with rocket-propelled grenades that
set off a chain of ammunition explosions in the tank,'' said one
source. ``No one could have escaped alive from the burning tank.''
   The source said there were several other serious casualties in
addition to the two fatalities in the ambush, but no specific
figures were available.
   The source said the guerrillas were either Shiite Moslem
fundamentalists or pro-Syrian leftists. Both groups operate in that
area. The source said there was not yet enough information
available to be more specific.
   The Israeli army had no immediate comment on the reported attack.
   Braachit is five miles west of Israel's border in an area where
an Israeli ``security zone'' overlaps with the area of operations
of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, known as UNIFIL.
   The scene is about seven miles east of the area where UNIFIL
troops and Shiite Moslem Amal militiamen have been searching for
U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins. Higgins, 43, of Danville,
Ky., was kidnapped south of the port of Tyre last Wednesday.
</TEXT>
