<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Opposition Leaders Meet On Party Merger</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with meeting over, call for more
talks. TRIMS thereafter to tighten. No pickup.
^By M.H. AHN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Young-sam and rival opposition
leader Kim Dae-jung met today to discuss merging their two parties
in time for the parliamentary elections, but they only agreed to
discuss the issue again.
   The surprise, two-hour private meeting was proposed by Kim
Young-sam after he emerged today from two weeks of near seclusion
and told reporters a merger would ensure an opposition victory in
the balloting expected be held in April.
   Kim Dae-jung, president of the Party for Peace and Democracy,
immediately agreed to the meeting, which was held at a Seoul hotel.
   ``We will do our best to make the opposition merger successful
at any cost,'' Kim Young-sam said afterward. Kim Dae-jung said he
was not as optimistic. No specific date was set for another meeting.
   Repeated efforts to reunite the two parties have failed and
several rounds of talks in recent weeks have not produced any
progress. Neither party indicated today that the situation had
changed.
   On Feb. 8, Kim Young-sam resigned as president of the
Reunification Democratic Party, purportedly to help reunite the
opposition before the National Assembly elections.
   The meeting was the two Kims' first since Oct. 29, when they
split in disagreement over which of them should run as the
opposition candidate in the Dec. 16 presidential elections. Each
insisted on running, giving government party candidate Roh Tae-woo
victory despite Roh's failure to win a plurality.
   After the defeat, the two Kims came under strong pressure to
retire from politics. Many people accused them of putting personal
ambition ahead of their avowed campaign goals of ending military
rule.
   When he quit as president of his party, Kim Young-sam said he
had expected the rival opposition groups could agree on a merger.
   Kim Young-sam today said he believed that ``the merger of the
opposition bloc is the only way to crush the ruling Democratic
Justice Party's plot to perpetuate its rule and revive democracy in
this country. So, it must be achieved with the people's power.''
   He said the new Cabinet formed by Roh, who is to take office
Thursday, is merely an extension of that of outgoing President Chun
Doo-hwan. The new Cabinet includes several key holdovers from
Chun's administration.
   Kim Young-sam said he had a ``great deal of doubt about Roh's
implementing democratic reforms.'' Roh, a former general like Chun,
has pledged to an end to the long tradition of authoritarianism in
South Korea.
   The governing and opposition parties, which have been squabbling
over the number of lawmakers to be elected from each district, have
failed to rewrite the election law and to set an exact date for the
National Assembly election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
