<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stun-GunAttack     02-23 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stun-Gun Attack,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Sentenced to Two Years In Prison for Stun Gun Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former police officer convicted of
torturing a 17-year-old boy with a 50,000-volt stun gun was
sentenced to two years in prison by a judge who called his action
``a gross betrayal of public trust.''
   Former Huntington Park Police Officer William Lustig Jr., 32,
was convicted in December of one count of felony assault under
color of authority because of the methods used during questioning
of Jaime Ramirez. Another former officer, Robert Rodriguez, 27, was
found guilty of aiding and abetting in the crime.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Berg on Monday sentenced Lustig to
two years in state prison and Rodriguez to six months in county
jail as a condition of three years' probation.
   ``In our society, a suspect in police custody has the right to
be free from torture,'' Berg said. ``These acts constituted a gross
betrayal of the public trust.''
   ``It's an embarrassment to everyone in the community, this type
of behavior,'' said Deputy District Attorney James Koller.
   Ramirez, who attended the hearing with his parents, said of the
sentencing: ``I think it's fair. It's the law.'' He has filed a $10
million federal lawsuit claiming his civil rights were violated
during the Nov. 30, 1986, incident.
   In December, jurors convicted the two former officers of using a
50,000-volt electric stun gun similar to a cattle prod to torture
Ramirez, who had been arrested for questioning about stereo
components he was carrying as he walked along a street in
Huntington Park, a Los Angeles suburb.
   Ramirez testified during the trial that Lustig used the stun gun
to burn his thighs through his clothing several times during
interrogation.
   Lustig's attorney, Richard Levine, said his client's actions
``were not criminally motivated'' and he has endured enough
punishment through the public humiliation he has had to withstand.
   Lustig had a ``misplaced belief that the ends justify the means
in a criminal investigation,'' Levine said.The attorney said he did
not know whether he would file an appeal.
   Rodriguez's lawyer, William Hadden, said he would appeal, and
the judge agreed to stay Rodriguez's sentence pending the outcome,
setting bail at $3,000.
</TEXT>
