<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugParachutist     02-23 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Parachutist,0486</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Charges Dismissed Against Drug Parachutist's Alleged Conspirator
^By TOM SHARP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conspiracy charges against a woman whose
boyfriend parachuted to his death with 77 pounds of cocaine
strapped to his body were dropped at the request of the prosecution.
   The motion to dismiss the charges against Rebecca Sharp, 32, of
Lexington, Ky., was filed Friday by Assistant U.S. Attorney James
R. Dedrick and approved without comment Monday by U.S. District
Judge James H. Jarvis.
   Dedrick declined to meet with a reporter or return telephone
calls Monday. His motion to dismiss the charges came a week after
he lost a battle to use against Ms. Sharp statements she made to a
government undercover agent.
   The trial of Ms. Sharp, a paralegal, on charges of conspiring
with former Lexington narcotics officer Andrew Thornton II to
import cocaine and to distribute the drug had been set to begin
March 1.
   Dedrick's motion asked that the charges be dismissed without
prejudice, which allows him to seek another indictment.
   ``Rebecca was very happy over that, as you might imagine,'' her
attorney, W. Thomas Dillard III, said of the dismissal of charges.
``Hopefully, that will be the end of it.''
   Dedrick's motion did not specify why he wanted the charges
dismissed, and Dillard said he would not care to speculate, but it
seemed likely that the ruling disallowing Ms. Sharp's statements
was a direct cause.
   Those statements were suppressed, meaning they could not be used
as evidence against her, on Feb. 12 by U.S. Magistrate Robert P.
Murrian.
   Murrian ruled the statements ``were made in a situation so
inherently coercive that they must be considered as involuntary and
compelled'' because the undercover agent posed as a representative
of violent Colombian drug dealers who wanted either their cocaine
or their $12 million.
   Thornton's body was found on a Knoxville driveway the morning of
Sept. 11, 1985. He carried bags with 77 pounds of cocaine in them,
and federal authorities have linked him to some 200 pounds of the
drug found in duffel bags scattered across northern Georgia.
   A few days after Thornton's death, Kieran Kobell, a special
agent with the federal Drug Enforcement Agency, visited Ms. Sharp
in Lexington.
   Kobell, using an alias, and a government informant now listed as
a fugitive took Ms. Sharp on a car ride during which, Kobell said,
she revealed an intimate knowledge of the cocaine-smuggling
operation and promised the deal would go through even if she had to
kill somebody.
   During testimony in the suppression hearing, Kobell said he did
not force Ms. Sharp to say anything during the car ride. However,
Murrian also noted that Kobell threatened both Ms. Sharp and her
attorney in Kentucky, Fred Partin, in a telephone call to the
lawyer the next day, according to Partin's testimony at the
suppression hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
