<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewCaledonia-Clash     02-23 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia-Clash,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Free French Cops; Conservatives Demand Separatists' Ouster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine police officers taken hostage
during a violent clash with separatist rebels were freed today, and
members of the dominant conservative party demanded that the
separatist faction be outlawed on this French-ruled island.
   About 100 protesters battled French gendarmes at a hospital
construction site on the east coast city of Poindimie, holding nine
officers for about 13 hours before releasing them. Officials said
17 officers were injured during the fracas.
   Authorities who spoke on condition of anonymity said all the
protesters involved escaped arrest.
   The Gendarmerie, a police force under the French military, said
in a statement that at least 20 people were injured by sticks or
stones in the battle and four police cars set on fire.
   The Rally for Caledonia in the Republic, a local party with
close links to French Premier Jacques Chirac's Rally for the
Republic party, adopted a resolution today calling on Overseas
Territories Minister Bernard Pons to dissolve the separatist Kanak
Socialist National Liberation Front.
   Dissolution would make the party illegal. The resolution also
called for party leaders responsible for the clash to be expelled
from the island.
   Yewene Yewene, a separatist leader, said the resolution showed
``a logic of intolerance, a policy of contempt and a desire to
humiliate the Kanak people.''
   Yewene said the protesters did not object to the building of a
hospital, but not at the site chosen, which he said was vital to
the local Tieti tribe.
   The Kanak group supports independence for New Caledonia, a
territory of 145,000 people about 1,100 miles east of Australia.
   In a referendum last September, a majority voted against
independence. The Kanak front boycotted the election, saying
immigrants who arrived in New Caledonia in the past three years
should not have been eligible to vote.
   Kanaks make up 42.6 percent of the population and Europeans 37.1
percent. Other nationalities make up the rest.
   Regional elections, which the separatists say they will boycott,
are scheduled for March.
</TEXT>
