<DOCNO> AP880223-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0832EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Helms-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0459 02-23 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helms-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,000</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 14th graf, Helms indicated, to make clear CIA, not
Helms, made inquiry</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms is asking the CIA to
investigate charges that the agency provided personal data to
Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega about Helms and Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy.
   In a letter to CIA Director William Webster, Helms said he had
received reports that the CIA had provided similar information on
other senators to officials in other foreign countries.
   The North Carolina Republican said maintenance of files on
members of Congress would be ``illegal and improper.'' The transfer
of such information to another government would ``call into
question the integrity'' of U.S. intelligence institutions, Helms
wrote.
   The letter, a copy of which was made available to The Associated
Press on Monday, was sent to Webster following testimony by Jose
Blandon, a former Noriega associate turned critic of Panama's
defense chief.
   Blandon, testifying before a Senate subcommittee on Feb. 9, said
the CIA passed to Noriega data about Helms, Kennedy, D-Mass., and
two of their aides. The senators have been among Noriega's
strongest critics on Capitol Hill, citing allegations of Noriega's
involvement in drug trafficking.
   At the time of Blandon's testimony, the CIA said it
``categorically denies'' his allegations.
   A CIA spokeswoman, Sharon Foster, had no comment Monday on
Helms' letter except to say that communications from members of
Congress are confidential but are taken seriously and responded to.
   Blandon's testimony reinforced the notion that the CIA had
maintained close ties with Noriega despite strong evidence dating
back several years that he was involved in drug trafficking
activities.
   Two federal grand juries have indicted Noriega on drug related
charges.
   Kennedy has said it was ``unconscionable that the CIA knew about
Noriega's drug trafficking activities and continued to work with
him for such a long time, but it is even worse to think that the
CIA would provide information about Noriega's leading American
critics to the general himself.''
   Blandon spent Monday at U.S. District Court with prosecutors
investigating the Iran-Contra affair. Although no details were
provided, Blandon presumably was questioned about his testimony
that Noriega agreed to provide training for Nicaraguan Contras
after receiving a request from former White House aide Lt. Col.
Oliver L. North in 1985.
   Helms, in a separate letter to FBI Director William Sessions,
asked if the agency had ever passed on data about members of
Congress or their staffs to the CIA and whether it had engaged in
wiretaps or surveillance on him or members of his staff.
   In his letter to the CIA's Webster, Helms asked whether the CIA
had maintained information on members of Congress or their staffs
and whether such information was ever passed on to any official of
a foreign government, specifically the Panamanian Defense Forces.
   Helms indicated he was skeptical about the CIA's denial,
contending that it made an inquiry afterward to CIA field offices
and to the heads of U.S. agencies involved in national security
issues as to whether the denial was accurate.
   Ms. Foster of the CIA said she was unable to comment on that
allegation.
   Helms asked Webster not to rely on CIA files because the
information alleged to have been passed on may have gone through a
``back channel'' without files being maintained.
   ``It is imperative that an internal investigation be conducted
and all employees in contact with Panamanian government or military
officials be questioned,'' Helms wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
