<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz 4thLd-Writethru a0517 02-23 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0517,0899</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources: Soviets Taking Initial Steps In Afghan Withdrawal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Shultz said ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
details from news conference in Brussels. PICKS up 5th graf, `The
garrisoning ...' SUBS grafs 11-13 pvs, bgng, `Also today .. ., with
6 grafs to UPDATE with details of travel plans, comments on Star
Wars. PICKS up 14th graf, `On human ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
left Moscow today without a firm timetable for a Soviet pullout
from Afghanistan, but U.S. intelligence sources said the Red Army
is taking initial steps to leave.
   Soviet troops are retreating to defensive positions and
dependents are being withdrawn, a solid sign the soldiers will not
be far behind, a senior U.S. official said.
   In addition, soldiers in the 115,000-man Soviet force are not
being replaced when they complete their tours of duty, said the
official, who briefed reporters on Shultz's flight to Brussels on
condition of anonymity.
   Shultz said Monday at the end of two days of talks in Moscow
that he did not have ``the slightest doubt'' the Red Army would
depart. And after briefing NATO officials in Brussels today, he
reaffirmed his expectation the Soviets would quit Afghanistan.
   But he evidently did not get a specific timetable from Soviet
Communist Party General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev or Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   The garrisoning of Soviet troops and departure of dependents is
``solid evidence'' the eight-year military intervention in
Afghanistan will soon end, the U.S. official said.
   On Feb. 8, Gorbachev offered to begin the pullout May 15 if
Pakistan and Afghanistan reach a settlement by March 15 in
negotiations due to resume in Geneva next week. He said the
withdrawal could be achieved within 10 months.
   The Soviets have, however, accused Pakistan of obstructing a
settlement by insisting an interim coalition government be created
in Kabul to prevent the protracted civil strife Islamabad says
would otherwise ensue.
   Shultz has said such a government could facilitate the troop
withdrawal and return of about 3 million refugees from Pakistan.
But another senior U.S. official said Washington does not endorse
Pakistan's position. Referring to the anticipated withdrawal, the
official told reporters: ``We wouldn't want to miss the bus. We've
been trying to get the Soviets out for years.''
   Gorbachev has said Moscow would not make the composition of the
government it leaves behind a condition of withdrawal.
   Shultz stopped at NATO headquarters in Brussels today to brief
the Western allies, who were especially interested in the steps
taken on arms control.
   From Brusssels, Shultz was flying back to Washington for a
26-hour respite before heading for the Middle East try to push
Arabs and Israelis into negotiations.
   ``I don't think many people give me much chance,'' Shultz said
with a smile. But, he added, ``Even if the chances are small, it's
worthwhile trying.''
   Also today, Shevardnadze left Moscow for Prague, Czechoslovakia,
to brief Warsaw Pact foreign ministers, the Soviet news agency Tass
said.
   On Monday, U.S. and Soviet negotiators were directed to prepare
within a month three draft agreements for a treaty to reduce
long-range, or strategic, nuclear weapons by 30 percent to 50
percent. Such missiles have a range of more than 3,400 miles.
   The drafts will deal with verifying compliance with the
cutbacks, disposing the weapons, and exchange of information. They
are to be ready for the next Shultz-Shevardnadze meeting, in
Washington on March 22-23.
   Shultz told reporters in Brussels that the two sides were still
far apart on the U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative. ``I think we
moved it a little bit in Moscow, maybe imperceptibly,'' he said of
the disagreement over the U.S. program to develop a space-based
defense against ballistic missiles.
   On human rights, Shultz persuaded the Soviets to drop for the
rest of the year, at least, a requirement that Jews who want to
emigrate have a close relative living abroad.
   A senior U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said about 90
percent of Jews who have applied for exit visas do not have close
relatives in Israel.
   In the past several months, the official said, the Soviets for
the first time provided the United States with figures on
applications waiting to be processed. On Feb. 1, he said, there
were 1,042 on file.
   Soviets who have performed work considered by the government to
be of vital national importance or that involved classified
information are routinely denied exit visas.
   Shultz told a news conference in Moscow on Monday that he gave a
``good mark'' to the two-day talks with Shevardnadze, that they had
moved the two sides closer to a strategic arms agreement and a
spring summit in Moscow.
   No specific date for a fourth summit between President Reagan
and Gorbachev was agreed to, but Shevardnadze told reporters Monday
that both sides want the summit in late May or early June.
   Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov said Monday the Soviets will
begin withdrawing shorter-range SS-12 missiles from East Germany
and Czechoslovakia late this month as a ``display of good will.''
   The missiles must be eliminated under the intermediate-range
arms pact signed in December. Such missiles have a range of about
300 to 3,000 miles.
</TEXT>
