<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bulgaria-HotelFire     02-23 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bulgaria-Hotel Fire,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five, Not Six People Killed In Blaze, Official Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch tourist who was believed to have
died in a hotel fire that killed five other people has been found
alive, the official Bulgarian news agency said today.
   The news agency BTA said 37 people from Britain, the Soviet
Union, West Germany, the Netherlands, Greece and Denmark were
injured in the blaze in the ski resort of Borovets, 22 miles
southeast of Sofia.
   On Monday, BTA reported six people were killed in the fire, but
today the agency said one man, from the Netherlands, ``has since
been discovered in good condition.'' It did not elaborate.
   According to BTA and the SAS insurance organization in the Dutch
city of Arnhem, the dead tourists included two Dutch women,
identified only as Ms. Ever Van den Berg and Mrs. Stekelenburg. Two
other victims have not been identified and the fifth was identified
as a Bulgarian tourist, Roumen Roussev.
   Of the 37 injured, BTA said 17 were British, four Soviet, five
West German, seven Greek, two Danish and two Dutch.
   BTA said preliminary reports suggest the fire started on the
ground floor and then quickly spread to the first and second floors
of the hotel, which was made of wood.
   Nineteen people were undergoing treatment at the Pirogov
emergency aid institute in Sofia, BTA repoted, adding two of them
were in ``severe'' condition.
   The other injured tourists are at another hospital in the
Bulgarian capital and in a hospital in the town of Samokov, the
agency said.
</TEXT>
