<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TV-Late-Night     02-23 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Late-Night,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS to Launch Pat Sajak Talk Show, Cancel Late-Night Series</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS plans to launch a late-night talk show
with ``Wheel of Fortune'' host Pat Sajak next season that would
compete with NBC's ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson.''
   Meanwhile in New York, NBC announced Monday it is launching
``Later with Bob Costas'' in August, a half-hour talk show that
will follow ``Late Night with David Letterman.''
   The Sajak show means cancellation of the network's late-night
lineup of action shows and music, said a source at CBS. The shows
are expected to remain on the air until at least September, said
the source, who is close to the productions and spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   They include the original series ``Adderly,'' ``Night Heat,''
``Diamonds'' and ``Top of the Pops'' and reruns of ``Hunter.''
   ``At least 20 percent of the CBS affiliates are not carrying the
late-night shows,'' the source said. ``CBS is turning to Sajak in
hopes of finding a format all its affiliates will stay with.''
   Sajak is host of ``Wheel of Fortune,'' the most successful
syndicated show ever.
   CBS Entertainment President Kim LeMasters said recently he
wanted the network to increase its late-night visibility with a
talk show and confirmed that the network was talking with Sajak.
Sajak also discussed the possibility of a CBS talk show recently
when he was a guest on NBC's ``Late Night.''
   The Costas show would be a half-hour addition to NBC's schedule,
following ``Late Night.'' Costas is a sportscaster with NBC, but
his show would feature interviews with people ``from all walks of
life,'' NBC said.
   The show will originate from New York, except in the summer when
it will be based in Costas' hometown of St. Louis.
   Sajak, host of both the NBC daytime version and syndicated
nighttime version of ``Wheel of Fortune,'' is expected to leave the
daytime show sometime this year, though he will stay with the
nighttime show, said Betsy Vorce, a spokeswoman for King World,
which distributes ``Wheel'' for syndication.
</TEXT>
