<2ND_LINE>PM-Webb-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resignation To Rekindle Debate Over Size, Importance Of Navy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Webb Resigns Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with Cohen's comments. Edits to tighten. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee said today that the resignation of Navy Secretary James
H. Webb will force Congress to take a closer look at the Pentagon
budget and the future size of the Navy.
   ``I think what his resignation will do will cause us to look at
our commitments,'' Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said on ``CBS This
Morning.'' ``Can we, in fact, afford to keep the commitment that
we've made without spending the money necessary to put out a fleet
to do it?''
   The senator later added that Webb's decision ``may spur very
critical analysis of exactly where we're going with the defense
budget.''
   Webb, in announcing his resignation Monday, said he quit because
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci made budget decisions that mean
the target of a 600-ship Navy will never be met.
   ``The resignation ... may be right for him but a bit premature
for us,'' Cohen said. ``After all, Secretary Carlucci has to come
before Capitol Hill, present the budget.
   ``We might disagree. We might agree with Secretary Webb that
perhaps the allocation of the cuts should not have come out of
shipbuilding, perhaps they should come out of some other service or
some other way of achieving those cuts,'' Cohen said.
   In 1981, President Reagan promised to build the Navy to a total
of 600 deployable ships from the 450 the service had at that time.
   The Navy was given large increases for shipbuilding as part of
the record military spending buildup in Reagan's first term.
Although overall defense spending has slowed sharply during the
last three years, Navy shipbuilding continued to grow, although
more slowly.
   Navy officials had said they would meet the target by next fall,
but Carlucci ordered the service to mothball 16 aging frigates,
leaving it with 580 ships.
   The defense secretary ordered the cuts as part of a package of
$33 billion worth of reductions Carlucci had to find under an
agreement reached by Reagan and the Democratic-controlled Congress
to cut federal spending.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said Monday that Webb's
decision ``has obviously launched an important new stage of the
debate about Pentagon priorities and the size and type of Navy we
need.''
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said, ``I never believed that there
was anything magic about the number 600.''
   While Carlucci ordered 16 older ships cut, the Navy's budget
includes money for 17 new ships. Among them are one missile-firing
submarine, two more 688-class attack subs, the first of a new class
of ``Seawolf'' attack subs, and three destroyers.
   Carlucci declined to respond Monday to Webb's criticism, but he
noted last week that he had to make ``tough choices'' in cutting
the budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
