<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Economy     02-23 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Economy,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Economy Grows, But Rising Prices Hurt Many</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's economy grew by a robust 9.4 percent in
1987, but rising prices caused by high consumer demand lowered
living standards for one out of five city dwellers, the State
Statistics Bureau said today.
   China's gross national product for the year was $295 billion,
ranking it seventh in the world. The report said industrial output
was up 16.5 percent, while agriculture output increased 4.7 percent.
   The bureau, in an annual report, said China's 200 million urban
dwellers made an average of $248 last year, up 10.6 percent before
inflation. Its 800 million peasants averaged $125 each, up 5.3
percent.
   But Zhang Zhongqi, director of the bureau's comprehensive
statistics department, also said at a news conference that a
nationwide survey showed 21 percent of urban households had less to
spend last year because of an 8.8 percent rise in the cost of
living index.
   He said retail prices rose 7.3 percent nationwide, compared to
about 6 percent rise in 1986. In the cities, however, inflation hit
9.1 percent.
   He said the main factor was the inability of the nation's
producers, particularly of food and consumer goods, to meet the
growing demands of a more affluent society.
   Meat, poultry and egg prices climbed 16.5 percent, and fresh
vegetables and aquatic products rose about 17 percent. Pork and
sugar were rationed for the first time in decades in many cities
because farmers, discouraged by rising prices for raw materials,
cut back production.
   Wage earners who received no salary raises and retirees on fixed
incomes suffered the most from the price spiral, he said.
   Zhang said the government was trying to overcome supply-demand
imbalances by promoting production of non-staple commodities,
controlling excessive investment that has led to an overheated
economy and subsidizing some prices where consumers and producers
are particularly hard hit.
   He said 10 percent of China's urban residents were economically
distressed, defined as having an annual income of less than $108.
   In rural areas, 8.2 percent, or about 60 million people, were
under the poverty line of $54 a year. Zhang said poor people in the
countryside fell from 80 million in 1986, but he gave no
comparative figures for the urban poor.
   Zhang said unemployment hovered around 3 percent in 1987. He
said underemployment _ millions of workers in factories and offices
with little or nothing to do _ was an even more serious problem.
   The Chinese government has acknowledged that inflation,
unemployment and income disparities are all problems that China
will have to live with as it adjusts from a rigid central planning
system to a state-controlled but increasingly decentralized market
economy.
   Among the strong points were the nation's foreign trade, with
exports rising 27.8 percent to $39.5 billion. The trade deficit
fell from $12 billion in 1986 to $3.7 billion last year.
   It said new foreign investment in 1987 totalled $7.57 billion,
up 4.3 percent, of which $5.33 billion was from borrowing and $2.4
billion from direct investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
