<1ST_LINE>r i PM-VampireHeist     02-23 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vampire Heist,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Munch Painting, `The Vampire,' Stolen From Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Vampire,'' a painting by Norwegian
artist Edvard Munch that was insured for $2.3 million, was stolen
today, the Munch Museum reported.
   Curator Arne Eggum said thieves broke through a ground floor
window of the museum and fled with the picture, which depicts a
woman with her mouth on a man's neck.
   ``After the museum alarm sounded, the theft was quickly
discovered and reported to the police by a caretaker who lives in
the museum building,'' he said.
   Wheel tracks outside the building indicated the culprits fled in
a small car, he told NTB news agency. Police said border
checkpoints were alerted.
   ``The Vampire'' was one of three paintings with the same theme
rendered by Munch in 1893 and 1894. A second painting also is in
the museum and a third is in Goteborg, Sweden.
   Munch, who died in 1944, bequeathed his private collection of
his art to the city of Oslo, including 1,100 paintings, 4,500
drawings and 18,000 prints.
   The Munch Museum has had several unresolved thefts since it
opened in 1963, and experts have called for improved security.
</TEXT>
