<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CubaPrisoners     02-23 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba Prisoners,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba To Release More Political Prisoners, U.S. Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cuban government plans to
release a significant number of political prisoners in an effort to
block a formal United Nations investigation of human rights in
Cuba, U.S. officials say.
   Fidel Castro will ``release thousands of political prisoners
mixed in with common prisoners'' to persuade member nations to vote
down the American proposal for the U.N. investigation, said Armando
Valladares, chief of the U.S. delegation to the U.N. Human Rights
Commission in Geneva.
   A spokesman for a Cuban delegation in Geneva was quoted today by
the Fort Lauderdale News-Sun Sentinel as saying a major
announcement would be made in Cuba on Wednesday, but he would not
elaborate.
   A State Department official who closely follows Cuban affairs
said the ``thousands'' suggested by Valladares, who spent 22 years
in Cuban prisons, may be overly optimistic, but a good chance
exists the Cubans will free enough prisoners to make the action
appear significant.
   ``Even if it is for cosmetic purposes, we love it,'' said the
official, who asked not to be identified. ``We're talking about
human lives here. Even if a release is done cynically, people are
still out of prison.''
   The United States placed a similar resolution before the U.N.
Human Rights Commission's annual session last year. It failed by
one vote on a procedural motion 19 to 18, with five nations
abstaining. The State Department again expects a close vote.
   Although the resolution does not condemn Cuba's human rights
record, a U.N. investigation of human rights practices on the
communist island would be politically embarrassing to Castro.
   Estimates of Cuban political prisoners range from as few as 500
to as many as 10,000. The State Department official said Castro
himself has acknowledged holding 1,000 to 2,000 such prisoners.
</TEXT>
