<HEAD>Shevardnadze Briefs Warsaw Pact Colleagues on Shultz Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with briefing over. CORRECTS to say CTK
now reporting Poland sent its deputy foreign minister, sted foreign
minister. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze briefed Warsaw Pact colleagues today on his talks in
Moscow with U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz, the state
news agency CTK said.
   Shevardnadze arrived in Prague this morning to a welcome from
Foreign Minister Bohuslav Chnoupek, then went to the Foreign
Ministry in the Cernin Palace to inform colleagues of the latest
superpower talks on arms reduction and Afghanistan.
   CTK quoted Foreign Ministry spokesman Dusan Rovensky as saying
Shevardnadze briefed Warsaw Pact colleagues ``in a profound and all
round manner'' about his talks with Shultz.
   The Foreign Ministry reported two hours after the session began
that the Warsaw Pact ministers had ended their talks.
   Shultz and Sheverardnadze concluded two days of talks in Moscow
earlier today, when the secretary of state departed for Brussels to
brief NATO foreign ministers. The superpower ministers said their
negotiating session moved the superpowers closer to a strategic
arms agreement and a spring summit in Moscow.
   Besides Chnoupek, foreign ministers attending today's session in
Prague included Romania's Ioan Totu and Bulgaria's Peter Mladenov.
   Poland sent Deputy Foreign Minister Henryk Jaroszek. East
Germany and Hungary were represented by their state secretaries,
Herbert Krolikowski and Gyula Horn.
