<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-US,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>25 U.S. Troops Detained Briefly, Embassy Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian officials detained 25 U.S.
military personnel here for two hours and then released them
without filing charges, a U.S. Embassy spokesman said today.
   But a top Panamanian military official denied the personnel were
detained, and said police officers only briefly stopped them to
check for drivers' licenses.
   The U.S. Embassy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
told The Asociated Press that Panamanian officials detained the 25
troops as they were driving Monday to U.S. military installations
located in the former Panama Canal Zone.
   Most of the troops were driving motorcycles but two were in cars
and one was walking, the spokesman said. Panamanian officials
released all 25 after two hours without charges, the embassy
official said.
   Col. Leonidas Macias, chief of police for the Defense Forces of
Panama, denied police had detained the U.S. personnel. Macias said
local police momentarily stopped them to ask for drivers' licenses
and to remind them that U.S. troops are prohibited from wearing
their uniforms outside the former Canal Zone.
   Relations between Panama and the United States have been
strained since last June, when protests started here against the
leadership of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, chief of the Defense
Forces and the power behind the civilian government.
</TEXT>
