<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan     02-23 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Announce A Plan For Cabinet To Replace Communists In
Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghan guerrilla alliance today
announced a plan to form a coalition Cabinet that would replace the
communist government of President Najib and ensure the withdrawal
of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Western diplomats in Kabul, meanwhile, reported a bomb went off
in the Soviet Embassy compound, indicating the guerrillas are
intensifying their attacks in the capital.
   The seven-party Islamic Unity of Afghan Mujahedeen announced the
plan in a statement telexed from the Pakistani border city of
Peshawar. It stipulates that Afghanistan would have a 28-member
Cabinet to replace Najib's Peoples Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   The statement said the government would be made up of 14
ministers from among the guerrilla leadership, seven
representatives from among the 3 million Afghan refugees in
Pakistan and ``seven Moslems presently living in Kabul.''
   Earlier, guerrilla leaders said these ``Moslems'' would include
non-communists in the Kabul administration who have not committed
serious offenses ``against the people'' during the eight-year war.
   The proposal, which would allow the guerrillas to control the
Afghan government, was not expected to be accepted by the Soviets
or the current administration in Kabul.
   Diplomatic sources said today that Moslem guerrillas have
stepped up attacks in Kabul, where Communist officials and Soviet
advisers reportedly are preparing to leave.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at
least 18 explosions were heard during the past week in the Afghan
capital, including one in the Soviet Embassy compound and one near
Radio Afghanistan.
   One source said a bomb inside the Soviet compound Feb. 19 caused
some injuries, but there were no further details.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced early this month
that the Red Army could begin pulling its 115,000 troops out of
Afghanistan by May 15 if Kabul and Islamabad sign a U.N.-sponsored
accord by mid-March.
   A new round of indirect talks between Islamabad and Kabul is
scheduled for March 2 at Geneva. Pakistan insists an accord should
be linked to an agreed plan on formation of a transitional
government.
   Islamabad and the guerrillas are pushing this point because they
fear an outbreak of fighting between various Afghan groups and the
communists if no government is in power.
   The Soviets, however, disagree, charging that such an insistance
on setting up an interim government is obstructing Soviet plans to
withdraw.
   Guerrilla leaders have rejected any power-sharing with the
current Kabul officials and today's statement from Peshawar backed
up that position.
   The statement said a Shoora-ali or supreme council would also be
formed to oversee the Cabinet. It would consist of the leaders of
the seven-party alliance and would provide ``joint leadership
during the interim period.''
   The insurgents said the ``broad-based transitional government
will represent all sections of the Afghan nation.''
   The alliance said there would be a consultative council of 75
members consisting of two members from each of Afghanistan's 28
provinces and 19 members from among Moslem religious scholars,
intellectuals and technocrats. The council would frame the interim
laws to administer the country until an elected constituent
assembly writes a constitution.
   The country would adopt the name, the Islamic State of
Afghanistan, ``wherein the Koran ... will be supreme,'' the
statement added.
</TEXT>
