<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LAGangs 1stLd-Writethru a0487 02-23 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LA Gangs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,0825</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Deployment Stirs Racial Tensions In Gang-Ridden L.A.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to recast, picking up 4th graf pvs,
`Authorities say ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police crackdown on street gangs has been
applauded by some black leaders tired of the violence that claimed
300 lives last year, but the arrest of an off-duty black officer
also raises the question of harassment.
   Black and Hispanic leaders accused police of largely ignoring
the gang violence until a woman bystander was killed Jan. 30 in
street-gang crossfire in an upscale neighborhood.
   But two weeks after the shooting, an off-duty black policeman
from a blue-collar suburb was arrested by Los Angeles police as he
stood on a street corner in the same neighborhood, accompanied by
six black youths. The officer said his group was conducting an
informal ``sting'' operation to investigate alleged harassment by
city police.
   Both the arrest and the killing of 27-year-old Karen Toshima
occurred in Westwood Village, a theater and restaurant district
that soaring housing prices have turned into a relatively wealthy
neighborhood.
   Authorities say there were more than 300 gang-related murders in
Los Angeles County in 1987 and the rate is increasing. But gang
violence usually is confined to the predominantly black and
Hispanic southside neighborhoods of the nation's second-largest
city where turf battles between drug dealers have led to drive-by
shootings.
   Five people were killed and five others were injured in gang
shootings last weekend even as police staged a crackdown. Deputy
Chief Glenn Levant, newly appointed as the city's anti-gang czar,
said the more than 50 arrests were part of a strategy to prevent
murders by taking gang members out of circulation.
   Children playing in parks and a 67-year-old woman sitting in a
wheelchair have been killed when gang hitmen missed their targets.
   ``And that's not the way it should be. We should be able to live
normally,'' said Barbara Thomas, spokeswoman for the South Central
Organizing Committee, which says it represents thousands of black
families.
   City Councilman Nate Holden, who is black and represents a
largely black district, said the yearning for more police
protection crosses racial lines.
   ``I've had white people complain about the gangs. They all just
want to feel secure in their community and their homes,'' he said.
   At the same time, the sting by Sgt. Don Jackson of the Hawthorne
Police Department called into question the racial sensitivity of
the Los Angeles police.
   ``None of those kids did anything except stand on that corner
and be black _ and that was enough,'' said Jackson, who was
released on his recognizance after being arrested on a misdemeanor
charge of resisting an officer.
   The police department defended the arrest of Jackson and
frisking of the others, saying the group, dressed like gang
members, was blocking the sidewalk and refused to move.
   The question of police harassment is among the issues being
considered as the city moves ahead with a plan to hire 150 more
officers, increasing the force to its largest strength ever, 7,500
officers.
   Police Chief Darryl Gates on Monday declined to say anything
about how he will deploy his forces until after a March 8 hearing
of the city's advisory Police Commission.
   Mayor Tom Bradley, as he approved the new hiring last week, said
the additional forces would help ``return this city to a drug-free,
gang-free atmosphere.''
   John P. Kenney, a criminologist and former Police Commission
member, said more police officers is not the answer. ``It wouldn't
solve the problem. It would for a few days or for a few weeks. Then
you get complaints of overpolicing and harassing,'' he said.
   ``Historically, there's a resentment to an excessive show of
force,'' said Garrett Capune, professor of criminology at the
University of Southern California. ``It has a racist overtone, you
know, there seems to be more crime because there's more officers.
It becomes a sort of self-fulfilling prophecy.''
   But Holden replied: ``These guys can sit in some classroom and
think what it's supposed to be like. But they haven't seen the real
world. I resent them. Let them come into the black community and
see what it's like.''
   Hundreds of southside residents demonstrated at police
headquarters after extra officers were deployed in Westwood this
month, primarily at the request of merchants who were afraid their
business would be hurt by news of the gang shooting.
   Minority activists later publicized a study by the independent
Public Administration Service in Virginia that appeared to show
police responded more slowly to crimes in poor areas.
   The police department on Friday released a letter from the
principal author of the report stating that it had been widely
misinterpreted. The letter said the study concluded the department
takes too long to respond to emergencies, but that geographical
differences are not significant.
</TEXT>
