<HEAD>Court Rejects Common Market's Ban On Hormone-Treated Meat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Court of Justice today voided a
1985 European Economic Community law banning the marketing of
hormone-treated meat in the 12-nation trade bloc.
   The EEC high court said the Common Market states had not
followed correct procedures when they enacted the ban, which was
passed by a written procedure that required unanimity.
   Denmark and Britain had opposed the ban and the British took the
issue to court.
   The ban on the use of cattle-fattening hormones took effect Jan.
1 for meat produced in the EEC. It was to take effect in January
1989 for imported beef.
   The United States has called the ban an unfair trade practice
and threatened retaliation. It also disputed the contention of EEC
consumer groups that there was enough scientific evidence to show
that the hormones posed a human health threat.
   Proponents ontended the ban did not discriminate against the
United States because it applied to all nations, including those of
the EEC.
   U.S. beef exports to the EEC total about $130 million a year.
</TEXT>
