<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InsuranceBattle     02-23 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insurance Battle,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Quick Trial In Attempt to Help Dying Boy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a quick trial of a lawsuit
that could affect whether an 11-year-old boy with leukemia lives or
dies.
   The suit was filed by the boy's father, Jim Lacina of Geneva, to
regain health insurance coverage he contends was mistakenly
canceled.
   Doctors say the boy, Jamie, needs a bone marrow transplant by
March 15 to survive more than a few months. But the Fred Hutchinson
Cancer Research Center, the Seattle hospital that could treat the
boy, requires patients to have insurance coverage or $100,000 in
hand before it will perform the procedure, said hospital
spokeswoman Susan Edmonds.
   Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Judge Carl J. Character declined
Monday to decide the case without a jury, but set a jury trial date
for Monday so a verdict could be issued in time for Jamie to get
the treatment.
   ``We've definitely advanced this case more than a year,''
Character said. ``They (the Lacinas) came in and indicated the
condition of the young man had become more critical. ... Hopefully
it can be resolved in a timely fashion.''
   Lacina says chemotherapy no longer is an effective treatment for
his son.
   In the lawsuit, filed in 1986, Lacina said Nationwide Life
Insurance Co. of Columbus terminated his health insurance without
notifying him.
   A nine-year agent for Nationwide, Lacina lost his job in 1983
because of company cutbacks. Attorneys for both sides agree that he
paid to continue his policy after he lost his job.
   Lacina's attorney, Gerald Jeppe, told Character that Lacina
didn't receive a copy of his policy, a notice that his premium was
due, or a termination notice in late 1983. He asked the judge to
rule in Lacina's favor without a jury trial.
   Jeppe said Lacina is applying for Medicaid while he awaits a
decision on the case. Meanwhile, a fund for the boy has been
established at a bank, he said.
   Nationwide's attorney, Edward E. Duncan, told Character that the
company mailed Lacina the documents in question. A jury should
decide whether Lacina received them, he said.
   ``The facts of this case are indeed tragic. A little boy through
no fault of his own may be denied care,'' Duncan said. ``The long
and the short of it is whether Mr. Lacina is telling the truth when
he says he didn't receive either of those letters or that policy.''
   Duncan said Nationwide will prove at the trial that Lacina's
behavior was inconsistent for a man who thought he had health
insurance coverage. Lacina ran up large hospital bills for his son
and filed for bankruptcy, Duncan said.
   ``The lawsuit wasn't filed until the summer of 1986,'' Duncan
said. ``What was Mr. Lacina doing between 1983 and 1986 with these
hospital bills if he had coverage?''
   Jeppe declined to discuss the case aside from the comments he
made in court.
</TEXT>
