<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Security 2ndLd-Writethru a0593 02-23 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Security, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0593,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Limits Job Protection for Some Government Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 15-19, In other action, with other cases.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today limited the job
protection for government workers fired for lacking security
clearances.
   By a 5-3 vote, the justices agreed with the Reagan
administration that the Merit Systems Protection Board lacks
authority to decide whether the denial of security clearance is
justified.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun, writing for the court, said, ``It
should be obvious that no one has a right to a security clearance.''
   He said judgments about who should receive clearance ``must be
made by those with the necessary expertise in protecting classified
information'' and he said the board lacks that expertise.
   The court ruled against Thomas E. Egan, who was hired in 1981 as
a laborer at the Trident Naval Refit Facility in Bremerton, Wash.,
on the condition he subsequently receive a security clearance.
   The facility is used to test and repair Trident submarines. All
jobs at the facility require security clerance.
   When he was denied the clearance because of two past criminal
convictions, Egan was fired in 1983.
   Egan challenged the firing in an appeal to the Merit Systems
Protection Board, which was created by the Civil Service Reform Act
of 1978 to protect federal civilian employees from unfair
disciplinary treatement.
   The board concluded that it lacked the authority to review
Egan's case. But a federal appeals court here overturned the
board's decision and sent Egan's case back to the board for further
study.
   The Reagan administration argued that the appeals court ruling
threatened the government's ability to protect national security.
   Dissenting today were Justices Byron R. White, William J.
Brennan and Thurgood Marshall.
   White, writing for the three, said the government's interest in
protecting its secrets would not be jeopardized by granting Egan a
hearing before the review board.
   ``The majority's decision frustrated ... congressional intent by
denying any meaningful hearing to employees such as (Egan) who are
discharged on national security grounds,'' he said.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who joined the high court Thursday,
did not take part in today's decision.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Ruled that a criminal suspect's rights are not violated when a
witness who is unable to identify the suspect in court testifies
about an earlier identification of the accused.
   The justices, voting 6-2, ordered the reinstatement of the
conviction of a California prison inmate in the beating of a prison
guard who suffered memory loss because of the attack.
   _ Ruled unanimously that businesses may not be sued in federal
court for refusing to contribute to multi-employer union pension
funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires.
   In an 8-0 ruling, the court rejected Reagan administration
arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases could undermine the
solvency of the multi-employer pension plans.
   The security case is Navy vs. Egan, 86-1552.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
