<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marines-Homosexuals     02-23 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marines-Homosexuals,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine Corps Charges Two Women with `Indecent Acts'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps has charged two
women officers with ``fraternization and indecent acts'' with other
female troops at the training base here, a spokesman said.
   Maj. Robert W. McLean, public affairs officer at the Marine
Corps Recruit Depot at Parris Island, said a sergeant and a captain
in the Fourth Recruit Training Battalion were charged Friday with
violations of several articles under the Uniform Code of Military
Justice.
   He said charges against other women are being considered.
   ``An Article 32 hearing, which is similar to a grand jury
hearing, has been scheduled for next week,'' McLean said. ``The
purpose of this hearing is to inquire into the allegations and
charges and recommend disposition.''
   The spokesman said the hearing could result in a recommendation
for court-martial, administrative action or a recommendation that
the charges be dropped.
   Charged were Capt. Judy A. Gretch, administrative officer for
the battalion, who has been in the Marines since 1981, and Sgt.
Mary P. Kile, a former drill instructor who has been in the Marines
since 1983, McLean said.
   Earlier this month, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
the Army's ban on homosexual soldiers unconstitutional.
   But McLean said the charges are not affected by the ruling.
   ``They are not being charged with lesbianism, but with indecent
acts,'' he said.
   Capt. Joanne Schilling, a public information officer for Marine
Corps headquarters in Washington, said Monday the Corps' policy on
homosexuality is the same as that of the Department of Defense.
   The uniform code states that homosexuality is ``incompatible
with military service,'' and that certain overt acts are prohibited.
   The Marines do not knowingly enlist people who are homosexual,
and the type of action they take against Marines who are found to
be homosexual is left up to the commanding officer, said Lt. Col.
John Shotwell. It can range from an administrative discharge, under
honorable conditions, to court-martial, which can include a
military prison sentence.
   Three women who said they were being investigated told The State
newspaper of Columbia that the Marine Corps had planned to
court-martial or discharge as many as 10 women who train female
recruits. None of the women interviewed by The State were charged
Friday.
   The women, who spoke to the newspaper on the condition they not
be identified, said they and others have been accused of
homosexuality, sodomy and fraternization but have not yet been
formally charged. They said they are not homosexual.
   Parris Island is one of two boot camps in the country where
recruits are sent for an 11-week basic training program, and the
only one to which women are sent.
   Of the 200,000 Marines, roughly 10,000 are women, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
