<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Kennedy-Mafia 3rdLd-Writethru a0586 02-23 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy-Mafia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0586,0946</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exner Told Story About Alleged JFK Mob Link for $50,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd-8th grafs, `Parts of ...,' with 7 grafs to add quote
from New York Post interview with Ms. Giancana.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People magazine paid Judith Campbell Exner
$50,000 for interviews in which she claimed to have served as a
courier and contact for President Kennedy and a Chicago mobster,
the author of the article says.
   Kitty Kelley said Monday that she and Exner, who claims to have
arranged at least 10 meetings between Kennedy and Mafia boss Sam
Giancana in the early 1960s, split a fee of ``about $100,000.''
   Parts of Exner's story were questioned today by Giancana's
daughter Antoinette, the author of ``Mafia Princess.''
   Ms. Giancana said on ``CBS This Morning'' that she never met
Exner but knew that she was her father's girlfriend. And she said
that her father wanted to help in the alleged assassination plot
against Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
   But she said that as far as she knew, her father never spoke to
Kennedy during his time in the White House.
   ``He always told us about people he'd been with and met,'' she
told the New York Post in an interview. ``But not once did he say
anything about meeeting Kennedy. I'm sure Dad would have said
something.''
   Moreover, ``my father had an utter contempt for the Kennedys.
Why would he ever want to meet with JFK in the White House or
anywhere else?'' she said on the CBS program.
   Ms. Giancana said her father did not need Kennedy's help, but
that Kennedy needed Giancana's help in Chicago while he was running
for president.
   She told CBS it was possible that Kennedy asked Exner to go to
Giancana and ask for help, ``but how, probably, I really don't
know.''
   Questioning Exner's account that Giancana gave her a note to
deliver to Kennedy, Ms. Giancana said her father did not put things
in writing. ``The man had at least a little class. He never put
anything in writing where they could bring it up or show it from
the day he had written it.''
   Kelley said she first arranged to talk to Exner about Kennedy
and Giancana in 1983, but plans fell through after Exner demanded
at the last minute to be paid.
   ``I told her, `I don't pay for interviews. Don't you just want
to be honest and tell the truth?''' Kelley recalled. ``But I didn't
get the story because I wouldn't pay. This time, People did it.''
   Kelley said payment was justified now because Exner has terminal
cancer and ``the story is a little piece of history.''
   Elizabeth Wagner, publicity manager at People, said the magazine
had no comment on the fee.
   Columnist Liz Smith reported in her column in today's New York
Daily News that she put Kelley and Exner together. Smith said she
did not pursue Exner's story herself because ``for Exner's sake, I
couldn't afford to.
   ``She is suffering from terminal cancer, she needs the money to
live out her days and pay medical bills, and only a magazine like
People can pay the big bucks needed to offer up such a story.''
   In a 1975 appearance before the Senate intelligence committee,
Exner said she had an 18-month affair with Kennedy before and after
he entered the White House, and that she later had an affair with
Giancana. But she said she knew of no ties between the two, and
that Kennedy never knew of her friendship with Giancana, which
predated her affair with Kennedy.
   In an interview Monday on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' Exner
said she changed her story because ``things have changed
dramatically for me. I've had two bouts with cancer and I've just
had my lung removed and I've been given a fairly short length of
time (to live.) And I was being very uncomfortable with not being
able to tell the truth.''
   In 1975, ``I was afraid for my life so I was afraid to tell the
truth,'' she said. ``My husband and I made a very coscious decision
not to tell the story.''
   Exner said she witnessed one of the Giancana-Kennedy meetings,
and that she carried envelopes on many occasions between Kennedy
and Giancana and Johnny Roselli, Giancana's lieutenant in Las
Vegas, Nev., and Southern California. She said Giancana once told
her he had met Kennedy in the White House.
   Kelley said Kennedy apparently wanted mob assistance to win the
presidency in 1960, and later to eliminate Cuban leader Fidel
Castro.
   Giancana was murdered in 1975, Roselli a year later.
   Kelley said Exner produced airplane tickets, hotel bills and
appointment books from 1960 through 1962 to support her story.
White House telephone logs show she had more than 70 conversations
with Kennedy.
   Jeff Smith, spokesman for Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said,
``There has been no comment and there probably will not be a
comment'' from the Kennedy family.
   G. Robert Blakey, a professor of law at the University of Notre
Dame and an expert on organized crime, said he found Exner's story
``incredible.''
   ``The president of the United States dealing directly with a
mobster and no one knowing around him knowing about it?'' he asked.
   Blakey, a former Justice Department lawyer who worked for the
House committee that investigated Kennedy's assassination, said
congressional investigators in the 1970s verified Exner's reports
of her affair with Kennedy.
   But, he said, ``my judgment was that she gave all the
information she had at that time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
