<1ST_LINE>u w PM-TaxReturns     02-23 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Returns,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>39 Percent of IRS Answers In Error: GAO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional auditors said today a very
preliminary survey indicates taxpayers are getting correct
responses only 61 percent of the time when they telephone tax
questions to the Internal Revenue Service.
   However, the General Accounting Office, which conducted the
survey, acknowledged that it is so incomplete that the results may
not be valid.
   IRS Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs told a House Ways and Means
subcommittee that a much more thorough check, by the IRS itself,
has found telephone ``assistors'' are giving the correct answer
74.8 percent of the time.
   ``We are obviously not satisfied with answering three out of
four questions correctly at this time,'' Gibbs said. ``We are not,
however, totally surprised by our figures . ... The large number of
tax law changes this year was bound to challenge our assistors
despite our training and planning efforts.''
   The commissioner noted that it is not just IRS employees who are
having trouble finding all the correct answers. He cited a survey
of 50 tax professionals who came up with 50 different answers when
asked by Money magazine to calculate the taxes owed by a
hypothetical family.
   Gibbs noted that the 74.8-percent accuracy rate by IRS telephone
answerers this year compares with a 79-percent mark in a GAO survey
last year, before most provisions of the landmark 1986 tax overhaul
had taken effect.
   Jennie S. Stathis, associate director of the GAO, an
investigative arm of Congress, told the subcommittee that ``under
the circumstances, we believe IRS did a good job in trying to
prepare its employees and the taxpaying public for the 1988 filing
season.''
   She said auditors found that 84 percent of taxpayers who visited
IRS walk-in facilities for help with their tax returns were
satisfied with the assistance and that 74 percent received help
within 15 minutes.
   However, Ms. Stathis said, the GAO found ``the need for IRS to
improve the accuracy of telephone assistor responses to assure that
returns are completed accurately and processed timely.
   She ackowledged that the GAO, in checking the accuracy of IRS
telephone assistors, had made only 224 calls over six days, and
said the results were so preliminary that they could not be
projected as an accurate sampling. Those calls produced correct
responses 61 percent of the time, although 4 percent were not
complete.
   The GAO survey is continuing, as is the IRS' own effort to check
how its employees are doing. In contrast, the IRS finding of 74.8
percent accuracy is based on more than 5,000 calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
