<HEAD>Man Surrenders After Shooting Police, Taking Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `After the ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
suspect's ID, charges; SUBS 9th graf, `The man ...,' with 2 grafs
to UDPATE with comment from hostage, delete outdated material.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drifter shot two plainclothes
policemen with one of their guns in a struggle on a downtown
street, then took refuge in an office building where he held six
hostages before surrendering, police said.
   Police Officer Ed Gorrell, 33, was shot in the head and was in
serious condition today after surgery at Brooke Army Medical
Center, hospital spokesman staff Sgt. King Lance said.
   Officer Onofre Serna, 26, suffered a graze to the chest area and
was in stable condition at Medical Center Hospital, hospital
spokeswoman Ruby Salazar said.
   The suspect, identified as David Johnson, 28, was charged with
two counts of attempted capital murder and was in Bexar County Jail
in lieu of $1 million bond, said police spokesman Sgt. Paul Buske.
   After the scuffle Monday night with the policemen, the gunman
ran into a nearby office building and took the hostages, Buske said.
   ``The officers stopped the individual ... and a struggle ensued.
One of the officers lost his weapon. (The suspect) picked up the
weapon and several shots were fired,'' Buske said.
   Police Chief William Gibson said the man made no demands when he
took the hostages. Gibson said he didn't know immediately why the
officers stopped him.
   The gunman fled into the Travis Park Plaza building, took two
people hostage on one floor, released them, and then took three
other people hostage on the third floor. The three escaped when the
gunman walked into another area to take a sixth hostage, Buske said.
   The gunman surrendered to police shortly before 10 p.m., about
an hour after he released the last hostage, following talks with
police negotiators, said Buske.
   ``He seemed disoriented at first, despondent, that he had gotten
framed,'' hostage Jerry Renaud said today. ``He said he wasn't
there to hurt us. He said he just needed a place to hide out for
the night.''
   The man was described as a street person by City Manager Lou Fox.
   ``My understanding is he (the gunman) had some mental problems
and it's your typical downtown problem that we've been faced
with,'' Fox said.
   Gorrell and Serna were part of a downtown foot patrol aimed at
deterring street crime; Buske described the patrol as effective in
combating downtown muggings.
   Last month, a mentally ill homeless man shot and killed a Dallas
police officer in a downtown parking lot. The killing touched off a
wave of public support for police when Dallas Police Chief Billy
Prince blamed some City Council members for creating an atmosphere
that led to the shooting by criticizing police.
</TEXT>
