<HEAD>Legislators Nominate BBC For Nobel Peace Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of legislators has nominated the overseas
radio service of the British Broadcasting Corp. for this year's
Nobel Peace Prize.
   BBC chairman Marmaduke Hussey announced the nomination of the
corporation's External Services on Tuesday. The BBC said there are
at least 100 other nominations from around the world for this
year's prize.
   The Nobel peace prize normally is awarded to individuals, but
the London-based human rights group Amnesty International received
it in 1977.
   The BBC's overseas radio services are headed by the flagship
English-language BBC World Service and broadcast in 37 languages to
an estimated world audience of 120 million.
   The 22 House of Commons legislators, who come from different
parties, said in their letter to the Oslo-based Nobel Peace Prize
committee the nomination was in recognition of the BBC's 55 years
of international broadcasting.
</TEXT>
