<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-ElSalvador     02-23 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-El Salvador,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Resolution Supporting March 20 Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee today
approved a resolution of support for El Salvador's upcoming
elections, but only after lawmakers expressed reservations about
the country's human rights record.
   On a voice vote, the panel approved a resolution noting El
Salvador's efforts since 1979 to establish a constitutional system
that institutionalizes an electoral process, and recognizing the
large turnout in 1984 for the election of President Jose Napoleon
Duarte, despite threats of violence.
   The resolution, sent to the full House for a vote, ``expresses
confidence that the people of El Salvador will reject efforts to
disrupt the election'' scheduled for March 20 to select national
legislators and local officials.
   Past elections have been plagued by threats of disruption and
warnings to voters not to participate made by the leftist Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front, which is waging a guerrilla war
against the Duarte government.
   The bill was watered down slightly after Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y.,
objected to phrasing flatly stating that El Salvador has achieved a
system ``which respects human liberties.'' The bill was changed to
say only that the country has ``sought to'' establish such a system.
   ``Give them a little credit for trying, Ted,'' said committee
Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla.
   Weiss referred to reports that rightist death squads have
resumed their activities in recent months, and noted that the
country's judicial system has failed to live up to U.S. hopes.
</TEXT>
