<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Neo-Nazi     02-23 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Neo-Nazi,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Accused of Neo-Nazi Activity Seeks Asylum in Denmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German living in Denmark
applied for political asylum after Bonn requested his extradition
for neo-Nazi activity, a Justice Ministry spokesman said Tuesday.
   Thies Christophersen, 70, applied for asylum on the grounds of
``political persecution'' in West Germany, said spokesman Clas
Nilas. ``We are presently considering the case according to normal
procedures.''
   West German authorities submitted an extradition request two
weeks ago for Christophersen, who has lived in Denmark for two
years.
   Christophersen has published works saying there were no gas
chambers in the Nazi concentration camps, no mass murders and no
medical experiments on humans.
   Such material is outlawed in West Germany, but not in Denmark.
The Justice Ministry, however, has expressed willingness to meet
the extradition request.
   Christophersen owns a publishing company in the town of Kollund
just north of the West German border that produces Nazi literature.
His residence and work permit was extended for five years in
September.
</TEXT>
