<1ST_LINE>u w PM-HijackingSuspect 1stLd-Writethru a0615 02-23 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijacking Suspect, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled today that a confession
by a suspected Lebanese Shiite terrorist that he had led the 1985
hijacking of a Jordanian airliner was illegally obtained by the FBI.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker, who sharply criticized
the FBI's interrogation, suppressed the oral and written
confessions that Fawaz Younis made to federal agents following his
Sept. 13, 1987, arrest in the Mediterranean after he was lured
aboard an FBI-chartered yacht off Cyprus.
   Younis, a former member of the Shiite Amal militia, is scheduled
to stand trial March 22 on charges he had led the June 11, 1985,
hijacking of a Royal Jordanian airliner from Beirut International
Airport.
   The plane was flown to several points in the Mediterranean and
destroyed by explosives the next day after passengers and crew were
taken off the jetliner.
   Parker ruled that fractures Younis suffered on both wrists when
he was slammed to the deck of the yacht by FBI agents, plus
seasickness, made it impossible for him to waive rationally his
rights against self-incrimination.
   The judge also noted that the FBI deliberately kept Younis
aboard a Navy ammunition ship for four days during which he
underwent ``relentless interrogation.''
   ``The defendant's will was overborne by the interrogation and
his capacity for self-determination was critically impaired,'' the
judge said.
   The judge sharply criticized the FBI for taking four days to
transport Younis from the yacht where he was seized to an aircraft
carrier from which he was flown to Washington for arraignment
before a federal magistrate.
   ``The slow voyage across the Mediterranean appeared to serve
only the government's purposes _ ample time to educe a confession.
This was a clear abuse of the obligation to bring the defendant
before a judiciali officer immediately following his arrest,''
Parker said.
   Justice Department spokesman Patrick Korten said the agency had
no immediate comment on Parker's decision.
   Federal prosecutors have other evidence against Younis,
including a videotape of him reading a statement to reporters
before the plane was blown up at the Beirut airport.
   Two Americans who were aboard the plane when it was stormed by
five gunmen carrying AK-47 assault rifles have identified Younis as
leader of the hijackers.
   In addition, the prosecutors will be able to use the testimony
of Jamal Hamdan, a friend of Younis who lured him to the
FBI-chartered yacht off Cyprus on the pretext of completing a drug
deal.
   Parker found that Younis ``was in an extremely weakened physical
condition at the very time when he was explained his rights. In an
uncertain physical condition, in an oppressive environment, and
subject to relentless interrogation, Younis lacked the will
necessary to voluntarily waive his rights.''
   The judge noted that ``the government had deliberately scheduled
four days for the voyage across the Mediterranean; four days which
Younis would be subjected to constant questioning by agents.''
   While ruling the confession was illegally obtained, Parker
dismissed a defense motion that Younis's arrest was illegal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SouthDakotaAt-A-Glance     02-23 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Dakota At-A-Glance,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from South Dakota to attend the 1988 Democratic and
Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Saturday, March 12
   Presidential filing deadline: Tuesday, December 29, 1987
   Non-binding presidential primary: Tuesday, February 23
   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, Richard
Gephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon
   Pledged delegates: 15
   Super delegates: 4
   Total delegates: 19
   Delegates allocated: Saturday, March 12
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, March 12 and Saturday, April 23
   South Dakota Democrats choose pledged national convention
delegates through a one-tiered caucus system put in place after the
national party determined the state's presidential primary was
being held in violation of the rules.
   The primary on Feb. 23 will be a non-binding ``beauty contest,''
although state party officials said they would feel bound by honor
_ if not by rules _ to honor the wishes of the voters in awarding
national convention delegates to presidential candidates.
   South Dakota, which has just one congressional district, will
choose 10 congressional-district delegates at a statewide caucus to
be held in Mitchell on March 12. The party has been compelled to
provide bus transportation to any Democrat needing a ride to the
caucus.
   The state's remaining five pledged national convention delegates
will be picked by the state committee on April 23 and will be
allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the
results of March 12 caucus.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, February 23
   Presidential filing deadline: Tuesday, December 29, 1987
   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, Pat
Robertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig
   Delegates: 18
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, February 23
   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, February 23
   All of South Dakota's 18 delegates to the Republican National
Convention will be elected directly from the primary ballot. Since
the state has one congressional district, all delegates will be
elected at-large.
   Delegates will be awarded to presidential candidates in
proportion to the results of the primary. A candidate must receive
at least 20 percent of the vote to qualify for any delegates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
