<DOCNO> AP880223-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeditionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0480 02-23 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sedition Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: White Supremacists Considered Poisoning Water to Create
Unrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new 4th graf with testimony today; SUBS 8th graf pvs,
`Ellison testified ...,' with 7 grafs to add more from today's
testimony. Deletes last graf to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white supremacist group considered
dumping enough cyanide to kill 440,000 people into the water
supplies of New York or Washington, D.C., to create civil unrest,
the group's former leader testified.
   James B. Ellison, a key prosecution witnesses in the trial of 10
men accused of plotting the violent overthrow of the government,
said one of the defendants, Robert Miles, gave him a 30-gallon
barrel of cyanide and declared:
   ``The ones who would be killed would not really matter. It would
be a good cleansing.''
   Ellison also testified that in 1983, members of a white
supremacist group he led had participated in a murder, robberies
and attempts to blow up utility facilities.
   Ellison is serving 20 years for racketeering and weapons
violations committed when he led the Arkansas-based
religious-military group, called the Covenant, the Sword and the
Arm of the Lord. He was arrested in 1985 after a four-day standoff.
   Ellison, 47, said Monday he agreed to cooperate with prosecutors
after the government agreed to relocate and give new identities to
the two women he considers to be his wives and to his nine children.
   Miles and nine others are charged with conspiracy to overthrow
the government by force. The government alleges that they and four
others on trial, including Aryan Nations leader Richard Butler,
espouse white supremacist goals or belong to white supremacist
groups.
   Those four, and one of the accused conspirators, are charged
with plotting to kill a federal judge and an FBI agent. Two are
also accused of interstate transportation of stolen money. All the
defendants face maximum sentences of 20 years in prison and $20,000
fines on each charge if convicted.
   Returning to the witness stand today, Ellison said that Richard
Wayne Snell, a member of his group, murdered William Stumpp on Nov.
11, 1983, in the robbery of a pawn shop that Stumpp operated in
Texarkana, Ark.
   ``This is what they were doing at that time,'' Ellison said,
referring to occasional forays involving robberies and attempts to
disrupt utilities.
   Ellison said he asked Snell later why Snell had killed Stumpp.
   ``He said that he was an evil man, he was a Jew, and that he
just needed to die,'' Ellison testified.
   Snell, one of the defendants in the case, is on death row in
Arkansas for the murder of Stumpp, and is serving a sentence of
life without parole for the 1984 slaying of state Trooper Louis
Bryant.
   Ellison said the robberies were undertaken because of an
agreement made in 1983 at Hayden Lake, Idaho, by himself and
leaders of other white-supremacist groups to take action designed
to bring down the government so that an all-white state could be
established in the nation's Northwest.
   In his testimony Monday, Ellison described how defendants
William Wade and his son Ray Wade solicited the group's help to
find and kill U.S. District Judge H. Franklin Waters and FBI
Special Agent Jack Knox, both of Fayetteville.
   He said the Wades wanted to avenge the slaying of a fugitive tax
protester, Gordon Kahl, who was killed along with an Arkansas
sheriff in a 1983 shootout with federal authorities at a house on
land owned by William Wade.
   Knox helped prosecute people who harbored Kahl, and Waters
presided over the trial.
   Ellison said Ray Wade urged that local officials involved in
Kahl's death ``be hanged publicly from the lamp post there in
Smithville.''
   The idea, Ellison said, was to make an example of them so that
other officials would not take similar actions.
   Ellison testified that Miles, 63, of Cohoctah, Mich., gave him
the barrel of cyanide after Ellison participated in a survivalist
conference in Dearborn, Mich., in 1981. Ellison said he also
received some chemicals to make explosives and rocket propellant.
   He said he was wary of transporting it, but Miles told him,
``You might need it sometime. It will kill a lot of people.'' The
government says the cyanide was enough to kill 440,000 people.
   Ellison testified that he, Miles and defendants Louis Ray Beam
Jr., 41, of Houston and Butler, 69, of Hayden Lake, Idaho,
discussed in 1983 using the cyanide to poison the water supplies of
New York or Washington, D.C., in an attempt to create public unrest
and show the government was powerless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
