<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Uganda     02-23 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Uganda,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ugandan President Reshuffles Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Yoweri Museveni reshuffled his
Cabinet for the second time since coming to power in 1986 and
created three new posts for deputy prime ministers, Radio Uganda
reported Tuesday.
   The state-owned radio gave no reason for the shake-up, in which
Museveni kept on all 44 ministers, but transferred 32 of them to
new posts.
   Among those receiving new portfolios was Stanislas Okurut, the
former minister of culture, sports and youth, who has not been
heard from since his kidnapping two months ago by rebels in eastern
Uganda. Okurut was named minister of labor.
   The new deputy prime ministers are former Minister of State
Eriya Kategaya, former Foreign Affairs Minister Paul Ssemogerere,
and former Minister of Internal Affairs Abubakar Mayanja. Samson
Kisekka retained his post as prime minister.
   Museveni seized power in this East African nation in January
1986 after leading a five-year bush war. His first Cabinet
reshuffle was in November 1986.
</TEXT>
