<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ElectionsRdp 1stAdd a0662 02-23 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elections Rdp, 1st Add, a0662,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: convention delegates.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The week's campaign marked something of a break between New
Hampshire's intensive leadoff primary a week ago and the highly
visible Southern contests ahead.
   But for Dole, it marked an opportunity to demonstrate strength
on the heels of his New Hampshire loss, and he taunted the vice
president for not competing.
   ``I don't know where George Bush is,'' he said in Duluth.
``We're going to send him a map of Minnesota so at least he gets a
little idea where it is.''
   But Bush's aides wanted no part of two states so close to Iowa,
where the vice president finished a humbling third in caucuses two
weeks ago. Instead the vice president spent his time in South
Carolina, which votes on March 5, and in several Super Tuesday
states.
   Dole enjoyed the support of Sen. Larry Pressler and Gov. George
Mickelson and was a prohibitive favorite in South Dakota.
   He looked for a boost from Minnesota, as well, but sounded less
confident of a victory there.
   Party officials said Minnesota was tailor-made for a Robertson
surprise, noting his earlier success in organizational contests
such as Iowa, where he finished a surprising second, and in Hawaii,
which he won. Robertson also was well known in the state because
his one-time television program was viewed widely.
   Kemp, his candidacy on the ropes after a weak third place finish
in New Hampshire, purchased television advertising at the last
minute in South Dakota. His aides conceded in advance that
Minnesota looked like a lost cause because of Robertson's presumed
strength.
   Among the Democrats, New Hampshire primary winner Dukakis
dreamed of a two-state sweep Midwestern sweep that would clearly
establish him as a candidate with national appeal.
   His rivals said he spent a fortune organizing Minnesota, leaving
Gephardt, Jackson and Simon in his wake.
   South Dakota was another story _ and a heated one.
   Gephardt, anxious for a victory, aired television commercials
attacking the governor. The Missouri congressman also won the
endorsement of Sen. Tom Daschle, and rushed a commercial onto the
air trumpeting the news.
   Dukakis responded with a late radio advertisement responding to
the attacks and pointing out that Gephardt accepts political action
committee campaign funds.
   Gore also invested in television advertising in South Dakota to
redeem his earlier declaration that he needed to demonstrate
strength outside the South.
   Despite his initial statement that he needed a win this week to
stay in the race, Simon changed course and vowed to fight for the
``heart and soul'' of the Democratic Party until the convention.
His aides conceded no victories were likely in either Minnesota or
South Dakota.
   Jackson made little effort in South Dakota, but worked hard in
Minnesota in hopes of matching his double-digit showing in the Iowa
caucuses next door.
   Hart said in advance he would stay in the race no matter where
he finished.
</TEXT>
