<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireSickout 1stLd-Writethru a0599 02-23 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Sickout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters End Four-Day Sickout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with 35 firefighters cited with
contempt, picking up 7th graf pvs, `On Monday ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-day sickout by 110 Providence
firefighters ended today when the firefighters returned to work
after being threatened with contempt of court.
   But 35 of the firefighters were cited with contempt anyway by
Superior Court Judge Americo Campanella because they did not show
up in court Monday to explain why they were absent over the weekend.
   Campanella said there was no evidence that the firefighters had
not acted in concert to stay off the job in violation of a
back-to-work order issued Saturday by another judge. He said he
would decide on penalties at a later time.
   The city had asked for the contempt citations even though the
sickout was over in order to prevent something similar from
happening in the future, said city labor attorney Vincent Ragosta
Jr. State law prohibits public safety employees from striking.
   ``Everything's back to normal,'' Fire Chief Michael F. Moise
said today.
   Eighty-seven firefighters who reported for duty Friday evening
were kept on the job during the sickout over a contract dispute. No
major fires occurred in the city during the four-day period.
   On Monday, Campanella postponed a hearing after Ragosta and Leo
J. Miller, president of the Providence Firefighters Union,
indicated that relatively few members of the union had been
notified of the temporary restraining order issued by another
Superior Court judge at the city's request Saturday.
   Miller testified he was only able to reach about half the 50
firefighters scheduled to work Sunday.
   Ragosta said the city served notices of the restraining order on
129 firefighters. Another 36 were notified of Monday's contempt
hearing.
   The union represents 450 of the city's total uniformed force of
479.
   The dispute apparently concerns language in a contract ratified
by firefighters in December that the city has yet to sign.
   Miller asserts the city is trying to renege on a provision that
calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit.
Union members also complain that promises to replace worn-out or
damaged equipment like boots, helmets and firecoats have not been
fulfilled.
   All but one of the 51 firefighters scheduled to report for work
at 8 a.m. Saturday called in sick, Moise testified Monday. Sixty
others called in sick for the shift that was supposed to begin at 6
a.m. Sunday, Moise said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
