<DOCNO> AP880223-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1347EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham-Goldwater     02-23 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Goldwater,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goldwater Chairs Rhodes Campaign, Blasts Mecham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham is as stubborn as a mule
and can't govern the state, former Sen. Barry Goldwater said today
as he became honorary chairman man of John Rhodes' Republican
gubernatorial bid.
   Goldwater, who backed Mecham, a fellow Republican, during the
1986 campaign, said at a news conference today that the endorsement
was a mistake.
   ``He screwed up too much ... He turned out wrong,'' Goldwater
told reporters.
   ``You look back over all the governors that we've had in this
state,'' said the senator, who has been considered the patriarch of
the Arizona GOP. ``We''ve had some darn good ones and we've had
some mediocre ones, but it took us a long time to get a really bad
one.''
   Nonetheless, Goldwater said Mecham will be difficult to beat in
the May 17 recall election because he still has a strong core of
support despite the governor's indictment on criminal charges and
upcoming impeachment trial.
   Rhodes, a former 30-year congressman, will face Mecham and
Democrat Carolyn Warner in the recall vote.
   Goldwater contended Mecham was too wrapped up in defending
himself against the impeachment and criminal charges during recent
months to spend much time governing the state.
   Mecham gave up the acting governorship to Democrat Rose Mofford
when he was impeached on Feb. 5. His Senate trial is scheduled to
begin Monday on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan,
misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to
his auto dealership, and trying to thwart an investigation of an
alleged death threat by a state official.
   Even if he could solve his legal problems, however, Goldwater
said he does not believe Mecham can govern the state.
   ``He is a very obstinate man,'' Goldwater said. ``I used to
drive mules and he's a lot like a mule.''
   Goldwater said he doesn't see much difference between Rhodes and
Mrs. Warner, except that he believes Rhodes has more experience.
</TEXT>
