<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     02-23 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Kill 20 Tamils After Four Troops Killed in Ambush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian troops shot and killed 20 Tamil
civilians Tuesday after four soldiers died in a ambush by Tamil
rebels, Sri Lankan military officials said.
   The civilians were killed after an Indian army officer and three
soldiers died in the ambush in Kuthukudiuppu, a northeastern
village in the Mullaitivu district about 173 miles northeast of
Colombo, the officials said.
   The Sri Lankan officials could not be identified in accordance
with briefing rules.
   A spokeswoman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy, denied
any Tamil civilians were killed. She said the body of one Tamil
rebel was recovered and at least 10 more rebels were believed
killed.
   Authorities clamped an indefinite curfew on the district after
the violence broke out, the Sri Lankan officials said. They said
there were reports of heavy air activity by Indian troops.
   More than 45,000 Indian troops are stationed in Sri Lanka to
disarm Tamil militants opposed to a peace accord signed last July,
which grants some autonomy to minority Tamils. The Tamils
constitute 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   Tamils say they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese, who control the government and the army.
   The most powerful Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam, has been battling Indian troops since last October in
the northern and eastern provinces, where most of the Tamils live.
   Also on Tuesday, Sinhalese extremists stabbed a police constable
and a security officer guarding an injured Sinhalese militant
inside the Colombo General Hospital, a police spokesman said. He
said both victims were in serious condition.
   The attackers are believed to be members of the People's
Liberation Front, an ultra-nationalist organization of the majority
Sinhalese people that also opposes the peace accord. They escaped
with their injured comrade.
   On Monday, Liberation Front members raided a Sri Lankan army
camp northeast of Colombo, killing two soldiers. The attackers
escaped with two Chinese-made T-56 automatic rifles and 120 rounds
of ammunition.
   The group has vowed to kill anyone who supports the Indian-Sri
Lankan accord, claiming it grants too many concessions to the
Tamils. Sinhalese extremists already have killed more than 150
people since the accord was signed.
   Last year, attackers believed to be members of the Liberation
Front killed a popular Sri Lankan film stars and politician, Vijaya
Kumaranatunga, who supported the peace pact.
</TEXT>
