<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MinnesotaAt-A-Glance 1stLd-Writethru   02-23 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minnesota At-A-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0648,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of Democratic glance to include that dispute
with DNC has ended and to include material on second vote being
compiled on caucus night.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from Minnesota to attend the 1988 Democratic and
Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Tuesday, February 23
   Presidential filing deadline: None.
   Pledged delegates: 78
   Super delegates: 9
   Total delegates: 87
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, February 23
   Selection of delegates: Sunday, May 1 and Sunday, June 12
   Minnesota Democrats plan to pick national convention delegates
through a four-tier caucus-convention system, beginning with
precinct caucuses on Feb 23. The precinct caucuses will elect
delegates to the county conventions, which elect delegates to the
congressional district and state conventions.
   Under an agreement reached with the national party, the results
of the presidential preference vote at the precinct caucuses will
not be tabulated until March 8. This was to end a confrontation
over the state's insistence on holding its leadoff event on Feb.
23, two weeks earlier than allowed by national party rules.
   The two sides remained at odds until a few weeks ago over a plan
by Minnesota's secretary of state to compile a poll of the
presidential preferences of delegates elected to the county
conventions. The state Democratic Party has agreed it would lend no
help to conducting the poll on precinct caucus night. Those
figures, which technically have no binding effect, were to be
gathered by thousands of volunteers recruited by the secretary of
state.
   The state's 51 pledged national convention delegates from
congressional districts will be chosen and allocated at the
congressional district conventions scheduled for April 29-May 1.
   The rest of the state's 27 pledged delegates will be chosen and
allocated among presidential candidates at the state party
convention June 10-12.
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale, the Democratic
presidential nominee in 1984, automatically will be seated as a
delegate because of his position as a former party leader.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Tuesday, February 23
   Presidential filing deadline: None.
   Delegates: 31
   Delegates allocated: Friday, April 15 and Thursday, June 16
   Selection of delegates: Friday, April 15 and Thursday, June 16
   Minnesota Republicans begin the four-step process of picking
national convention delegates with precinct caucuses on Feb. 23.
   Participants in the caucuses elect delegates to county
conventions to be held between March 5-26. These conventions pick
delegates to the congressional district conventions to be held
between April 15-May 7; and to the state convention to be held June
16-18.
   The eight congressional district conventions each will choose
three delegates to the national convention. The state convention
will choose Minnesota's remaining seven delegates at-large.
   Minnesota GOP rules do not require that participants in the
state caucuses or conventions bind themselves to any presidential
candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
