<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NotSold     02-23 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Not Sold,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Not Sure About New Homes Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TCHULA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have a big selling job to do in
this improverished town if 30 families are to get new homes, the
mayor says.
   The families living in old shacks, rusting trailers and leaning
houses on Tchula's north side are to get new homes in about a year,
but Mayor David Cotten says it is going to be hard to convince some
that officials are trying to improve their quality of life and not
swindle them.
   ``They're scared and you can't blame them,'' Cotten said. ``The
most devastating thing to fight is ignorance.''
   Cotten and U.S. Rep. Mike Espy were on hand Monday for a
ground-breaking ceremony on the site of a burned-out house in the
middle of a four-block strip targeted for revitalization.
   ``We're going to be tearing these down,'' Cotten said of the
stretch of homes. ``But this a drop in the bucket. We want to
change the face of Tchula. We want everyone to be a homeowner.''
   When farmworkers are idle, unemployment in the central
Mississippi town of 2,000 can reach 85 percent, Cotten said. Poor
housing conditions are easily visible from the road.
   With a $695,832 community development block grant _ federal
money allocated by the state _ city and state officials are to
begin razing some homes in March and refurbishing others. In place
of the homes to be torn down, 30 new single-family dwellings will
be built.
   Residents who already own their land and homes will get the new
homes free, and renters will have a chance to buy homes through
low-interest programs, Cotten said.
   The city also will use the money to pay half the rent of
displaced homeowners during the renovations.
   Lillie May Brooks, 67, who lives alone in a home just a few feet
from where ground was broken for the first new house, was
suspicious of the plans.
   ``This house belongs to me and I don't want my house torn
down,'' said Brooks as she sat on her porch. ``This house suits me
all right.''
   Another resident, Jesse Riley, watched curiously from the road
while officials spoke.
   ``Can they really take someone's home?'' he asked a bystander.
``It's nice but I don't see why they should take people's
property.''
   The mayor said many will change their minds as they understand
the program.
   ``We have a lot of people here with no education,'' Cotten said.
``There are many who think you're going to steal their land.''
  
</TEXT>
