<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1411EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CabinetFlap     02-23 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cabinet Flap,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Secretary Says Colleague's Criticism Was Low Blow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary John Herrington told a House
subcommittee Tuesday he had been dealt a low blow by Interior
Secretary Donald P. Hodel through Hodel's interpretation of why
Herrington opposes one of Hodel's ideas.
   Herrington recommended that the panel not consider Hodel's
request for funds for what he called the ``frivolous'' idea of
removing the O'Shaughnessy Dam in Hetch Hetchy Valley in
California's Yosemite National Park and draining the reservoir
behind the dam.
   The dam provides three-quarters of San Francisco's water. The
city earns about $38 million a year selling water and electricity
from the reservoir.
   Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., chairman of the House Appropriations
interior subcommittee, said he found Hodel's idea ``strange,'' and
he had been ``shocked if not surprised'' that Hodel proposed it
last year.
   Yates read the opening paragraph of a news article about the
feud between the two Cabinet secretaries describing Hodel's belief
that Herrington was opposing removal of the dam because Herrington
was concerned about what it would do to his job prospects in
California.
   ``That's a low blow, isn't it?'' Yates said.
   ``It really is,'' Herrington replied.
   ``What about this job you're going to get?'' Yates asked.
   ``I don't know who fabricated that,'' Herrington said.
   Hodel has said the Hetch Hetchy Valley, filled by the reservoir
from 1913 to 1923, could relieve some of the visitor pressure on
Yosemite Valley, which attracts more than 2 million people a year.
He has said the project could not be begun for years, but is asking
for $600,000 in his budget for further studies.
   Yates asked Herrington, ``Your recommendation to this committee
would be not to consider an appropriation which would result in a
change in the status of Hetch Hetchy?''
   Herrington replied, ``That's my recommendation.''
   ``As energy secretary, I am concerned about destroying an
infrastructure that produces a substantial amount of electricity,''
he added.
   The generating capacity _ about 150 megawatts _ eventually will
have to be replaced, ``and I just don't think enough thought has
been given to the economic consequences,'' Herrington said.
   Herrington said his department estimated that removal of the dam
and restoration of the valley could cost $5 billion to $6 billion,
``a lot of money for a frivolous idea.''
</TEXT>
