<DOCNO> AP880223-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1403EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     02-23 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,350</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Tuesday by the Supreme Court.
   
   SECURITY CLEARANCES
   
   The court limited the job protection for government workers
fired for lacking security clearances.
   By a 5-3 vote, the justices agreed with the Reagan
administration that the Merit Systems Protection Board lacks
authority to decide whether the denial of security clearance is
justified.
   The case is Navy vs. Egan, 86-1552.
   
   CRIMINAL IDENTIFICATION
   
   The court ruled that a criminal suspect's rights are not
violated when a witness who is unable to identify the suspect in
court testifies about an earlier identification of the accused.
   The justices, voting 6-2, ordered the reinstatement of the
conviction of a California prison inmate in the beating of a prison
guard who suffered memory loss because of the attack.
   The case is U.S. vs. Owens, 86-877.
   
   PENSION FUNDS
   
   The court ruled that businesses may not be sued in federal court
for refusing to contribute to multi-employer union pension funds
after a collective bargaining agreement expires.
   In an 8-0 ruling, the court rejected Reagan administration
arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases could undermine the
solvency of the multi-employer pension plans.
   The case is Welfare Trust Fund vs. Advanced Lightweight
Concrete, 85-2079.
   
   GULF COAST
   
   The court, rejecting claims by private landowners, ruled that
the state of Mississippi owns thousands of acres of oil- and
gas-rich land near the state's Gulf Coast.
   By a 5-3 vote, the justices said states may claim title to land
beneath waters subject to the tie's influence _ and not only land
under navigable waters.
   The case is Phillips Petroleum vs. Mississippi, 86-870.
   
   MISSOURI RIVER BASIN
   
   The court, in a victory for three midwestern states, today
limited the secretary of the interior's authority to allocate water
stored in Missouri River Basin reservoirs.
   The justices ruled unanimously that the interior secretary
exceeded his authority when in 1982 he approved a contract
authorizing Energy Transportation Systems Inc. (ETSI) to take water
from Lake Oahe in South Dakota for a coal slurry pipeline project.
   The case is ETSI Pipeline Project vs. Missouri, 86-939 and
86-941.
</TEXT>
