<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     02-23 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrillas Announce Plans for New Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan insurgents announced plans
Tuesday to replace the Communist regime with an Islamic government,
which they said would promote peace and ensure the safe withdrawal
of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   The guerrilla alliance said the civil war would not end until
such a government was established to guide the way to a nation
called ``The Islamic State of Afghanistan.''
   President Najib responded that a new government should be formed
after the Soviets withdraw, and is a matter for ``Afghans alone.''
   Kabul radio quoted Najib as saying: ``No one can direct the
Afghans on this ... or give their views.''
   His comments appeared to reflect the government's position that
the issue of a coalition government should be settled within
Afghanistan, not by guerrilla leaders in neighboring Pakistan.
   Afghan guerrillas began fighting after a Communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet soldiers entered the country in December 1979. An
estimated 115,000 now are in the country helping fight the
insurgents.
   On Feb. 8, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev offered to begin
withdrawing troops May 15 if Pakistan and Afghanistan reach
agreement by March 15 in U.N.-sponsored negotiations that resume in
Geneva next week. He said the pullout could be accompalished in 10
months.
   Islamic Unity, an alliance of seven guerrilla groups, announced
its plans for a government in a statement telexed from the border
city of Peshawar, Pakistan, calling for a 28-member cabinet to
replace Najib's government.
   It said the government would consist of 14 ministers from the
guerrilla leadership, seven representatives of Afghan refugees and
``seven Moslems presently living in Kabul.''
   Insurgent leaders have said the Moslems in Kabul would include
non-Communists in the current administration who have not been
closely involved in the war.
   In a separate statement, alliance leader Yunis Khalis said: ``As
long as a single Communist remains in power in Kabul, the regime
will have to face the Mujahedeen resistance. Until we have
established an Islamic government, we will never lay down our
arms.''
   About 3.5 million Afghan refugees live in Pakistan. Most are in
border cities and camps that serve as bases and supply points for
the guerrillas known as mujahedeen, or holy warriors.
   The alliance statement said a ``supreme council'' would be the
government's highest body and oversee the cabinet. Its members
would be leaders of the seven-party alliance based in Pakistan, who
would provide ``joint leadership during the interim period'' after
moving to Kabul.
   ``This government is proposed to replace the present regime in
Kabul before the signing of the Geneva accords under the auspices
of the United Nations,'' and would ``represent all sections of the
Afghan nation,'' the announcement said.
   It said the chief cabinet minister also would be the head of
state, but it did not say who would hold the post or name proposed
cabinet members.
   Another organ of government would be a consultative council of
75 members _ two from each of the 28 provinces and 19 Moslem
religious scholars, intellectuals and technocrats, the statement
said. It said the council would make interim laws to apply until a
new constitution was written.
   Provincial councils would be in charge of regional affairs.
   The statement said an independent election commission would
supervise the election of a constituent assembly immediately after
the Soviet withdrawal.
   In ``The Islamic State of Afghanistan,'' the statement said,
``the Koran and Sunnah (teachings and practices of the Prophet
Mohammed) will be supreme.'' It said the country would be governed
by an elected head of state and legislative assembly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0144 </DOCNO>
