<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSBrothers-Doctor     02-23 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Brothers-Doctor,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Probe of Physician</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered an investigation
into why a doctor waited two months to disclose that one of three
hemophiliac brothers exposed to the AIDS virus had been diagnosed
with AIDS-related complex.
   U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich said in a court order
Monday that she has ``grave concerns'' with Dr. Jerry Barbosa's
statements to the press that he withheld the diagnosis out of
respect for the privacy of the family of Clifford and Louise Ray.
   In a medical report filed Feb. 12, Barbosa said Ricky, 11 and
the oldest of the brothers, was diagnosed with ARC, AIDS-related
complex.
   Barbosa, a physician at All Children's Hospital in St.
Petersburg, told the St. Petersburg Times that he knew of the
diagnosis in December but didn't report it out of concern for the
Rays' privacy, the Times said Tuesday.
   ``I left out a number of things on purpose,'' the Times quoted
the doctor as saying.
   In her order, Ms. Kovachevich asked a magistrate to find out
what the doctor told a Times reporter and who was aware of
Barbosa's ``intentional omissions from the medical reports and when
they were aware of the omissions.''
   In addition, she said she wanted to know whether attorneys told
the court any contradictory medical information and whether an
independent doctor should be appointed.
   Last August, the judge ordered the DeSoto County School Board to
reinstate the three Ray boys _ Ricky, Robert and Randy. The
brothers, all hemophiliacs, were barred from class after they
tested positive for antibodies associated with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   During a hearing last summer, doctors said the boys probably
were contaminated through plasma products used to clot their blood
and showed no symptoms of having the disease.
   The AIDS virus can remain dormant for years. ARC is found when
the virus causes a set of symptoms that usually are considered a
precursor to AIDS.
   Barbosa said in his Feb. 12 report that Ricky's condition
appeared to be stable. The boy has been treated with AZT, an
anti-AIDS drug.
   The Ray boys' medical records are supposed to be on public file
as a condition of the August injunction that returned them to
school. The family, however, fled DeSoto County a week after
classes began because of a parental boycott, bomb threats that
emptied the school and a deliberate blaze that destoyed their home.
   They now live in Sarasota, where the boys enrolled in school
without objection from school officials, although some parents
objected.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread
through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers,
infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their
offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
