<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Heckler     02-23 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Heckler,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador to Ireland Margaret
Heckler prayed at the churchyard where her grandparents are buried
and visited the cottage where her father lived before he emigrated
to the United States.
   The visit by Mrs. Heckler was supposed to be a secret, but
people in Ballysteen, a village of 200 people near the River
Shannon 14 miles west of Limerick, found out in time to spruce up
the ancestral cottage.
   In the tiny two-bedroom house, Mrs. Heckler, who has been
ambassador to Ireland for two years, found a loaf of home-baked
bread, scones and tea laid out on the table by the villagers.
   Limerick County Council chairman Paddy Sheehy, who happens to be
Mrs. Heckler's cousin, greeted her when she arrived, and the local
folk music band regaled her with songs of welcome.
   ``It's a moment I've long waited to cherish,'' said Mrs.
Heckler, 56. ``It's fascinating to see the country roads where my
family once walked and to see the hills where they probably once
roamed.''
   Mrs. Heckler, a former congresswoman from Massachusetts, served
as the federal secretary for health and human services before being
posted to Dublin in January 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American rock star Tina Turner
arrived here Tuesday for two performances this week, accompanied by
an eight-piece band and 10 tons of equipment.
   Turner, with four Grammy and two American Music awards to her
credit, said that she plans to concentrate on acting, which means
she can't keep traveling at the same time.
   However, the 48-year-old singer said, she will try to satisfy
her rock fans by continuing to do recordings and television
specials.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motherhood makes Amy Irving pine to play the
title role in ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' the actress says in the
March issue of Vogue.
   ``Since I had (3-year-old) Max, my work has changed. There's
less naivete to it,'' said Irving, 34. ``I'm not being sent the
sweet young thing parts any more.''
   Now, she wants to conquer a roster of illustrious roles. ``I
want to play the shrew, all the Shaw women. I want to do a St.
Joan,'' she said.
   When Ms. Irving is working, her husband, director Steven
Spielberg, stays home with their son. When Spielberg is on
location, the family goes with him.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faye Dunaway, divorced from British photographer
Terry O'Neill and back in New York after living for several years
in England, says she's found new satisfaction in living alone.
   ``I am happier now than I've ever been, more centered on who I
am and what I want to do, and much less dependent on whoever's
around and whatever their opinions are,'' the actress says in an
interview in the March issue of Vogue magazine.
   Her return to America came with the movie ``Barfly,'' a film
about the life of writer Charles Bukowski and shot in seedy
locations around Los Angeles.
   Speaking of her role, played opposite Mickey Rourke, she says,
``I found myself at a place in my life, and there was Wanda at the
same place.
   ``That's what I want _ to connect in my work with who I actually
am. God knows I've had a lot of artifice,'' she says. ``I don't
want to play any larger-than-life monsters, grotesques. I don't
want to play any more queens.''
   Miss Dunaway, who lives with her 7-year-old son, said she's not
ready to make any long-term commitments in her private life.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Princess Anne met with
President Yoweri Museveni and visited hospitals and health clinics
Tuesday, hours after arriving on the start of a 12-day swing
through East Africa.
   The 37-year-old princess, Queen Elizabeth II's only daughter, is
visiting hospitals and clinics in Uganda, Mozambique and Somalia
established by the Save the Children Fund.
   The princess, who has been president of the international
charity since 1971, is the first member of Britain's royal family
to visit this former British colony in 23 years.
