<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-FBIInfiltration 2ndLd-Writethru a0572 02-23 0960</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI Infiltration, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0572,940</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 12 grafs new; pickup 7th graf pvs, Some have; deletes
last 5 grafs pvs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top FBI official admitted today that some
agents came ``very close'' to conducting a political investigation
of anti-Reagan activists, but denied they intended to do so or
received any instructions from the Reagan administration.
   Oliver B. Revell, executive assistant director, told a Senate
panel there were legitimate reasons to investigate the Committee In
Solidarity with the People of El Salvador, including possible links
with Salvadoran-based terrorists, and discussions by CISPES members
of committing violent acts.
   The investigation was closed down without any charges being
filed, and the bureau has now begun an investigation of its agents'
conduct. CISPES has said it was investigated because it opposes
President Reagan's Central America policies.
   Several members of the Senate Intelligence Committee told Revell
they remained skeptical of the FBI information that triggered the
investigation in March 1983 and fueled it until it closed in June
1985.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., the former district attorney of
Philadelphia, said he has ``grave questions'' about Revell's
justifications, adding ``You have to proceed on the basis of
tangible hard facts and evidence'' _ which he indicated were
lacking in this case.
   Revell, noting this was a terrorism investigation, testily
replied that if the FBI always waited ``until there was tangible
evidence, you would have been picking up the pieces of the bombs.''
   Documents previously released in the probe show that FBI agents
and informants sent to spy on CISPES collected so much information
on peaceful protest activities that bureau headquarters was worried
that the investigation had gone too far.
   The documents, released under the Freedom of Information Act,
have shown that while the investigation was targeted at CISPES, the
files eventually included information on hundreds of other
individuals and groups, ranging from Roman Catholic nuns to union
leaders who opposed Reagan policies.
   Revell said that more than a year after the investigation began,
top FBI officials warned field offices about investigating
legitimate political activity, beause they ``sensed'' the conduct
of some agents was ``very close to the line.''
   ``We may have seen some wavering over that line,'' he said, but
maintained that the investigation was legitimate under the FBI's
foreign intelligence and counter-intelligence guidelines.
   He flatly denied that the administration ever tried to influence
the investigation, commenting, ``There's been absolutely no contact
by anyone in the administration concerning tasking, opening or
closing of the investigation.''
   In defending the probe, Revell testified that in addition to
possible violence, CISPES was involved in circulating forged U.S.
documents and had strong ties to the U.S. communist party.
   ``Some have insinuated that this investigation was politically
motivated as many individuals associated with CISPES were opposed
to Reagan administration policies in Central America,'' Revell
said. ``Nothing could be further from the truth.
   ``We did find indications that some CISPES members were at least
discussing and planning violence. Our investigtions uncovered one
CISPES member who was tasked to determine response times of
emergency services in a major American city; another CISPES member
stated he had developed a system to shut down a public utility in a
major midwestern city; as well as plans to violently disrupt the
1984 Republican convention.''
   The bureau initiated the investigation under foreign
intelligence and counter-intelligence guidelines, designed to
protect the United States against crimes such as espionage and
terrorism, in which foreign powers or groups are involved.
   These guidelines allow the FBI to focus more on politically
oriented groups and their missions than on specific crimes that are
planned or carried out. Because of this wider latitude, some
lawmakers and the American Civil Liberties Union warn that it is
easy to cross the line and investigate free speech and peaceful
assembly.
   FBI Director William S. Sessions said the investigation in this
case ``was predicated on information received from several sources
that certain leaders and key members of CISPES were involved in
covertly furnishing funds and materials to a foreign terrorist
organization.'' The group was identified as the FMLN, the group
fighting a war against the U.S.-backed government of El Salvador.
   Jerry Berman, chief legislative counsel for the American Civil
Liberties Union, said the investigation should have started under
the most strict guidelines, those for general criminal
investigations.
   These investigations can only begin ``when facts or
circumstances reasonably indicate that a federal crime has been, is
being, or will be committed.'' If the crime has already been
committed, the probe focuses on who committed the act and on
securing evidence.
   The FBI is given greater leeway for a domestic ``intelligence''
investigation, which can focus on groups in the United States
trying ``to further political or social goals through activities
that involve criminal violence.''
   The bureau did not place the CISPES investigation under either
the intelligence or general guidelines, but under the foreign
intelligence and counter-intelligence rules that involve
participation by foreign entities.
   These rules remain largely classified, but officials familiar
with them say they provide the widest latitude among the different
sets of guidelines.
   On July 26, 1984 _ some 16 months after the investigation began
_ FBI headquarters sent 32 field offices a message that suggested
some of them were going beyond the guidelines.
   ``Some offices have reported information recently regarding
political statements and political lobbying by CISPES or CISPES
affiliates,'' it said. ``Supervisors in recipient offices must
carefully monitor this and related investigations and asset
operations within your respective divisions to ensure appropriate
direction, targeting and reporting.''
   But messages from the field showed that bureaus were still
confused.
   In August 1984 the Denver office told headquarters, ``the field
is still not sure of how much seemingly legitimate political
activity can be monitored.''
</TEXT>
