<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Governors 3rdLd-Writethru a0667 02-23 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Governors, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0667,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Support U.S.-Canada Free Trade Pact, With Some
Reservations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 14th graf, `Forty-three,' to update with 44 governors
signing letter sted 43; deletes old 18th or penultimate graf,
`Delaware Gov.' as redundant; SUBS last graf to delete word
`proposed'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Governors' Association voted
after a spirited debate today to support the U.S.-Canada free trade
agreement despite fears that some state industries could suffer.
   The vote was 30 to 5, with the governors of Kentucky, Michigan,
North Dakota, West Virginia and Wyoming in the minority.
   The governors also adopted policies urging the federal
government to take action on child care, including a ``modest''
commitment of funds to help poor working families.
   The fight against the resolution supporting the free trade
agreement was led by Wyoming Gov. Michael Sullivan, who charged
that American energy producers, fisheries, precious metal miners
and others ``are left at a disadvantage.''
   ``We can express our support for free trade without endorsing
the agreement,'' Sullivan said. He said it was premature and
governors should wait until their next meeting in August to take a
stand.
   But Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson replied, ``I don't like the
beer, you don't like the energy, Governor Sullivan, but how are we
going to have some input'' in the Senate ratification debate.
   An aide to the Wisconsin governor explained that some American
brewers have licensees in Canada, but Wisconsin's Heilemann's does
not and could be left at a disadvantage.
   But Thompson said it would be ``a terrible mistake'' to spurn
the agreement.
   Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson said that if the governors did
not put aside ``partisanship and parochial fears for the greater
good of the country'' on this issue, ``then I have to say my voice
would be a little softer'' when he asked Congress to lay aside
politics in dealing with the deficit or welfare reform.
   The governors, who were concluding their three-day winter
meeting, did add an amendment to their resolution offered by Gov.
Garrey E. Carruthers of New Mexico which said: ``The governors have
significant concerns about issues created or not fully resolved by
the agreement and ask to be consulted as the implementing
legislation or other measures are developed to ameliorate these
problems. The administration should enter into additional
negotiations to address inequities regarding subsidies.''
   The governors adopted a policy two years ago supporting the
U.S.-Canada free trade negotiations. The new policy says the
governors' support ``is contingent upon Canada and the U.S. doing
nothing'' before the final treaty ratification to jeopardize or
undermine ``the spirit and benefits of the free trade agreement.''
   The governor of Guam, Joseph Ada, expressed concern that U.S.
territories were left out of the initial agreement.
   The governors of Hawaii and Maine abstained from the vote, which
did not include all the state leaders, because of their concerns
about the agreement, which was signed by President Reagan and
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney on Jan. 2. The agreement,
which must be ratified by Congress and the Canadian Parliament,
would eliminate all tariffs between the two countries by 1999. It
also would set up a new tribunal to settle future trade disputes.
   Forty-four governors signed a letter urging the Senate to pass a
welfare reform bill this year and the governors also asked Congress
to extend through 1992 their right to issue mortgage revenue bonds.
A provision in the 1986 tax reform law forbids their issuing new
mortgage revenue bonds after 1988.
   On Monday the governors went to the White House to hear
President Reagan make a pitch for a no-frills, $1.1 billion
Republican alternative to the $4.3 billion House-passed version of
welfare reform. He also cautioned them to ``tread carefully'' on
the issue of child care.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, a Democratic presidential
hopeful, called Reagan's speech a disappointment. He said the
president should have joined the governors' call for passage of New
York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's welfare reform bill in the
Senate.
   Reagan instead said he still strongly supports the less costly
Republican alternative that the House rejected two months ago,
which would give states more flexibility in running their welfare
programs. Unlike the Democratic bill passed by the House, it would
not provide any big increase in Aid to Families with Dependent
Children.
   The governors' policy on child care calls for the public and
private sectors to work in concert on the problem, and says that
despite the deficit, ``the governors believe that the federal
government should begin to take action to improve child care.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
