<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Waldheim     02-23 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anniversary To Mark Annexation By Nazis Surrounded By Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Austria's three main political
parties called Tuesday for a reconsideration of plans to have
President Kurt Waldheim address a ceremony on the 50th anniversary
of Austria's annexation by Nazi Germany.
   The debate over the solemn ceremony March 11 is the latest round
in the international controversy surrounding Waldheim and his role
in the German army under Adolf Hitler.
   Several high-ranking politicians have suggested the event should
be called off, saying a Waldheim speech is not the way for the
country to reflect on the atrocities of the Nazi era.
   None of the officials Tuesday called for a cancellation and none
said that Waldheim should be barred from speaking. Still, it was
clear that the politicians were not satisfied with the structure of
the ceremony as it stands.
   Waldheim has consistently denied that he committed wrongdoing as
a first lieutenant serving in the German army in the Balkans in
World War II.
   An international historians' commission report released earlier
this month left open the question of whether Waldheim committed
Nazi wartime atrocities.
   However, the report said Waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to
Nazi atrocities in the Balkans, knew they were going on and made no
attempt ot stop them. It also said Waldheim concealed his wartime
past.
   The commission, which started work in 1987, was formed after the
U.S. government placed Waldheim on a ``watch list'' of undesirable
aliens, effectively barring him from the United States.
   At a joint news conference Tuesday, the parliamentary leaders of
the conservative People's Party, the Socialists and the
rightist-oriented Freedom Party said organizers should rethink
plans for the cermony which include a Waldheim speech.
   Parliament President Leopold Gratz, a Socialist, said it is not
a question of canceling the ceremony. But he emphasized a meeting
of the organizers is needed ``because high officials have gone
public with their questioning of the sense of the planned official
ceremony.''
   Several thousand protesters are expected to gather outside the
Hofburg Palace, where the ceremony is set to take place, to
demonstrate against Waldheim and demand his resignation.
   Protesters, many of them opposed to Waldheim, also have promised
to flood Heroes' Square next to the Hofburg on March 12, the day
after the scheduled Waldheim speech.
   Gerulf Stix, parliamentary leader of the Freedom Party, also
called Tuesday for a rethinking of the commemoration plans, while
the tiny Greens party has called for its scrapping altogether.
   Several other political leaders also have expressed their
reservations.
   ``I have misgivings about this event,'' Socialist Party chief
Fred Sinowatz told reporters at a news conference Monday.
   The former chancellor called, instead, for reflection of ``what
happened on March 11, 1938 and what must be done so that such a
thing never happens again.''
   German troops marched into Austria nearly 50 years ago,
officially linking this Alpine nation with Hitler's Third Reich.
   Austrians are marking the annexation, called the Anschluss in
German, as a time of reflection on the troubled past.
   Austrian television and radio, along with many of the country's
newspapers, have started programs leading up to the March 11
commemoration date. There also are films and exhibitions.
</TEXT>
