<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nielsens     02-23 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC's Olympics Coverage Claims Four Top Spots in Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC took the gold for its coverage of the
Winter Olympics, winning the week, moving into the lead in the
February sweeps and taking over second place for the season, ahead
of CBS.
   Olympics events took six places among the top 20 shows, forcing
NBC into second place for the week ending Feb. 21 and for the
sweeps, which help determine the rates local stations charge
advertisers.
   The opening chapter of NBC's much-ballyhooed miniseries ``Noble
House'' ended up 16th. However, it did beat out ABC's Olympics
coverage for Sunday night as well as the CBS movie ``Bring Me the
Head of Dobie Gillis.''
   Coverage of the Olympics in Calgary, Canada, gave ABC its first
weekly victory since Super Bowl Week, ending Jan. 31. Its only
other first place for the season was during the World Series, the
week ending Oct. 25.
   ABC's coverage of the Tuesday night events were first in the
ratings. NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' was second and ABC's Saturday
coverage was third. Wednesday's coverage was seventh and Thursday's
was ninth.
   ABC won the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings for the week with an
average of 19.4. NBC was second with 15.0 and CBS was third with
12.8. The rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with television.
   The new season-to-date ratings: NBC 16.3, ABC 13.8, CBS 13.6.
   The Top 10 shows were: ABC's Tuesday Olympics, NBC's ``The Cosby
Show,'' ABC's Saturday Olympics, NBC's ``A Different World,'' CBS'
``60 Minutes,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' ABC's Wednesday Olympics, CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote,'' ABC's Thursday Olympics, and NBC's ``Family
Ties'' and ``ALF,'' tied for 10th.
   ABC's evening news show, benefiting from the Olympics
viewership, remained ahead of its rivals with a rating of 12.0. CBS
was second with 11.1 and NBC third with 10.0.
   The lowest-rated network show was CBS' ``48 Hours: Campaign
Trail.'' Here are the five bottom shows in descending order: CBS'
``Houston Knights,'' CBS' ``Ringling Brothers Circus: 20th
Anniversary of the Clown College,'' CBS' ``West 57th Street,''
NBC's ``Decision: 88, New Hampshire,'' and CBS' ``48 Hours:
Campaign Trail.''
   Meanwhile, the Fox Broadcasting Co. was also enjoying good
ratings for its Sunday night shows. ``21 Jump Street'' had its
highest rating to date with 6.6, which would place it ahead of
three network shows. ``Married With Children'' got a 5.7 rating,
its highest ever. That would place it higher than the two bottom
network shows. ``Werewolf'' got its highest rating ever in its 8
o'clock time period, 5.1, which would give it a tie with the
network's' lowest-rated show.
</TEXT>
