<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Burial Bjt   02-23 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Burial, Bjt,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Case Of Soldiers Burying Palestinians Alive Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHAN YUNIS, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adel Ali Massoud said
Tuesday that when soldiers took him to the Mediterranean beach near
his home here, beat him and buried him in the sand, they told him:
``Don't think you are going to return alive.''
   The 18-year-old youth and a Gaza lawyer want to take the army to
court over the brutality Massoud says was inflicted on him. It is
the second time this month Palestinians have reported being buried
alive by soldiers.
   The Israeli army says it is investigating both incidents.
   ``They took me to the beach'' about a mile and a half away,
Massoud said. ``They attached me to a jeep and dragged me behind it
through the sand and the water.''
   Massoud said he saw another youth on the beach, whom he
identified as Saleh Hamad, receiving the same treatement.
   ``They put sand in my mouth and covered me with sand, then they
covered me up, using their hands,'' he said.
   The youth said he did not know how deeply he was buried, but the
weight on his chest was very heavy and he lost consciousness.
   ``The next thing I remember, I was in the hospital,'' he said.
   Lying under a blanket on a mattress spread on the floor of his
spare home in the Khan Yunis refugee camp, the young Palestinian
recounted how Israeli soldiers burst into his home at 4 a.m. Feb.
14.
   ``They used ladders to climb over the wall'' into the tiny
courtyard in front of the house, Massoud said.
   As family members and neighbors began to gather in the small
room, he said: ``I was sleeping, here, like this. I suddenly saw
soldiers. They shined a strong light in my face. They started to
beat me with sticks.''
   The youth said the soldiers put a chain around his neck to raise
him to his feet, beat him to the ground and used the chain to raise
him again.
   Aisha Ali Massoud, 40, mother of Adel and nine other children,
said the soldiers also entered her room. She said about 15 entered
the one-story house.
   Ms. Massoud said soldiers also grabbed her 10-year-old son Sami,
and one of them stuck a gun in Sami's mouth.
   ``I grabbed for him, and they hit me here,'' she said, pointing
to a fading mark on her forehead.
   She said neighbors told her later the soldiers had raided many
houses in the neighborhood, a maze of winding, narrow alleys. They
were looking for teen-aged boys, she said, but her son Adel was the
only one in the area.
   After the soldiers took Adel to the beach, buried him in the
sand and left, families living near the beach rescued him.
   ``Of course I'm angry,'' he said. ``This is no way to treat
people. They told me on the road, on the way to the beach, `Don't
think you are going to return alive.'''
   On Feb. 5, soldiers grabbed four Palestinian youths and covered
them up with a bulldozer in the village of Kfar Salem, near Nablus,
40 miles north of Jerusalem. The army detained two soldiers in the
case, but the investigation is continuing.
   Gaza attorney Mohammed Abu Shaaban wants to press the case in
the Supreme Court in Jerusalem.
   ``I think we will have some problems because he and his family
will be afraid,'' Shaaban said. ``The military police have
threatened people in other cases.''
   The medical report at Khan Yunis' Nasser hospital indicate the
youth was treated in the emergency room but suffered only bruises.
X-rays showed no broken bones. A doctor, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Massoud's family refused to allow him to be
admitted for fear the army would come for him.
   ``We aren't going to court for justice,'' Shaaban said. ``We are
going to court because we know all the newspapers will talk about
it. That's useful. But we know we'll never get justice.''
   The boy's father, Ali Mohammed Massoud, said he too wants to
push the case in the courts, but is afraid.
   ``If we go to court, the next day they will come and beat him,''
the father said. ``Maybe, after it is in the press, I'll discuss it
with the lawyer. ``If it makes trouble for us, we won't do it.''
</TEXT>
