<1ST_LINE>r i AM-KoreanPlane     02-23 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korean Plane,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Command Charges North Korea With Plane Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Command rejected North Korean
charges Tuesday it is building up forces for a nuclear attack and
it demanded the communist nation admit it ordered the bombing of a
civilian airliner.
   The United Nations Command dismissed a North Korean demand that
the United States and South Korea call off joint military
exercises, called ``Team Spirit.'' It accused North Korea of
fomenting tension on the divided Korean peninsula and trying to
sabotage the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul.
   The United States maintains 40,000 troops in South Korea and
heads the command, which represents the 16 nations that fought
under U.N. auspices against North Korea and China during the Korean
War.
   ``Don't miscalculate ... the will of the world to react, with
appropriate action, to continued barbaric acts of terrorism which
result in the deaths of innocent people,'' said U.S. Rear Adm.
William T. Pendley, the chief U.N. Command delegate.
   Pendley demanded North Korea punish those involved in the
bombing last November of a South Korean airliner and apologize to
the world. All 115 people aboard the Korean Air jet were killed
when it blew up Nov. 29 over the Andaman Sea near Burma.
   Chief North Korean delegate Maj. Gen. Li Tae Ho said Pyongyang
had nothing to do with the attack and charged South Korea with
destroying the plane in a scheme to retain power and discredit the
north.
   The charges were made at the first meeting of the Military
Armistice Commission since the loss of the plane. The commission
polices the ceasefire that ended the Korean War between north and
south in 1953.
   North Korea called the meeting to demand the United States and
South Korea abandon the annual ``Team Spirit'' exercises that start
next month, charging the exercises were preparations for an
American nuclear attack.
   ``You have nuclear war plans worked out,'' Li charged.
   Pendley dismissed the North Korean accusations and said the
exercises were lawful military activities intended to guarantee the
safety of South Korea.
   The U.N. Command's delegation presented a videotape of a
televised confession last month in Seoul by Kim Hyon Hui, a woman
who claimed she was a North Korean agent and destroyed the plane to
disrupt the Olympic Games that start in Seoul in September.
   Ms. Kim, who rode an early leg of the KAL flight, took poison
along with a male companion when they were detained in Bahrain. The
man died but she recovered.
   Pendley said the confession was damning evidence that the north
could not refute. ``You thought you had committed the perfect
crime, but, like all criminals, you made a mistake,'' he said.
   North Korea has been demanding to be a co-host of the Olympic
Games. The International Olympic Committee and South Korea have
rejected the demand.
</TEXT>
