<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CampusTakeover     02-23 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campus Takeover,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hampshire College Students Occupy Dormitory Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While hundreds of University of
Massachusetts students discussed racism in class, a small group at
neighboring Hampshire College on Tuesday occupied a dormitory
office to protest racial attitudes at that elite school.
   The takeover came nearly a week after the end of a six-day
occupation of a University of Massachusetts building by more than
100 people protesting racial violence on campus.
   That occupation ended when protesters reached an agreement with
the chancellor, Joseph Duffey, which included increased hiring of
minority faculty and staff.
   Penny Premdas, a spokeswoman for the Hampshire group, Students
of Underrepresented Cultures, said up to 40 students occupied the
office of the Dakin House dormitory, a traditional meeting place
for minority students, at 8 a.m. to work on a list of demands,
including that an office in the dormitory be converted into a Third
World cultural center.
   ``We have been to the administration several times over the past
three years with our demands and concerns and nothing has been
done,'' said Ms. Premdas, who is black. ``It's been all lip
service. It seemed this was the only way to get something done.''
   Unlike the University of Massachusetts, which has been the scene
of attacks on blacks, ``We have never had any blatant physical
harassment here,'' Ms. Premdas said. ``It has all been emotional
and mental and institutional.''
   A Dakin House resident, Marston Chickering, said the occupation
was ``particularly hard at this school, which has an image of being
politically correct and aware.''
   ``No one's ever satisfied at this school,'' said Karen Bagninm,
a freshman from New York City who lives across the yard from Dakin.
``Everyone's always feeling belittled or discriminated against. If
it's not minorities, it's females ... this is what they (the
protesters) feel they have to do to get attention.''
   About 100 of the 1,100 undergraduate students at the private
college are minorities, said Petez Gluckler, a spokesman for the
administration.
   A consultant hired by the school last year to investigate racial
attitudes on campus is preparing his final report, Gluckler said.
   The school planned to provide the protesters with food and
sleeping bags, said Hampshire spokeswoman Lee Wicks.
   Hundreds of students at the 25,000-student University of
Massachusetts campus across town from Hampshire attended class
discussions on racism on Tuesday.
   At least 35 classes were devoted to the topic in response to a
call by the Graduate Student Association to boycott all classes
Tuesday and Wednesday in lieu of forums on racism, said school
spokeswoman Jeanne Hopkins.
   Duffey had warned in a statement against students boycotting
classes and had suggested that racism discussions be held in
classes.
</TEXT>
