<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BallProfile     02-23 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ball Profile,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Secretary Nominee Said To Have Savvy in Congressionl Budget
Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Navy Secretary Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William L. Ball III, President Reagan's new
choice to pilot the Navy through the shoals of Pentagon budget
cutbacks, was described Tuesday as savvy coalition builder with
years of experience at the White House and Capitol Hill.
   ``All of us who know him here at the White House know that the
Navy is getting a strong advocate and a strong fighter,'' White
House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in announcing Reagan's
decision to nominate Ball.
   Ball, a stocky, 39-year-old who has served as the president's
chief lobbyist on Capitol Hill since 1986, was tapped Tuesday to
succeed James H. Webb as secretary of the Navy.
   Webb abruptly handed in his resignation Monday after accusing
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci of scuttling administration
dreams for a 600-ship Navy.
   Fitzwater, a long-time friend of Ball's, described him as ``the
kind of guy who knows how to build coalitions and work with people.
... He has a great love and respect for the Navy and he knows how
to get things done.''
   The spokesman said Webb's resignation had caught the
administration by surprise, but that Ball was easily recognized as
a top candidate for the job due to naval, congressional and White
House experience.
   ``He's a known quantity. Everyone instantly recognized him as
the perfect choice,'' Fitzwater said.
   The spokesman said Ball earned Carlucci's respect in the wake of
the Iran-Contra affair, when the legislative liaison helped the
former national security adviser forge a new relationship with
Congress and its intelligence oversight committees. Ball also
worked with Carlucci on the formulation of the latest budget
policies, Fitzwater said.
   ``He earned Frank's respect. ... He knows intimately the
problems Frank is facing,'' the spokesman observed.
   Fitzwater said the South Carolina native has a ``wry sense of
humor'' and ``is personable and savvy'' when it comes to working
with Congress and the military.
   ``He should have no problems,'' the spokesman predicted.
   Prior to working in the White House, Ball was assistant
secretary of state for legislative and intergovernmental affairs.
   In 1981, he served as the chief clerk of the Senate Armed
Services Committee. Earlier, he had worked as the administrative
assistant for former Sens. Herman Talmadge, D-Ga., and John Tower,
R-Texas.
   Ball was commissioned as a regular officer in the Navy in 1969
and served three years aboard the guided missile destroyer USS
Sellers, followed by three years of service in the Department of
the Navy.
   He graduated from the Georgia Institute of Technology with a
degree in industrial management.
   Ball is married to the former Patricia Adkins of Memphis, Tenn.,
and has two daughters.
</TEXT>
