<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Wapner     02-23 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Wapner,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers Award $2,500 Settlement To People's Court Loser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``People's Court'' Judge Joseph Wapner's word
is the law on television, but not necessarily off camera, where the
popular show's lawyers have agreed to pay a $2,500 settlement to a
man the judge ruled against.
   The show's producers said the $2,500, awarded to 72-year-old
former Mr. America Rex Ravelle, marked the first time the judge has
settled out of court with someone who has sued over a TV decision.
   ``The judge's decision was so bad it was unbelievable,'' said
Ravelle, who had sought $2,000 in back rent and return of a bedroom
set he said was taken by a woman he evicted from his house.
   Ravelle said in a recent interview that he was set up to look
like a bully and a buffoon and then Wapner ruled against him for
dramatic effect when the show was taped Dec. 4, 1985.
   ``I was instructed to project my voice and assert myself, while
the defendant was submissive and scarcely audible,'' Ravelle said.
``This obvious ploy clearly established me as the big, macho
villain.''
   Wapner said he couldn't recall Ravelle's case and was unaware of
the settlement, but added he tries to be fair to all people on the
show.
   ``I try to be fair, and our track record is there,'' said
Wapner, former presiding judge of Los Angeles Superior Court. ``I
try to make sure that each side gets a fair shot.''
   Ravelle, who had sued the show for $1 million, agreed to drop
the suit in exchange for the settlement last week.
   Of approximately 2,000 small claims cases Wapner has heard
during the show's seven years, Ravelle is one of only three
disgruntled litigants to sue, said James B. Pollock, vice president
for Ralph Edwards Productions, the show's producer. He is the only
one to win a settlement, Pollock added.
   Participants on ``People's Court'' are selected from among those
who file for damages in small claims courts in 36 Southern
California localities. Since files are open to the public,
researchers can read cases and get in touch with those filing
claims. Those selected after phone interviews appear for personal
interviews and are selected by producers for the program.
   All participants volunteer to take part and sign papers making
it legally binding under California's law on arbitration. Wapner
has a private arbitration practice.
</TEXT>
