<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2133EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Inmates-Insemination     02-23 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inmates-Insemination,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Officials Say Inmates Cannot Inseminate Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive staff of the U.S. Bureau
of Prisons has decided federal inmates should not have the
privilege of begetting children through artificial insemination.
   If such a police were allowed, the government believes ``that
numerous other inmates from regular prison institutions of all
security levels would desire to beget children,'' according to the
government's response filed Monday in the case of a federal
prisoner.
   The response was filed Monday in the case of Steven James
Goodwin, 31, a prisoner in the Medical Center for Federal Prisoners
in Springfield.
   Goodwin had filed a lawsuit against the government and received
a favorable ruling from U.S. Magistrate James England. The judge
recommended in November that U.S. District Judge William R.
Collison rule that the bureau's lack of a policy on artificial
insemination isn't a constitutionally sufficient reason to prohibit
the procedure.
   Goodwin had asked in his lawsuit that doctors be allowed to
collect his sperm at the prison so it could be frozen and sent to
his wife's doctor in St. Louis.
   The executive staff of the bureau met earlier this month to
consider a policy on the issue, Assistant U.S. Attorney David C.
Jones said in the government's response.
   If the procedure were allowed in one case, all 48 federal
prisons would be affected. The prisons either would have to develop
collecting, handling and storage procedures for semen, or private
medical personnel would have to be allowed into the institutions,
Jones said.
   As result, the response said, the bureau believes the situation
could be extremely costly or create substantial security risks.
   The government disagreed with England's ruling that begetting or
bearing children is a fundamental right that survives
incarceration. Actually, begetting or bearing children is one of
the many rights that is restricted by imprisonment, Jones said.
   Goodwin is serving a 14-year sentence on a charge of conspiracy
to distribute cocaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
