<DOCNO> AP880223-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireSickout     02-23 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Sickout,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Holds 33 Firefighters In Contempt For Sickout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-seven firefighters who had been
on duty for more than three days were sent home Tuesday as
colleagues ended a sickout and returned to work under threats of
contempt of court citations.
   More than 100 firefighters called in sick Saturday, Sunday and
Monday, despite a judge's order Saturday that they report for duty.
   Thirty-three firefighters who defied the order were held in
contempt Tuesday by another judge, Americo Campanella of Superior
Court, for failure to show up in court to explain why they were
absent.
   The firefighters had been served notice by the city to appear in
court on Monday.
   Campanella's ruling stunned attorneys for Local 799 of the
International Association of Firefighters. They told Campanella it
was their impression he only wanted union president Leo J. Miller
and secretary-treasurer Richard Kless in court.
   Attorney Harry J. Hoopis said he thought his representation of
the union membership as a whole, as well as Miller's, was good
enough to constitute the presence of the absent members.
   Campanella, who continued the hearing on the status of the rest
of the firefighters who called in sick, said he would decide later
what penalty to assess against the 33.
   Mayor Joseph R. Paolino urged that no jail time be imposed.
However, the city continued to press for contempt citations, even
though the sickout ended with the start of Tuesday's day shift, to
prevent something similar from happening in the future, according
to city labor attorney Vincent Ragosta Jr.
   The sickout, which the city is trying to prove is an illegal job
action by municipal employees, cost the city about $84,000 in
overtime and related expenses, estimated Fire Chief Michael F.
Moise.
   It also meant a long haul for firefighters who went to work at 6
p.m. Friday. Moise kept them on duty through the sickout, but they
went home Tuesday.
   The sickout apparently stemmed from a dispute over language in a
contract ratified by firefighters in December but yet to be
approved by the City Council.
   Miller contends the city is trying to renege on a provision that
calls for an officer to be placed in charge of each rescue unit.
Union members also say the city is not replacing worn-out or
damaged equipment as promised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
