<DOCNO> AP880223-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1555EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FBIInfiltration Bjt   02-23 0913</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI Infiltration, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Webster Kept in Dark Over Probe of Dissidents, Congress Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Then-FBI Director William Webster was kept
unaware of problems with a probe of anti-Reagan activists, even
when it became clear that some agents were investigating legitimate
protest activities, a top agency official said Tuesday.
   Oliver B. Revell, executive assistant FBI director, also told
the Senate Intelligence Committee that no one in the administration
told the bureau to conduct the investigation.
   Revell's testimony offered the first in-depth look at the FBI's
investigations of the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El
Salvador, or CISPES, which began in 1981 and ended in 1985. Leaders
of CISPES maintain that the inquiries were politically motivated,
but Revell denied that charge.
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth,'' he said. ``We have
investigated a number of groups on the other side of the political
spectrum. ...
   ``The focus of the FBI investigations has been and is
criminality, or the collection of intelligence which will keep our
nation and citizens safe from terrorism,'' he said.
   At another point, Revell said, ``I have no knowledge of any
political taskings by anyone in the Reagan administration of the
FBI's CISPES investigation.''
   No criminal charges ever have been filed against CISPES or any
of its members.
   Several members of the committee told Revell they remained
skeptical of the FBI information that triggered the investigation
of CISPES.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said he had ``grave questions'' about
Revell's justifications, adding, ``You have to proceed on the basis
of tangible hard facts and evidence'' _ which he indicated were
lacking in this case.
   But Revell noted that it was a terrorism investigation, and
added that if the FBI always waited ``until there was tangible
evidence, you would have been picking up the pieces of the bombs.''
   Earlier, Specter asked Revell the extent of Webster's
involvement in the CISPES probe.
   ``He was aware of several cables sent to him for informational
purposes,'' Revell said. ``He did not authorize any of the
activities. The supervision was at the sectional level.''
   Revell added that it is impossible for the FBI director to keep
up with all the investigations the bureau conducts. However, he did
say that in the wake of revelations about the conduct of the CISPES
case, ``we have taken interim steps to increase the level of
review'' of sensitive probes.
   Webster, who now directs the CIA, has had no public comment on
the investigation.
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, vice chairman of the intelligence
panel, joined Specter in criticizing the FBI probe.
   ``It is apparent that whatever the rationale for its initiation,
it resulted in the FBI subjecting many Americans and U.S.
organizations to various types of scrutiny without any basis other
than the exercise of their First Amendment rights,'' Cohen said.
   He later asked Revell why the FBI headquarters had to send a
memo on July 26, 1984, cautioning the field offices against
reporting legitimate political activities by CISPES.
   Revell replied that the memo was sent because top FBI officials
``sensed'' the conduct of some agents was ``very close to the
line.''
   ``We may have seen some wavering over that line,'' he said, but
he maintained that the investigation was legitimate under the FBI's
foreign intelligence and counterintelligence guidelines.
   Revell said the FBI opened its investigation into CISPES on
Sept. 3, 1981, after the Justice Department requested the bureau
examine whether the group was supplying money and material to
leftist rebels in El Salvador and therefore was required to
register under the Foreign Agents Registration Act.
   Revell described that probe as ``just a records check,'' and it
was closed in February 1982.
   A little more than a year later, on March 30, 1983, the
counterterrorism section at the FBI authorized a new investigation
of CISPES. This probe, Revell said, was into whether members of
CISPES were ``engaged in international terrorism, activities in
preparation therefor, or knowingly aiding and abetting the
terrorists in El Salvador and other countries in the conduct of
international terrorist activities.''
   That investigation continued for more than two years, during
which time, Revell said, ``we did find indications that some CISPES
members were at least discussing and planning violence.''
   He cited an instance of a CISPES member given the job of
determining response times of emergency services in a major
American city, another of a CISPES member saying he had developed a
system to shut down a public utility in a major Midwestern city and
a third of discussion of plans to disrupt the 1984 Republican
Convention in Dallas.
   Angela Sanbrano, executive director of CISPES, who attended the
Intelligence Committee hearing, denied afterward that any of the
charges were true. She suggested that the comments about possible
violent activities might have been made by someone ``planted'' at
CISPES meetings.
   Revell said the FBI closed the investigation in June 1985 ``when
we found there was insufficient evidence to continue the
investigation.''
   He said ``part of the reason for that was the disinformation and
misinformation supplied to us'' by Frank Varelli, who told a House
subcommittee last year hat he was paid by the FBI to infiltrate the
Dallas chapter of CISPES and told the bureau what it wanted to hear.
   Revell said earlier that the Dallas FBI agent who directed
Varelli was investigated for ``mishandling documents, funds and
direction.''
   Varelli has sued the FBI in an attempt to get pay he claims he
is owed for his work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
