<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-President     02-23 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-President,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Elects Herzog To Second Presidential Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's parliament on Tuesday elected
Irish-born Chaim Herzog to a second five-year term as the country's
president.
   Eighty-two members of the 120-member Knesset, or parliament,
voted to re-elect Herzog, who was unopposed. Two voted against him
and 18 did not vote, Israel radio reported. Other members were not
present.
   The office of president is a largely ceremonial one in Israel
and the president has no formal party affiliation.
   ``I heartily thank the members of Israeli Knesset for their
trust and their vote and (I) accept the Knesset's decision with
appreciation and gratitude,'' he said on Israel radio. ``I am proud
to serve the people.''
   Herzog, 69, was first elected to the post in March 1983.
   His first term in office was marked by a controversial decision
to pardon Shin Bet security agents, including the former head of
the service, Avraham Shalom, who were found guilty of lying in
court about the beating deaths of two captured Palestinian
hijackers.
   Herzog was criticized for the decision, but won praise when he
took a strong moral stand against a ring of Jewish terrorists
jailed for crimes against Arabs. He rejected a call from right-wing
Israelis to pardon all of them, although he did lessen the
sentences of some.
   Herzog was also praised for his behind-the-scenes efforts to end
an election stalemate in September 1984 between Shimon Peres'
centrist Labor Party and Yitzhak Shamir's conservative Likud bloc.
His efforts contributed to the forming of Israel's unusual
coalition government.
   Herzog headed Israel's military intelligence from 1959 to 1962.
In 1967, he became the first military governor of the occupied West
Bank, captured by Israel from Jordan in that year's Middle East
war. He also served as Israel's ambassador at the United Nations
from 1975 to 1978.
</TEXT>
