<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     02-23 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier in 1983 Shooting Freed; Ireland Probes Ulster Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British soldier sentenced to
life in prison for slaying a Belfast Catholic has been released
from jail and returned to his regiment after only three years in
prison, the army said Tuesday.
   Pvt. Ian Richard Thain was not, however, returned to active
service in Northern Ireland.
   An army statement Tuesday said Thain killed the man when he was
18.
   ``While the army in no way condones his action, we consider the
incident to have been a tragic error of judgment made by a young
man in very difficult circumstances,'' the statement said.
   The Rev. Denis Faul, a Roman Catholic priest and human rights
campaigner in Northern Ireland, said he had no objection to the
release, but asked why similar clemency could not be shown to
civilians serving life sentences for actions committed in their
youth.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, claimed Thain's release showed there was no
justice in Northern Ireland.
   ``I'm very, very shocked and distressed. I can't believe this
has happened,'' said the victim's father, Jim Reilly.
   The announcement of Thain's release came amid new tension
between Britain and Ireland.
   On Sunday, a Catholic was killed by a British soldier in
Northern Ireland. The Irish government announced it would undertake
its own investigation of the slaying, even though the incident
occurred in Northern Ireland outside Dublin's jurisdiction.
   The Irish move was seen as a calculated slight to Britain, since
its police force has already announced its own inquiry and the
soldier has been placed in military custody.
   Sunday's shooting of 23-year-old Aidan McAnespie occurred near
Aughnacloy, half a mile from the frontier in County Tyrone.
   McAnespie was killed by a bullet from an army observation tower
at a checkpoint as he walked to a football match.
   McAnespie was a Sinn Fein supporter, and his former parish
priest said he was harassed whenever he passed through the
checkpoint. Press Association, the British news agency, said the
soldier who fired at McAnespie told his interrogators it was an
accident.
   Thain was convicted of killing Thomas Reilly, road manager of
the pop group Bananarama, on Aug. 9, 1983. He claimed in court that
he fired because he believed Reilly was about to pull a gun on him.
   The judge found Thain ``deliberately untruthful.'' The private
was the first soldier sentenced to life imprisonment for actions in
Northern Ireland.
   Thain was released on a life license, a form of parole whereby
he can be reimprisoned ``should his behavior give rise to
concern,'' the Home Office said.
   It said he was freed after a review by the state parole board.
   Anglo-Irish relations are already under strain on a series of
issues including disputes over the extradition of IRA suspects and
British anti-terrorism laws which Dublin sees as discriminatory
toward Ulster Catholics.
   The worst tension, however, is being generated by Britain's
announcement last month that it will not prosecute Northern Ireland
police officers involved in the shooting of six unarmed Catholics
in three incidents in 1982, despite evidence of a police conspiracy
to pervert the course of justice.
</TEXT>
