<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EmergencyLanding     02-23 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Jet Makes Emergency Landing At O'Hare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delta Air Lines jetliner bound from Boston to
Salt Lake City made an emergency landing Tuesday at O'Hare
International Airport after the flight crew shut down one engine, a
federal aviation official said.
   Delta Flight 235, a Boeing 757 flying from Boston to Salt Lake
City with 127 people on board, made an unscheduled landing at
O'Hare at 9:22 a.m. CST, said Marjorie Kriz, a spokeswoman for the
Federal Aviation Administration.
   No injuries were reported, she said. The jetliner landed safely
and taxied on its own to a terminal, she said.
   ``They're designed to fly on one engine,'' Ms. Kriz said.
   The plane's 120 passengers and seven crew members remained on
board while repairs were made, and the craft left for Salt Lake
about 11:20 a.m., said Delta spokeswoman Christa Anderson.
   The crew shut down the engine as a precaution because an
indicator gauge showed low oil pressure, said a Delta official
reached at the company's marketing office in suburban Schaumburg.
   The official, who declined to be identified, said that the
incident would not be termed an emergency landing and that the
passengers were never in danger.
