<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryStrength     02-23 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Strength,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Forces Size Down 12,000 Over Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The active-duty strength of the nation's
military services in January was virtually unchanged from the
previous month but more than 12,000 below the same period last
year, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   As of Jan. 31, the Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force had
2,167,378 men and women on active duty, up 767 from Dec. 31 figure.
   That combined total represents a decrease of 12,023, however,
compared with the Jan. 31, 1987, tally. The armed services reported
active-duty strength of 2,179,401 a year ago.
   It is not unusual for military strength to swing up and down on
a monthly basis during the year, primarily because of differences
in the flow of new recruits. The strength totals are expected to
vary even more widely than normal this year, though, because the
Pentagon is reducing its active-duty strength in a budget-cutting
move.
   According to the latest ``Military Strength'' assessment, two of
the four armed services reported declines in personnel in January
from December.
   The Marine Corps reported 198,243 men and women on active duty,
down 194 from December. The Air Force reported 604,574, down 755.
   The Army had an active-duty strength of 778,835 as of Jan. 31,
up 1,155 from December. And the Navy reported 585,726 on active
duty last month, up 561 from December.
</TEXT>
