<1ST_LINE>r a AM-L'AmbianceCharges 1stLd-Writethru a0727 02-23 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-L'Ambiance Charges, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0727,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State's Attorney: No Charges In Apartment Collapse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD one graf with company comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State prosecutors said Monday they
won't seek criminal charges against contractors of an apartment
building that collapsed during construction in Bridgeport last
year, killing 28 workers.
   Chief State's Attorney John Kelly and Bridgeport State's
Attorney Donald Browne said investigators determined that the cause
of the collapse ``did not involve intentional criminal conduct on
the part of any contractor involved in the construction.''
   ``While investigators have disclosed the most probable cause of
the building collapse, we do not believe that they have
demonstrated either a gross deviation from a reasonable person's
standard of conduct or that the prosecution could demonstrate
responsibility for criminally negligent homicide beyond a
reasonable doubt,'' the prosecutors said in a statement.
   Richard Bieder, an attorney representing families of some
collapse victims, said authorities probably don't know all there is
to know about the accident because some people with information may
not have come forward.
   ``My experience is that more of them with information will begin
singing like canaries as the pressures (of lawsuits) mount,'' he
said.
   ``I think there's more behind this story,'' echoed Anthony
Petta, general manager of the Waterbury Foundation Co. Inc., which
was a concrete subcontractor for the L'Ambiance project and lost 11
workers in the accident. ``Who knows what will happen after all of
the court proceedings?''
   L'Ambiance Plaza, a multi-story apartment complex in
Bridgeport's downtown, was being built in the lift-slab method. In
that method, huge concrete floor slabs are poured and allowed to
harden in a stack on the ground before they are jacked into place
on steel columns.
   Federal authorities concluded the April 23, 1987, collapse was
triggered when a small bracket that was part of the lifting system
bent under pressure.
   The National Bureau of Standards concluded that builders failed
to conduct stress-analysis tests to find out if the lifting
brackets, steel pieces measuring about 4 by 12 inches, could hold
up the concrete slabs.
   The Labor Department assessed a record $5.1 million in fines
against five companies for violations at the apartment complex. The
heaviest fines went to TPMI-Maycomber, a joint venture of TPM
International of Darien and B.H. Maycomber of Boston, which was the
primary contractor and project manager, and Texstar Contruction Co.
of San Antonio, Texas.
   The decision announced Monday by Kelly and Browne affects only
state prosecution.
   A regional administrator for the U.S. Occupational Safety and
Health Administration, John Miles, said recently he has recommended
federal criminal charges be filed as a result of the collapse. The
federal review process could take months.
   Joe Egan, business agent for Ironworkers Local 424, which lost
seven men in the collapse, said he couldn't understand the state
prosecutors' decision.
   ``If there has to be criminal intent, than most manslaughter
cases would have to be thrown out of court,'' Egan said.
   Bridgeport Mayor Thomas W. Bucci declined to comment on Monday's
announcement except to say, ``They (Kelly and Browne) are both
excellent prosecutors and I'm not going to second guess their
decision in this matter.''
   In a lawsuit filed Oct. 28 by the victims' families, the city
was accused of negligence in issuing a building permit for
L'Ambiance Plaza and in inspecting construction of the building.
   David Turlington, a lawyer for Texstar Construction Co. of San
Antonio, Texas, said Connecticut's decision verifies ``that ... the
cause of the disaster has not been determined and Texstar continues
to dispute the findings by the National Bureau of Standards and
OSHA.''
</TEXT>
