<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brite     02-23 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brite,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They had the goods on Bucky. Even if
he'd had an alibi, he wasn't in a position to tell anyone about it.
   But when Hamilton County Sessions Court Judge H.L. Smith handed
down his sentence Monday, maybe he took into account this was
Bucky's first offense. And that he was only 3 years old. And also
that he was a deer.
   Bucky is a white-tailed buck judged too tame to survive in the
wild after being illegally raised on a farm since he was a fawn.
Smith ordered him to spend the rest of his life in Chattanooga's
Warner Park Zoo.
   The sentence satisfied Hershel Bradshaw, a 70-year-old
Birchwood, Tenn., man who had taken care of the deer since its
mother and another fawn were accidentally killed by a combine he
was operating.
   Bradshaw was concerned that Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency
officials wanted to destroy the seven-point buck.
   ``For a while, they were talking about taking it out in the
woods and shooting it,'' he said. ``I just don't think that would
have been right.''
   Bradshaw's attorney, Bob Moon, said his client was charged with
illegally taking and possessing a Class IV animal. Wildlife
officials were told about the deer by a group of hunters who became
angry when Bradshaw would not let them shoot the animal, which was
caged, Moon said.
   Tennessee law prohibits anyone except ``zoos and transient
circus acts'' from possessing or displaying a class of wildlife
that includes such as white-tailed deer, black bears, bobcats and
wild turkeys.
   The judge said he had no intention of fining Bradshaw.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that Michigan's 150th birthday is
over, the state office in charge of the bash has to figure out what
to do with nearly 10,000 birthday cards and letters.
   Many were placed by staff of the Sesquicentennial Office in a
large laundry hamper, but some can't be filed away so easily.
   For example, there is the 150-pound, 4-foot by 4-foot ceramic
tile state map, a joint venture of Detroit's Vernor Primary School
and Pewabic Pottery.
   There also are 28 6- by 4-foot birthday cards sent in by
Michigan shopping malls, some of them bearing more than 9,000
signatures.
   Some communities sent in birthday scrolls up to 20 feet long and
signed by hundreds of residents. Most of the cards are hand made.
Many are from kindergartens and elementary schools, but there's
even one from ``all of us at the Eaton County Jail.''
   The state's 18-month-long celebration of its 150th birthday
ended Jan. 26.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANITO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Things are popping out on the farm, thanks
to a jump in consumption of the fluffy white snack Americans devour
by the ton each year.
   Production of popcorn statewide has doubled since the early
1980s when the last official estimate was made, said John Unger,
statistician for the Illinois Agricultural Statistic Service in
Springfield.
   ``Consumption of popcorn has increased with the popularity of
microwave ovens,'' Unger said. ``The price of popcorn is up, and I
think some farmers see it as an alternative crop that will make
them a little more money.''
   Scott Talbott of Manito is hoping to take advantage of the
popcorn craze. He and his father, Gnile, grow up to 800 acres of
popcorn each year near this town of 1,900 located 20 miles south of
Peoria.
   Unger estimated Illinois farmers grow upwards of 35,000 acres of
popcorn each year, more than double the 15,000 acres reported in
1981 in the last census.
   Indiana leads the nation, with about 53,000 acres of popcorn,
and Nebraska and Ohio rank about even with Illinois.
   Deirdre Flynn, spokeswoman for the Popcorn Institute in Chicago,
said industry sales started climbing in 1984, and a reported 700
million pounds were sold in 1986.
</TEXT>
