<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Treaty-Obstacles Bjt   02-23 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treaty-Obstacles, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Negotiating Deadline Will Be Difficult To Meet</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet diplomats will have a tough
time meeting a one-month deadline for drafting portions of a treaty
to slash superpower nuclear arsenals, government and private
experts said Tuesday.
   ``The aspects of the agreements that they have agreed to draft
within 30 days are important, but they are appendages to the main
treaty,'' said Albert Carnesdale, a former arms control negotiator
now at Harvard University.
   And another former negotiator, James Hackett of the conservative
Heritage Foundation in Washington, cautioned that ``the best way to
get a bad agreement is to give your negotiators a deadline. Thirty
days is an incredibly short time for an agreement that should take
years to negotiate.''
   Both the Soviets and Americans would have to make major changes
in their bargaining positions to produce an agreement before a
summit planned for Moscow in late May or early June, said
Carnesdale, Hackett and administration sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and his Soviet counterpart
Eduard A. Shevardnadze set the 30-day deadline at their meeting in
Moscow on Monday, directing their staffs to reach draft agreements
dealing with verifying compliance with the cutbacks, disposing the
weapons, and exchange of information.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze meet again in Washington on March 22-23.
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and Soviet Defense Minister
Dmitri Yazov are also scheduled to discuss the issues at a meeting
in Bern, Switzerland, on March 16-17.
   The foreign ministers announced no major breakthroughs in the
Strategic Arms Reduction Talks (START), which President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev have agreed should cut superpower
nuclear arsenals to 6,000 warheads, a reduction of 30 percent to 50
percent, depending on how the weapons are counted.
   Among the major points of disagreement are a U.S. proposal to
limit the number of Soviet land-based intercontinental ballistic
missiles (ICBM's) to 3,300, no more than 1,630 of which can be on
rockets carrying seven or more warheads. And the Soviets are
demanding limits on the number of cruise missiles aboard submarines
and aircraft.
   One administration source said, ``It's going to be tough to get
a deal unless the two sides agree to mix and match,'' the formula
adopted in the second Strategic Arms Limitation Treaty, signed in
1979. That pact set overall limits on warhead levels but did not
achieve the limits on land-based Soviet ICBM's that the
administration has been seeking under START.
   Some analysts believe that no START deal is possible unless the
superpowers reach agreement on the degree to which the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty limits the testing of weapons
developed under Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative.
   However, Congress has barred the administration from spending
any money through next September on tests that would break the ABM
pact, and U.S. experts believe that enthusiasm for Star Wars will
wane after Reagan leaves office.
   ``Star Wars is probably a moot point,'' said an administration
source.
   A spokesman at the Soviet embassy, Boris Malkhov, said Tuesday
that ``we are confident that technical obstacles can be overcome.
We have the political will, and we think that President Reagan
does, also,'' to produce a START accord before the summit.
   ----
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Bryan Brumley writes on national security issues
from Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
