<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SurgeryShaking     02-23 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surgery Shaking,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tremors After Surgery Caused By Anesthetic Not Body Temperature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Post-operative trembling endured by half
the 25 million people who undergo surgery each year results from
the use of anesthetics, not from decreased body temperature as had
been assumed, according to a new study.
   The finding could lead to improved treatments to prevent the
unpleasant and uncontrollable tremors that in some cases resemble a
seizure and can be dangerous to patients, researchers said Tuesday.
   ``We now know that a very dramatic side effect of surgery has
been misinterpreted for more than 35 years,'' said Daniel I.
Sessler, assistant professor of anesthesia at the University of
California-San Francisco and head of the study.
   Sessler, along with researchers at UCLA and the University of
Minnesota, compared electrical signals produced in the muscles
during normal shivering to those in nine women recovering from
anesthetic after surgery. They found the post-surgical tremors were
not related to body temperature, but matched tremors produced in
people with severed spinal cords.
   Anesthetic, they found, wears off in the spine while the brain
remains asleep, essentially disconnecting the spine from the
brain's chemical messages.
   If the patient's skin gets cold, triggering shaking, the brain
cannot signal the muscle reflex to stop, Sessler said. After about
15 minutes, when the brain wakes up, the tremor stops, he said.
   ``People have been trying to do something for years about
post-surgical tremors, but generally without success because they
have been treating it as a thermo-regulatory problem,'' said
Sessler, who reported the finding at last year's meeting of the
International Anesthesia Research Society. The study will be
published in the journal Anesthesiology this year.
   Dr. Richard Stein, vice president of the American Society of
Anesthesiologists, said the finding will not drastically alter
current practice at hospitals, which already use lamps or blankets
once tremors begin.
   But according to Sessler, warming the skin with infrared heating
lamps or even something as simple as a hair dryer while the patient
is still asleep should prevent the tremors altogether.
   ``Infrared heating lamps are used empirically in some hospitals
and have already been shown to work ...,'' said Sessler. ``But most
don't treat this except with blankets. Routinely keeping the
patient warm would prevent this, even a modest increase in the
warming system.''
   The shaking, which can occur with almost all general anesthetics
in use today, can raise the patient's heart rate and blood
pressure, in addition to pulling apart incisions and damaging
teeth, Sessler said.
   Stein differed with Sessler's estimate that half of all surgical
patients experience some tremors, from mild to severe. He said such
cases are rare and are usually not serious.
   The condition is most common among patients treated in cold
operating rooms, such as those receiving hip or knee replacement,
he said. Orthopedic surgeons keep the temperature at around 62
degrees because of the heavy gowns they must wear and the air
conditioning system, both designed to prevent infection, he said.
   In a separate study, Sessler's research team disproved another
assumption _ that surgery patients lose all ability to control body
temperature. Anesthetics do not eliminate control but instead lower
the threshold for cold. The regulatory reaction occurs, but at a
much lower body temperature than normal, they found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
