<HEAD>DOE Says No Decision on Super Collider Site Before November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Selection of a site for the $4.4 billion
``super collider'' atom smasher will be delayed by up to four
months to prepare a draft environmental impact statement before,
instead of after, the choice, the Energy Department said Tuesday.
   Word of the delay, from July to November or December, came in
budget questioning of Secretary John Herrington before the interior
subcommittee of the House Appropriations Committee.
   He was asked whether he would pick the site before or after the
committee acts on his request for $363 million in construction
funds for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   ``I don't see us making the decision'' before the committee must
act, Herrington said. ``I would guess a preferred site would be
selected in November or December.''
   The department has planned for more than a year to chose the
final site in July and confirm it in January, subject to
preparation of an environmental impact statement.
   Department spokesman Jeff Sherwood said later that DOE now
believes it is better to do more work on the environmental impact
statement and complete a draft covering all possible sites before
chosing the final site.
   ``That will be on the street and people will be able to comment
on it, and we'll have the benefit of the comments in choosing the
fon to delay announcement
of a final site recommendation.
   ``The longer you go in with this project without getting the
funding committed, the more risk there is it won't get funded,''
Blanchard said at the National Governors' Association winter
meeting in Washington. ``The more you narrow down the site
selection, the less likely Congress is to fund it.''
   If Congress builds it, the superconducting super collider will
investigate exotic scientific theories of the origin of matter by
whirling beams of protons into each other at an energy 20 times
greater than what is now possible.
   Believed to be the largest scientific instrument ever built,
state governments are anxious to win the contest for the
53-miles-around tunnel because it will create 3,000 jobs and have
an annual operating budget of $270 million.
   Besides Michigan, Illinois, Texas, Arizona, Colorado, Tennessee
and North Carolina remain in the competition to build the collider.
</TEXT>
