<2ND_LINE>AM-Marine-Family,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Reacts to Tape of Marine Held Captive In Mideast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sisters of kidnapped Marine Lt. Col.
William Higgins said he appeared well on a tape released Monday by
his Lebanese extremist kidnappers.
   ``He looks good, considering what he's been through in the last
few weeks, but he is under a lot of stress,'' said his sister, Mary
Fisher, of the Jefferson County suburb of Okolona.
   ``It's strange to be seeing this. It's something you think can
never happen to you,'' said another sister, Linda Lee Miller of
Memphis, Tenn., who is visiting Mrs. Fisher.
   On the scratchy tape, Higgins, who was born in Danville, Ky.,
and grew up in nearby Garrard County, read a list of demands that
had to be met in order to obtain his release, including withdrawal
by Israel from its border ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   Higgins, 43, head of a United Nations observer force in Lebanon,
was kidnapped last Wednesday as he drove alone in a jeep on the
higihway south of Tyre, about 50 miles from Beirut.
   A group calling itself the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth, which claimed responsibility for the abduction, released the
70-second tape.
   ``I don't believe he thought it could happen to him. I believe
he thought he was safe,'' Mrs. Fisher said of her brother.
   Both Mrs. Fisher and Mrs. Miller said their brother would not
want the United States to give in to the kidnappers' demands.
   ``He would want them to take a hard line, not give in to them,
to stand up for the rights that the U.S. believes in,'' Mrs. Miller
said.
   While both sisters said they were glad to see that their brother
was alive, they realized it could be a long wait. Currently, there
are eight other Americans being held hostage in Lebanon, for as
long as nearly three years.
   ``He wouldn't want us to just stop our lives because he's in
this situation,'' Mrs. Fisher said.
   Mrs. Fisher said she would like to be able to get word to her
brother of the death of their father, William Higgins Sr. The elder
Higgins died Thursday, the day after his son's abduction, without
knowing what had happened to the Marine.
   Mrs. Fisher said she also had a message for her brother's
kidnappers.
   ``Please let him come home. Please release him.''
</TEXT>
