<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1717EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HijackingSuspect 2ndLd-Writethru a0767 02-23 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0767,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Confession of Hijacking Suspect</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: to UPDATE that top FBI official Oliver Revell was present
when Younis arrested, INSERT one graf after 9th graf pvs, bgng:
``The slow''; picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng: Younis' ``capacity</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI illegally obtained a suspected Shiite
Lebanese terrorist's confession to leading a 1985 airplane
hijacking during ``relentless interrogation'' that violated his
rights, a judge ruled Tuesday.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker suppressed oral and
written confessions that Fawaz Younis gave to agents after he was
lured aboard an FBI-chartered yacht in the Mediterranean last Sept.
13.
   Parker ruled the statements were inadmissable as evidence
because Younis was denied his constitutional protection against
self-incrimination and his right to legal counsel during four days
of questioning aboard a Navy ship in the Mediterranean.
   ``Somehere along the way, in its zeal and determination to
indict and prosecute an alleged hostage-taker and hijacker under
recent congressional enactments, and in securing Fawaz Younis'
written confession, the FBI failed to comply fully with
constitutional restraints and predecential Supreme Court
decisions,'' Parker said in a 47-page opinion.
   ``Law enforcement agencies must follow the letter and the spirit
of the law, even though the accused is not a citizen of the United
States,'' Parker said. The FBI ``failed to do so in September 1987
when it interrogated the defendant.''
   Younis was arrested when a friend who had become a government
informant lured him onto an FBI-chartered yacht with the prospect
of making a drug deal. Prosecutors say they have a videotape and
other statements from witnesses that place Younis at the scene of
the June 11, 1985, hijacking of a Royal Jordanian jetliner from
Beirut International Airport.
   He is scheduled to go to trial March 22 before Parker on charges
that he led hijacking, during which the plane was blown up after
passengers and crew were taken off the aircraft.
   Although Parker declined to rule that the arrest was illegal, he
concluded that the FBI deliberately kept Younis aboard the USS
Butte for four days to obtain a confession in ``a clear abuse of
the obligation to bring the defendant before a judicial officer
immediately following his arrest.''
   ``The slow voyage across the Mediterranean appeared to serve
only the government's purposes _ ample time to educe a
confession,'' Parker said. ``That deliberate action coupled with
the lengthy and relentless interrogation was all to the defendant's
prejudice and detriment.''
   The FBI launched its plan to abduct Younis early last year under
the direction of Oliver Revell, the bureau's executive assistant
director, who witnessed the arrest and was aboard the Butte for
part of its four-day voyage, according to testimony.
   Younis' ``capacity for self-determination was critically
impaired'' by seasickness and throbbing pain from wrists that were
fractured when agents slammed him to the deck of the yacht, Skunk
Kilo, following his arrest, Parker said.
   The judge noted that the FBI kept Younis in windowless,
overheated room aboard the ammunition ship as it steamed slowly
from waters off Cyprus to a rendezvous with the USS Saratoga four
days later. Younis was then flown from the carrier to Andrews Air
Force Base, Md.
   The defendant had been advised of his rights to remain silent
once during his interrogation, but ``In an uncertain physical
condition, in an oppressive environment, and subject to relentless
interrogation, Younis lacked the will necessary to voluntarily
waive his rights,'' Parker said.
   ``We are reviewing the decision carefully within our office and
with our colleagues in the Department of Justice,'' Timothy J.
Reardon III, principal assistant U.S. attorney, said in a
statement. FBI spokeswoman Susan Schnitzer said the bureau would
not comment on the decision.
   Parker also criticized the ship's doctors for providing
inadequate medical treatment and ``negligent diagnosis'' despite
Younis' ``constant complaints'' about the pain.
   Younis was given ice packs but his wrists were not X-rayed and
put into casts until after he was flown to Washington.
   Parker said he was ``extremely troubled'' by the FBI's failure
to provide Younis with a defense lawyer ``despite the meticulous
detail of Operation Goldenrod'' _ the FBI's code-name for the
effort.
   ``If the FBI could arrange to have a medical surgical team of
five doctors and several tons of medical equipment aboard the
Butte, would it have been too difficult to arrange for a competent
and detached attorney?''
   Besides the confession, prosecutors also have the testimony of
two Americans who identified Younis as one of five men who boarded
the plane with AK-47 assault rifles. They also have the testimony
of Jamal Hamdan, Younis' one-time friend who had several
conversations with him about the hijacking.
   In addition, prosecutors have a videotape of Younis reading a
statement to reporters before the plane was blown up in the
background.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
