<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WestVirginiaBudget     02-23 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-West Virginia Budget,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out State Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court on Tuesday
declared West Virginia's $1.49 billion budget unconstitutional
because it contains a deficit, and the state auditor's office said
all state spending would cease immediately.
   ``We've got to quit everything right now,'' said Don Adams,
chief clerk for Auditor Glen Gainer.
   Adams said no further expenditures of state money can be made
until the $26 million deficit in the current budget is corrected.
   There was a unanimous reaction of shock at the decision, which
had been pending for months.
   ``The governor has been saying it's unconstitutional since June.
I'm sure he'll be interested to hear that,'' said Gov. Arch Moore's
press aide, John Price.
   Moore was in Washington at a governor's conference Tuesday and
could not immediately be reached for comment.
   The court ruled in a 3-2 decision, in an opinion written by
Justice Darrell McGraw, did not tell Gov. Arch Moore and the
Legislature what to do about the unconstitutional budget.
   `` ... We presume the governor and Legislature will do their
duties,'' McGraw wrote.
   The decision resulted from a lawsuit brought by the West
Virginia Education Association last year that challenged cuts in
funding for education. The association did not seek to have the
budget declared unconstitutional but asked that Moore be forced to
call a special session to address the problem.
   In his response, Moore did not contest the allegations and said
the Legislature budgeted $26 million more than he had said would be
available in revenues. He said the document was unconstitutionally
out of balance.
   The state Constitution's requires ``that the estimate of revenue
and the budgeted appropriation be in balance so as not to create a
deficit.''
   But the high court said it refused to tell the Legislature and
the governor what they should do to correct the problem and
rejected the education association's request that a special
legislative session be ordered.
   It said the branches of government are equal and the court
presumes that the executive and legislative branches will do what
they are supposed to do.
</TEXT>
