<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HistoricTrail     02-23 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Historic Trail,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Park Service Dedicates Black History Trail In Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Park Service affirmed the dream
of a former Boy Scout Tuesday by dedicating a national trail he
conceived to show tourists landmarks that illustrate the rich
history of blacks in the nation's capital.
   The Black History National Recreation Trail winds from a
179-year-old cemetery in the exclusive Georgetown neighborhood to
the home of 19th century black leader Frederick Douglass in the
city's poor Anacostia section.
   ``The trail is a continued and living legacy to the achievements
of black Americans,'' said Willard Andre Hutt, 27, who started the
drive for the trail as his Eagle Scout project in 1979.
   Dedicated to the memory of late black historian Carter G.
Woodson, the tour through Washington is part of a series of
National Park Service trails, such as the Appalachian Trail, that
represent periods in American history.
   The trail includes such landmarks as Lincoln Park on Capitol
Hill; the downtown home of educator and presidential advisor Mary
McLeod Bethune; the Metropolitan African Methodist Episcopal
Church, the first AME in Washington, created in 1822 when a group
of dissatisfied blacks broke away from a predominantly white
church; Howard University, founded after the Civil War to provide
higher education to blacks; and the preserved home of abolitionist
Douglass.
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel, urging tourists to visit the
sites, wrote in a letter that the trail ``will surely contribute to
an increasing awareness of the vitality and rich history of the
black community in Washington D.C.''
   ``Our young people need to see these sites,'' Mayor Marion Barry
Jr. said at a dedication ceremony. ``They need to understand we
didn't get to where we are because of who we are, but because of
the struggle of these people.''
</TEXT>
