<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCare 1stLd-Writethru a0651 02-23 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Say Their Child Care Bill Has Better Chance Of
Becoming Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs Dodd comment after 5th graf bgng ``Hatch said
... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Republicans said Tuesday their $375
million child care improvement bill is far more likely to become
law than a multibillion-dollar alternative sponsored by Democrats.
   ``It's closer to what the president is going to sign than
anything else on the table or under discussion,'' said Rep. Nancy
Johnson, R-Conn., House sponsor of the GOP bill. ``It is practical.
It is realistic. It is doable.''
   The plan sponsored by Johnson and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
relies on state regulation and private initiatives. The $2.5
billion Democratic proposal requires federal regulation and, among
other things, provides more direct aid to low-income families.
   ``There's no way they can get that past a Democrat president,
let alone this president,'' Hatch said.
   Hatch said he would have to ``sit down and negotiate'' with Sen.
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., sponsor of the Democratic bill in the
Senate. He predicted no child care bill would pass unless it comes
close to what he has proposed.
   But Dodd said he and Hatch already have had ``numerous
conversations'' about the two child care proposals, with little to
show for them.
   ``I frankly feel that under any of the presidential candidates,
I would fare better with my child care proposal than under this
administration,'' Dodd said. ``So unless I sense that Sen. Hatch
and others are willing to move more in our direction to really
target low- and moderate-income families, I am going to be
unwilling to necessarily reach a compromise this year.''
   Hatch initially introduced his bill last year, saying
conservatives had to take a leadership role in resolving the child
care problems faced by many working families. He reintroduced it
Tuesday with some refinements and Johnson's companion measure in
the House.
   The bill provides $250 million for state grants to projects
designed to improve or expand child care or make it more
affordable, $100 million for liability pools that any licensed
provider could join and $25 million for capital improvements to
regulated day care homes.
   In addition it would limit provider liability, give tax credits
to employers with on-site child care and offer a double tax
exemption to families in which a parent stayed home for six months
to care for a newborn. The break would be worth about $500 to $600
to the average family.
   Though some experts have said state regulation of day care is
inconsistent and in some cases very poor, Johnson said that would
change because the bill requires state regulation and will
stimulate debate.
   ``When that debate becomes public ... it results in good
standards,'' she said.
   Johnson also said the bill would decrease the incidence of
``underground'' providers because it addresses the liability
problem and simplifies taxes for family day care providers.
   ``If you don't deal with those disincentives, you're not going
to bring people into the regulated system,'' she said.
   The National Governors' Association, meanwhile, urged the
federal government Tuesday to take action on child care, including
a ``modest'' commitment of funds to help poor working families.
   The governors, ending their three-day winter meeting in
Washington, called for the public and private sectors to work in
concert on the problem, and said that despite the deficit, ``the
federal government should begin to take action to improve child
care.''
   But President Reagan on Monday cautioned the governors to
``tread carefully'' on the issue of child care.
   ``Maybe it's my conservative bent, but I can't help but feel
uneasy sometimes'' about proposals to seek government solutions to
such problems, Reagan said.
   Hatch and Johnson described their bill as bipartisan, although
most Democrats are supporting the Dodd bill, introduced in the
House by Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich.
   Proponents of the Democratic measure say a strong federal role
is needed to unify and strengthen the current piecemeal system and
to give the private sector a framework in which to invest.
   Only 5 percent of employers currently offer day care services or
direct financial aid to pay for them.
</TEXT>
