<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia 1stLd-Writethru a0770 02-23 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0770,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands March in Territorial Dispute</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDS: Deletes `a' in 7th graf `The government' to make spelling
Nagorno-Karabakhskaya
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people marched in Soviet Armenia on
Tuesday to demand control of territory assigned to another
republic, dramatically illustrating tensions among the nation's 100
nationalities.
   Demonstrations in Yerevan, capital of the southern Soviet
republic, followed protests in the disputed area, a small
mountainous region just north of Turkey.
   A former political prisoner said from Yerevan that the
protesters want the small area _ part of the neighboring republic
of Azerbaidzhan _ to be made part of the republic of Armenia
because many Armenians live there.
   Other problems between different nationalities have led to
demonstrations in the republics of Kazakhstan, Estonia, Lithuania
and Latvia.
   Nationalist demonstrations have increased since Mikhail S.
Gorbachev gained power in March 1985 and adopted a policy of
``glasnost,'' or openness on selected social issues. On Feb. 10, he
said developing a nationalities policy is ``the most vital,
fundamental issue of our society.''
   Dissidents in Moscow said Tuesday at least 100,000 demonstrators
took to the streets in Yerevan, but a participant claimed later the
number was 200,000. In either case, it appeared to be one of the
largest unofficial gatherings ever reported in the Soviet Union.
   The government acknowledged ``breaching of public order'' took
place in the the disputed area, Nagorno-Karabakhskaya, and said the
territorial demands were against the public interest.
   Tamara Grigoryants, a Moscow dissident whose husband is
Armenian, said the disputed area in the Caucasus was given to
neighboring Azerbaidzhan in the early 1920s although most of its
inhabitants are Armenian.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan, a 38-year-old former political prisoner, said
in a telephone interview from Yerevan that protests began late
Monday and continued Tuesday. Yerevan is 1,100 miles south of
Moscow.
   ``No one slept all night,'' he said. ``We gathered at the opera
house at about 11 p.m. and stayed out demonstrating until 5 a.m.
About 200,000 people massed outside the Council of Ministers, the
Central Committee headquarters and the Supreme Soviet.''
   About one-third of Armenia's 3.3 million people live in Yerevan.
   Ayrikyan led an underground Armenian nationalist group called
the National Unification Party and was jailed for 17 years
beginning in 1969. He said he now is chairman of a nationalist
group called Alliance for National Determination.
   Earlier this month, he said, the Nagorno-Karabakhskaya
government council asked that the region be made part of Armenia,
citing the constitutional guarantee of the right of
self-determination. The Communist Party Central Committee rejected
the request, and demonstrations followed in Nagorno-Karabakhskaya
and Yerevan, Ayrikyan said.
   Soldiers brought in tanks to quell protests in
Nagorno-Karabakhskaya and rumors circulated that some demonstrators
were killed, he said.
   The government made its comment through the official news agency
Tass, and the dispatch was read later on the national evening news
program.
   ``Breaching of public order was provoked as a result of
irresponsible calls by extremist individuals,'' Tass said of events
in Nagorno-Karabakhsaya.
   It said the Central Committee ``holds that the actions and
demands directed at revising the existing national and territorial
structure contradict the interests of the working people in Soviet
Azerbaidzhan and Armenia and damages inter-ethnic relations.''
   The Central Committee urged residents ``not to yield to
provocations by nationalist elements'' and said all measures would
be taken to ``safeguard public order,'' Tass reported. It did not
give the number of demonstrators or say what actions were taken to
stop the protest.
   Alexander Ogorodnikov, a former political prisoner who lives in
Moscow, said demonstrators in Yerevan chanted the slogan, ``One
nation, one republic!''
   Karen S. Demirchyan, the Armenian Communist Party chief, went on
television Monday night asking people to be calm, but thousands
gathered outside the opera whistled and jeered, Ogorodnikov and
Ayrikyan said.
   Police followed the demonstrators as they marched through
Yerevan but did not detain or harrass the protesters, Ayrikyan said.
   He added that rumors were circulating of authorities sending
martial arts experts to the city to cause disorder and provide
police with a pretext for intervention.
   Problems of nationalities gained prominence last summer in the
Baltic republics, and there were street demonstrations in Latvia,
Lithuania and Estonia to mark the anniversary of a secret
German-Soviet agreement that led to the Soviet takeover of the
three countries in 1940.
   On Feb. 16 in Vilnius, the capital of Lithuania, there was a
heavy presence of police patrolling the streets and squares in an
apparent move to prevent any demonstrations on the 70th anniversary
of Lithuanian independence.
   Estonian dissidents plan more protests Wednesday.
   In the Central Asian republic of Kazakhstan, at least 3,000
people rioted Dec. 17-18, 1986, in the capital Alma Ata to protest
appointment of an ethnic Russian to replace a Kazakh as the
republic's party leader.
</TEXT>
