<DOCNO> AP880223-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StatePenalties     02-23 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Penalties,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monitors Should Hit Big Overpayments in State Assistance Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal monitors of state-run family
assistance programs should penalize only those states with
excessive rates of overpayments, a congressional study said Tuesday.
   Moreover, the report by the Nationa Research Council said the
current federal monitoring system should be replaced with one that
measures state efforts to accomplish the social purposes of the
programs rather than just financial accountability.
   Recommendations of the panel, an operating arm of the National
Academy of Sciences, are based on an 18-month study ordered by
Congress.
   The new report focuses on Aid to Families with Dependent
Children and Medicaid. A similar report issued last May
concentrated on the Food Stamp program.
   The underlying call for different ways of measuring
effectiveness applied to all three programs, which account for
about 40 percent of total federal spending on the poor.
   Nevada is the only state that has escaped sanctions that are
expected to total $3 billion by 1989. Nearly all of the 49 states
facing sanctions are appealing and some are challenging them in
court.
   Intended to deter overpayment errors in the three programs,
penalties are imposed if a state's error rate exceeds 5 percent of
its Food Stamp payments and 3 percent of its AFDC and Medicaid
payments.
   The panel endorsed the concept of imposing sanctions for
improperly run programs, but said the overpayment error rate should
not be the sole criteria of a state's performance.
   It said the present monitoring system does not provide the
``detailed data that are needed for identifying and correctioning
problems at the service-delivery level.''
   Because of uncertainties in the available information, sanctions
should be limited to ``extremely bad performers'' until a more
comprehensive method of measuring performance is developed, the
panel said.
   It said federal officials should measure the states against each
other, rather than the present absolute gauge, and penalize only
those with ``excessively large'' error rates.
   However, the report did not specify a cutoff point as being
``exessively large'' and said, ``There is no absolutely reliable
way of determining, say, the 10 states with the highest error
rates.''
</TEXT>
