<HEAD>Conn. Attorney General Challenges Weicker; McCloskey Seeks New
Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT that disputed recount was not in
McCloskey's first election but his second; SUBS penultimate graf to
CORRECT number of votes cast in 1984 election to 230,000, sted
260,00.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut Attorney General Joseph I. Lieberman announced
Monday he will challenge maverick Republican Sen. Lowell P. Weicker
Jr.'s bid for re-election, while Democratic Rep. Frank McCloskey of
Indiana _ who won re-election in 1984 in a disputed recount _ said
he would seek a fourth term.
   And in Augusta, Maine, longtime congressional aide Edward S.
``Ted'' O'Meara said he would run for the GOP nomination in the 1st
Congressional District, challenging L.L. Bean heiress Linda
Bean-Jones in a primary. The seat is held by Democrat Joseph E.
Brennan, the former governor.
   Lieberman, 45, a Democratic former state senator who ran
unsuccessfully for Congress in 1980, attacked Weicker for using the
Senate as ``a debating society'' for his own agenda.
   Weicker, 56, who announced his candidacy for a fourth term
earlier this month, has made a name for himself as a liberal
Republican, frequently at odds with his party and president. He has
championed constitutional issues and civil rights and worked
against school prayer and balanced budget amendments.
   The candidates will be determined at state party conventions
this summer. So far, Weicker is unopposed and Lieberman has only
token opposition from Gary Johnson, who describes himself as a
veterans' rights advocate.
   McCloskey said he expected another tough campaign in the 8th
Congressional District, which is situated in southwestern Indiana.
In 1984, McCloskey won by just four votes in a hotly disputed
recount after a race with Republican candidate Rick McIntyre of
Bedford in which more than 230,000 votes were cast.
   So far, two Republicans have filed to challenge McCloskey _ John
Smith, a Bloomington businessman, and John Myers, an Odon newspaper
publisher.
</TEXT>
