<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Secretary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0739,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Taps Capitol Hill Veteran To Succeed Webb as New Navy
Secretary</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: to UPDATE with Reagan, Pentagon comment, INSERT two grafs
after 13th graf pvs, bgng: Fitzwater said; picks up 14th graf pvs,
bgng: `It is</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wr~</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday picked a veteran
Capitol Hill infighter, William L. Ball III, to step into a
simmering dispute over Pentagon budget cuts as his new secretary of
the Navy.
   The White House said the president will nominate Ball, a former
Capitol Hill aide who has been chief lobbyist for both the State
Department and the White House, to succeed James Webb, who resigned
as Navy secretary on Monday with a blast at Secretary of Defense
Frank C. Carlucci.
   ``We look to Will Ball to continue working aggressively for a
strong U.S. Navy,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said,
noting Webb's charge that Carlucci had needlessly sacrificed the
administration's goal of a 600-ship fleet.
   Fitzwater said the administration still seeks a 600-vessel Navy,
but now expects that the goal will be reached in fiscal year 1992,
more than two years after Reagan leaves office, rather than in
fiscal 1989 as originally planned.
   ``The budget restructuring under way at the Pentagon now is a
difficult and painful process,'' Fitzwater said. ``Secretary
Carlucci is doing an admirable job. He's quite capable and suitable
to the task, and he's carrying out thepresident's policies in that
regard.''
   Of Ball, he said, ``All of us who kFw him here at t Z/e
House know that the Navy is getting a strong advocate and a strong
fighter both on the Hill as well as in any of the other courts of
public opinion around the country.''
   Ball, 39, a soft-spoken Southerner who came to Washington as an
aide to former Sen. Herman Talmadge, D-Ga., has a reputation for
skill at the behind-the-scenes compromises and maneuvers needed to
steer legislation through Congress.
   Webb, on the other hand, was more noted for outspoken advocacy
of such controversial positions as his criticism of the service
academies' admission of women and his ruling that the Navy would no
longer accommodate officers who want to play professional sports.
   Ball has been assistant to the president for legislative affairs
since February 1986. Before that he had been assistant secretary of
state for legislative and intergovernmental affairs. From 1981 to
1985 he was administrative assistant to`hen Sen. John Tower,
R-Texas, serving also as chief clerk of the Senate Armed Services
Committee in 1981. He was Talmadge's administrative assistant in
1978.
   A native of South Carolina, he is a graduate of the Georgia
Institute of Technology and was a regular officer in the Navy from
1969 to 1975.
   As secretary of the Navy, Ball will oversee approximately
584,000 Navy personnel and 199,000 Marines.
   He will be succeeded at the White house by a deputy, Alan
Kranowicz, who has been primarily responsible for White House
lobbying efforts in the House. Kranowicz served as chief of staff
to former Rep. Tom Loeffler, R-Texas, while Loeffler was in
Congress.
   Fitzwater said Webb ``did the honorable thing'' in resigning
when he could no longer support the president's policies. He said
Webb's service was ``distinguished and the president appreciates it
very much.''
   Later the White House released a letter from Reagan to Webb
accepting the resignation ``with regret'' and saying, ``As your
service to this administration comes to a close, I want to thank
you for the selflessness and loyalty that you have always
personified.''
   Defense Department spokesman Dan Howard said, ``The Pentagon is
very pleased that someone with such positive credentials has been
named so quickly.''
   ``It is a painful restructuring they are having to go through to
absorb some of those reductions in spending levels,'' the
presidential spokesman said. ``The president has been a strong
advocate of the military and has worked hard to build it up over
many years and feels that pain no less than anyone else.''
   The budget cuts being carried out by Carlucci, the former White
House national security adviser who succeeded Caspar W. Weinberger
at the Pentagon late last year, result from a compromise reached by
Reagan with the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   In his budget message delivered last Thursday to Congress,
Reagan said he had kept his part of the bargain and expected them
to keep their part by appropriating the full amount agreed upon for
Pentagon spending.
   Ball's nomination requires confirmation by the Senate. He is
expected to have little difficulty since the nomination will be
reviewed by the Senate Armed Services Committee, many of whose
members know him as a former aide to the panel and to Tower, who is
a former member and chairman.
   In announcing his resignation Monday, Webb charged that Carlucci
had instructed him to deny news stories reporting that it was the
Defense Department, not the Navy, that wanted to mothball ships.
   He also said Carlucci needed to ``spend a lot more time with the
top leaders in this building (the Pentagon),'' but instead had been
``spending a lot of time with the State Department and a lot of
time on the Hill.''
   Carlucci declined to respond, saying only that he had learned of
Webb's resignation with ``regret.''
</TEXT>
