<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Elections     02-23 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Elections,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead In Election Denounced By Church Leader, Politicians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new election system in which people vote
for candidates by lining up behind them led to one death and
widespread charges of fraud, Kenya newspapers reported Tuesday.
   The purpose of Monday night's voting was to choose parliamentary
candidates for Kenya African National Union of President Daniel
arap Moi, Kenya's only legal political party.
   John Matere Keriri, who was assistant transport minister but
failed in his nomination bid, called the vote ``an absolute sham, a
fraud not an election.''
   Keriri and a few other losing candidates claimed they or their
agents were arrested and harassed by partisan officials the night
before the Monday vote and that several agents were barred from
polling stations.
   One man identified as a Keriri supporter died and two other
people were hospitalized in the northern Kirinyaga district, where
violence was used to keep some people from voting, newspapers
reported.
   The elections marked the party's first test of the new system
and a much-criticized regulation that allows nominees with more
than 70 percent of the vote to enter Parliament unopposed.
   At least 30 candidates received more than 70 percent.
   Church leaders, lawyers and a few politicians have called the
line-forming system as intimidating and said the 70-percent rule
disenfranchizes non-party members.
   Under the new system, voters lined up behind candidates and
officials took a head count.
   Government officials contend the new system will prevent
corruption and give the party rank and file a greater voice.
Candidates previously were chosen by the party chairman,
secretary-general and treasurer.
   Preliminary results indicated poor turnouts in many
constituencies. The Standard, an independent Nairobi newspaper,
reported hundreds of eligible voters milled outside some voting
locations and only a few lined up to vote.
   ``It appeared more people came as spectators than as voters,''
it said.
   Anglican Bishop David Gitari accused election officials of
trying to rig the ballots. He said the election official at one
polling station refused to count heads when more people lined up
behind Keriri than behind his opponent.
   Official tallies were expected later this week in the week.
   Presidential nominations are due Saturday but no-one is expected
to challenge Moi. He has held the office since the death of the
first president, Jomo Kenyatta, a decade ago.
</TEXT>
