<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Helms-Missiles     02-23 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helms-Missiles,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Arms Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said Tuesday that
most U.S. intelligence agences now believe the Soviet Union is
hiding hundreds of potent medium-range missiles in Europe. The
Reagan administration said his assertion is incorrect.
   Helms, commenting as the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
continued its examination of the new treaty banning all
medium-range missiles in Europe, has repeatedly said estimates from
the Defense Intelligence Agency indicate the existence of at least
300 more SS-20 missiles than those declared by the Soviets.
   The senator, who opposes the treaty, said on Tuesday he now has
been told a majority of U.S. intelligence agencies support that
view.
   But Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-RI., the committee chairman, read an
administration statement denying that.
   The statement called the Helms assertion incorrect, and added:
``The majority of the national intelligence community does not
support the view the Soviets have withheld a number of SS-20s.''
   The statement said that all data on the number of such weapons
will be reviewed when the Soviets submit an updated report on their
medium-range missile force after the new treaty is ratified by the
Senate.
   That report will be verified by on-site inspection, the
statement said.
   It said that CIA Director William Webster, ``speaking for the
entire intelligence community, has said the (submitted) Soviet data
... `falls within (U.S.) intelligence estimates.'''
   The SS-20 is a mobile, highly accurate, medium-range missile,
each of which carries three nuclear warheads.
</TEXT>
