<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, Snow Over Most of Eastern U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Tuesday from Michigan to New York, while rain dampened
areas from the Gulf Coast to New England.
   Clear to partly cloudy skies prevailed west of the Mississippi
River.
   Snow fell in southeastern Kentucky, West Virginia, and western
sections of Pennsylvania and New York, mixed with rain across parts
of northern New England and central New York.
   Heavier snowfall Tuesday morning included 6 inches at Coopers
Rock State Park in West Virginia; 5 inches in Laurel Village, Pa.;
and 3 inches at Somerset, Pa., and Chalke Hill, Pa.
   Snow showers dusted the Michigan shore of Lake Superior between
Marquette and Sault Ste. Marie.
   Rain was scattered from southern New England across southeastern
New York and eastern Pennsylvania, and the Tennessee Valley, and
fell in portions of the central Gulf Coast and central Florida.
   Gale warnings were posted along the New England coast, where
winds were clocked at 20 to 35 mph. Winds of 20 to 35 mph also were
common from the northern Plains to the upper Great Lakes, resulting
in sub-zero wind chill readings.
   Ice jams prompted flood warnings along streams near Buffalo, N.Y.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 84 degrees at Homestead, Fla. The morning low was 14
below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for sunny skies over most of the
nation, with snow showers in parts of the Great Lakes region and a
few rain showers in the Florida peninsula.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 20s and 30s from
Wyoming and Colorado across the northern half of the Plains, the
middle-Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and the Ohio Valley to
New England; the 60s in much of California, southern New Mexico,
southern Texas, northern Florida and southern Georgia; the 70s and
low 80s in the desert Southwest and southern and central Florida;
and the 40s or 50s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
