<2ND_LINE>AM-Nasser-Son,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Denies That Nasser's Son Has Political Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia denied Tuesday that it
had granted political asylum to the son of former Egyptian
President Gamal Abdel Nasser, who is wanted for terrorism in Egypt.
   In a statement read to The Associated Press over the telephone,
a Yugoslav Foreign Ministry spokesman also denied that Khaled Abdel
Nasser is a permanent resident of Belgrade.
   ``It is true that he periodically visits Yugoslavia like any
visitor who has a tourist visa,'' said the spokesman, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Nasser and 19 others were indicted in Egypt last week in
connection with four shooting attacks on Israeli and U.S. diplomats
and embassy workers in Cairo between 1984 and 1987. Two Israelis
died and six Israelis and two Americans were wounded in the
shootings.
   Nasser, 38, and 10 other defendants face possible death
sentences. The other nine could receive life sentences.
   Arab reports said Nasser had been living in Belgrade with his
family for four months and that Yugoslavia granted him political
asylum.
   ``We want to emphasize that he has never asked for nor was
granted political asylm'' in Yugoslavia, said the statement. ``He
(Nasser) is not engaged in any political activity in Yugoslavia.''
   The spokesman said that Nasser possesses a multiple-entry
tourist visa given to all those who have diplomatic passports.
   ``He has an Egyptian diplomatic passport,'' he added.
   Cairo newspapers reported that authorities in Yugoslavia had
been notified that Nasser is a fugitive sought by Interpol, the
international criminal police organization.
   The daily Al-Akhbar also said Ahmad El-Khawaga, a defense
attorney and head of the Egyptian bar association, went to Belgrade
to bring Nasser back from exile.
   Yugoslavia's late leader Josip Broz Tito was a co-founder of the
Non-Aligned Movement with Gamal Abdel Nasser. Egypt and Yugoslavia
have no extradition treaty.
</TEXT>
