<HEAD>Two Israeli Soldiers Killed, Two Wounded In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli tank was attacked while on patrol in
south Lebanon, and two Israeli soldiers were killed and two
wounded, the military command announced Tuesday.
   Lebanese security sources said earlier Tuesday that guerrillas
using rocket-propelled grenades ambushed an Israeli armored patrol
consisting of one tank and one armored personnel carrier near the
south Lebanese village of Braachit, killing two soldiers and
wounding others.
   The Israeli army announcement said the tank was hit by an
explosive device at 6 p.m. Monday near Braachit, six miles north of
the Israeli border in Israel's self-designed security zone in south
Lebanon.
   ``The explosive device was activated and as a result of that,
two soldiers were killed and two others suffered light wounds and
were rescued,'' the brief announcement said. It said Israeli
soldiers launched a search in the area.
   The announcement gave no details. The military command did not
explain why the announcement was delayed for over 24 hours.
   The Israeli fatalities in south Lebanon were the first this year.
   ``Both vehicles were raked with rocket-propelled grenades that
set off a chain of ammunition explosions in the tank. No one could
have escaped alive from the burning tank,'' said one of the
Lebanese sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the guerrillas were either Shiite Moslem fundamentalists
or pro-Syrian leftists. Both groups operate in that area.
   Israel created its six- to 10-mile-wide security zone when it
withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon in June 1985, ending a
three-year occupation.
   The zone is patrolled by about 1,000 Israeli soldiers assisted
by about 1,000 militiamen from the mostly Christian South Lebanon
Army, which is trained and backed by Israel.
</TEXT>
