<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Minister     02-23 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Minister,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Canadian Cabinet Member Acquitted</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ST-JEAN, Quebec (AP) _ Andre Bissonnette, who was dismissed from
the federal Cabinet after news reports linked him to a questionable
land deal, was acquitted Tuesday of four charges of fraud, breach
of trust and conspiracy.
   Normand Ouellette, Bissonnette's close friend and political
associate, was convicted of one count of fraud but acquitted of one
charge of breach of trust, one count of conspiracy to commit fraud
and one count of conspiracy to commit breach of trust.
   Charges were filed after a series of sales that tripled the
price of a piece of land in St-Jean from $800,000 to $2.98 million
in 11 days of January 1986. The Canadian dollar is worth about 79
U.S.
   Oerlikon Aerospace Inc. contracted to buy the land 13 weeks
before the federal government awarded it a $600 million contract to
build Canada's low-level air defense system.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney fired Bissonnette, 42, of St-Jean
a day after reports of the land sales were made public last year.
He had been junior transport minister.
   In Ottawa, Mulroney's office released a statement saying ``the
prime minister is very pleased that Mr. Bissonnette has been fully
exonerated by a jury of his peers.'' The statement said nothing
about Bissonnette's chances of getting back into the Cabinet.
   The jury was told to decide whether steps taken by Ouellette
that drove up the price were ``objectively dishonest,'' and whether
Bissonnette helped him.
   Judge Jean-Guy Boilard of Quebec Superior Court also instructed
the jury to determine whether Bissonnette knew of methods used by
Ouellette, who managed his blind trust.
   Prosecutors alleged that Bissonnette and Ouellette used
privileged information to profit illegally from the sale.
Bissonnette denied in court that half the profit from the final
transaction, in which Ouellette was involved, wound up in the bank
accounts of himself and his wife.
   Bissonnette smiled slightly as the verdict was read. He later
crossed the room, patted Ouellette on the back and wished him luck.
   Bissonnette, a self-made millionaire, was known as the ``Chicken
King'' of Quebec because one of his companies supplied much of the
barbecued chicken sold in restaurants in the province.
   Outside the courthouse, he shook hands with several jurors. He
thanked Mulroney for supporting him over the past 13 months and
said he would leave any decision about his political future up to
the prime minister.
</TEXT>
