<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria-AIDS     02-23 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria-AIDS,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Reviewing Plans For Complete Screening Of Blood
Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BADAGRY, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is reviewing plans for
comprehensive screening of blood supplies for AIDS, since some
blood banks were testing only 8 percent of their supplies, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported Tuesday.
   Dr. Etim Essien, chairman of the National Adivsory Committee on
AIDS, said testing in Nigeria's nine blood banks ranged from 8 to
85 percent of supplies.
   Essien said the incidence of AIDS in Nigeria was small, but
plans for a comprehensive screening program were under review to
guard against the spread of the disease through blood transfusions.
   Essien said there were 20 known cases of AIDS in Nigeria,
Africa's most populous nation with more than 105 million people,
and the chances of getting the disease through blood transfusion
were small. He gave no details about the screening program or say
when it would be implemented.
   Essien's comments followed the launching of a $1 million
national AIDS education program.
   Meanwhile, a Lagos newspaper confirmed the death Friday of the
country's 12th AIDS victim, a Gambian national living in Nigeria.
   Professor Idris Mohammed, also speaking at the launching of the
new AIDS program, said Nigeria's AIDS victims were mostly
low-income farmers who patronized prostitutes.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a disease in which a
virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible
to a wide variety of infections and cancers.
   AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual contact. Other
means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or
blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles
or syringes by drug abusers. AIDS can also be passed from mother to
child at or before birth.
</TEXT>
