<2ND_LINE>AM-Officers Shot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0764,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage: Suspect Claimed He Was Framed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, Officer Onofre...', to CORRECT that policeman
wounded in his left shoulder, sted `her'. Picks up 8th graf,
`According to...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 28-year-old transient was being held
Tuesday in lieu of $1 million bond, accused of shooting two
plainclothes policemen and then barricading himself with hostages
in an office building.
   David Johnson was charged with two counts of attempted capital
murder in the Monday night shooting.
   Authorities alleged that Johnson, a familiar figure to officers
patrolling downtown, scuffled with police who confronted him, got
an officer's gun and opened fire.
   One of the captives, Jerry Renaud, said the gunman seemed
disoriented and contended he was being framed by police.
   ``My understanding is he had some mental problems and it's your
typical downtown problem that we've been faced with,'' City Manager
Lou Fox said Monday night.
   Meanwhile, Officer Edwin Gorrell, 33, a two-year veteran, was in
critical condition at Brooke Army Medical Center after more than 13
hours of surgery on a head wound, said hospital spokesman Robert
Clark.
   Officer Onofre Serna, 26, was in good condition at Medical
Center Hospital with a wound to his left shoulder, said hospital
spokeswoman Inez Eisazadeh.
   According to police spokesman Sgt. Paul Buske, the two officers
had stopped the man and a female companion who appeared to be
intoxicated.
   ``A struggle ensued,'' Buske said. ``One of the officers lost
his weapon. (The suspect) picked up the weapon and several shots
were fired.''
   The man took a gun, a badge and a police radio and fled into a
Travis Park Plaza building, where he took two hostages. He released
them and went to a third-floor office, where he took three hostages.
   Renaud, an accountant who was working late with others at
Deloitte, Haskins and Sells, said he at first thought the gunman
was joking, then decided to listen to the man to calm him down.
   ``He seemed disoriented at first, despondent, that he had gotten
framed,'' Renaud said Tuesday. ``He said he wasn't there to hurt
us. He said he just needed a place to hide out for the night.''
   After a few minutes, he said, he and the man got a soft drink to
cool off.
   ``Right after he got his Coke, I decided I needed a drink
desperately and poured a little Seagram's Seven in my Coke so I
could think,'' Renaud said. ``I got interrupted quite a few times
by the telephone, but I never really tried to say anything that
would upset him.''
   Renaud and his two co-workers escaped when the gunman walked
into another area to take a sixth hostage, Buske said. He
surrendered an hour later.
   The San Antonio Express-News talked to the man by telephone
Monday night. He told the newspaper he was just walking when he was
grabbed by a man with a gun and a badge.
   ``The gun just went off ... I didn't mess with nobody,'' he said.
   Gorrell and Serna were part of a downtown foot patrol aimed at
deterring street crime.
   Last month, a mentally ill homeless man shot and killed a Dallas
police officer in a downtown parking lot.
</TEXT>
