<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Wopat Adv04-06   02-23 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Wopat, Adv 04-06,0785</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04-06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 4-6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Tom Wopat Battling ``Good Ole Boy'' Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ``Dukes of Hazzard'' star Tom
Wopat is battling his spirited ``good ole boy'' image with love
songs and a new TV show about modern family issues.
   Wopat is starring in the new CBS-TV drama, ``Blue Skies,'' and
is maintaining a singing career with country music-oriented songs
that have a more romantic feel than driving souped-up cars as the
adventurous Luke Duke.
   ``Blue Skies'' is scheduled to begin this spring and the action
involves coping with contemporary issues such as aging and
alcoholism rather than rural escapades with his blond buddy John
Schneider.
   ``It was a golden opportunity to be involved with fine persons
and escape the `good ole boy' stereotype,'' the 36-year-old Wopat
said. ``I'm a totally different character. In `Dukes,' everything
was fantasy. In `Blue Skies,' it's straightforward and as near to
life as possible.
   ``I feel it's the type of show the public is looking for as
shown by the success of `Our House,''' he said. ``It's about three
generations of family and the problems of the parents and their
families.''
   Wopat and Schneider, and their high powered car, the General
Lee, co-starred in ``Dukes of Hazzard'' for seven seasons beginning
in 1978. Since then, both have gone on to country music careers and
remained in acting.
   He and Schneider just reunited in a holiday special, ``Christmas
Comes to Willow Creek,'' which did well in the ratings. He sees
Schneider six to 10 times a year.
   ``I love him dearly,'' he said. ``He's like a brother. We shared
so much and we were in so many scenes together. We genuinely liked
each other and had the same interests.
   ``We decided from the beginning it was going to be fun and we'd
enjoy it and I think this came across on the screen. It's not
common to have two leading men who got along as we did.''
   Looking back on the highly rated ``Dukes,'' Wopat said it was
popular because it was different.
   ``Until then, urban half-hour comedies were on. We were a new
rural show that was action oriented with some violence and exciting
stunts. It was a calculated approach: a dark-haired boy, a
light-haired boy, a mean old man, a nice old man, a comical old
man, a pretty girl.
   ``It was pure entertainment. Kids could watch it with older
people. There was no cussing and no sex except for (Catherine
Bach's) legs. There was a little moral message once in a while and
it was oriented to family, not like `Dallas' or `Dynasty.'
   ``There were imitators, but we outlasted them all. No show will
ever be seen again like it. The cost is too high.''
   Wopat, who directed some episodes of ``Dukes,'' is selecting
songs now for his second album. The first was ``Tom Wopat: A Little
Bit Closer.'' A cut from the album, ``A Little Bit Closer,'' is the
current release and has zipped up the country music charts.
   Two previous songs have reached the Top 20 on the charts: ``The
Rock and Roll of Love'' and ``Susannah.'' He and his band,
Southwind, do four to eight shows a month.
   Since ``Dukes,'' he has performed in two stage musicals,
``Carousel'' in Washington, and off-Broadway in ``Olympus on My
Mind.''
   He's not done quite as well musically as Schneider, who's had
No. 1 country music songs such as ``I've Been Around Enough to
Know,'' ``What's a Memory Like You (Doing in a Love Like This)''
and ``Country Girls.''
   ``It's been a long and frustrating process except when you have
a passion for it,'' Wopat said about his music career. ``We're
looking for a song to make a big difference _ that big hit that
changes everything.
   ``I'm still in the process of making believers out there in my
commitment to country music. I think I can broaden the base of
country music because of my visibility on TV. I'm optimistic about
my future in country music. I think I'll be here for a long time.''
   Wopat, who was raised on a small dairy farm in Lodi, Wis., says
he watches very little television these days, mostly ``Cheers'' and
reruns of ``The Andy Griffith Show.'' He hasn't seen reruns of
``Dukes of Hazzard'' for a long time.
   ``I have them all on tape. I got one out a while ago and looked
at how I directed it.'
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 4-6</NOTE>
