<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0753EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   02-23 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0382</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES REINDL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Serious Swingers'' (Fantasy) _ Bud Shank and Bill Perkins
   
   Halfway through this record you swear you've heard this music
somewhere before. You have if you listen to Side 1.
   The most noteworthy thing about this album is that it marks only
the second time these two longtime studio musicians have recorded
together. The first time was in 1954.
   However, the title is ``Serious Swingers,'' and this album
doesn't pretend to be any more than a good time _ incidental music
for a Saturday night.
   In the jungle of over-produced pop jazz and fusion albums, there
is a place for people who want to swing, to plow straight ahead in
familar fields. Yet, this record somehow leaves an empty feeling.
All the chops are just right, the solos just free enough that you
know they weren't charted, the mix of ballad and swing ever so
correct.
   A solid rythym section drives Bill Perkins' tenor sax and Bud
Shank's alto.
   But the bottom line is this material has been done before and
better by many. If you want the real thing instead of an homage,
check out early Miles Davis or Thelonious Monk or Charlie Mingus.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Jimmy Rowles-Red Mitchell (Contemporary) _ ``I'm Glad There Is
You''
   
   This is a collection of simply played standards, spare in
phrase, but beautifully executed.
   Jimmy Rowles' lilting piano combines with the delicate brush
work of Colin Bailey on Rodgers and Hammerstein's ``It Might as
Well Be Spring'' to create music mindful of the first scents of
early April.
   On the title track, Rowles brings out the passion those simple
words have exchanged by trusting lovers. Stacy Rowles' charming
trumpet solo to close the piece seconds the emotion.
   Red Mitchell shows his style without imposing on any of the
arrangements with that need that bass players sometimes exhibit to
prove they can do more than keep the beat.
   There is no flash in this record, only clean playing that sets a
pleasant, content mood.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
