<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AirlineStrikes Bjt   02-23 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airline Strikes, Bjt,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Threats, Labor Bitterness at Pan Am, Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the nation's biggest and best-known airlines are facing
strike threats over wages, benefits and concessions that reflect
growing hostility between labor and management in the intensely
competitive deregulated industry.
   Pan Am Corp. and the union representing 4,500 ground employees
in 14 cities remained deadlocked Monday following the breakup of
their talks. Union leaders in New York threatened to call a strike
at any time and vowed ``guerrilla war'' tactics that included
losing passenger bags and canceling reservations.
   At the same time in Minneapolis, flight attendants at Northwest
Airlines voted by a 94.4 percent majority to strike this weekend if
a contract dispute over wages and benefits is not resolved.
   ``The strike authorization of 94.4 percent refects the
deplorable state of labor relations at Northwest Airlines,'' said
Jeff Musto, spokesman for the Teamsters Local 2747 representing
6,500 Northwest attendants.
   Officials at both airlines said managers would replace strikers
in the event of walkouts and predicted minimal disruption. But the
threat of a labor rebellion at Pan Am already appeared to be
discouraging potential passengers.
   ``It's a very bad situation for everybody,'' said David Perlman,
president of DMS Travel in midtown Manhattan. ``Some people are
shying away (from Pan Am flights).''
   Perlman said his agency has been using double bookings as an
insurance technique for customers booked on Pan Am flights. For
passengers taking Pan Am from Kennedy airport to Europe on Monday
night, for example, he also booked them on flights offered by other
airlines to the same destinations.
   The union threats against Pan Am came against a background of
staggering losses for the eighth-largest U.S. airline, which once
dominated overseas travel but has been struggling over the past
several years because of high costs and growing competition from
other carriers, a partial result of airline deregulation a decade
ago.
   Pan Am management has demanded $35 million in concessions from
the Teamsters, who control ground workers at Boston, Detroit,
Chicago, Seattle, San Francisco, San Diego, Los Angeles, Honolulu,
Houston, Washington, New York and the Florida cities of Tampa,
Orlando and Miami.
   Prospects of a strike disruption at Northwest were considered
less severe, partly because flight attendants are the most easily
replaced of all airline workers. But the carrier's machinists and
pilots unions have not said whether they would honor a strike by
flight attendants.
   Northwest and its major unions have been engrossed in talks on
new contracts since the 1986 merger with Republic Airlines, another
result of deregulation, which made Northwest the fifth-biggest U.S.
airline.
   Many former Republic employees are paid less than their
Northwest counterparts, a cause of friction between the airline and
its unions.
   Northwest's latest proposal to the Teamsters offers immediate
elimination of pay gaps between former Northwest and former
Republic flight attendants. The union claims the company is
compensating by reducing vacation pay and retirement benefits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TakeoverLaw Bjt   02-23 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Takeover Law, Bjt,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Thwarts Ohio Takeover Law, Part of Federated's Anti-Campeau
Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio's new anti-takeover law, a key element of
Federated Department Stores Inc.'s strategy to thwart a hostile
acquisition by Canadian developer Campeau Corp., has been
invalidated by a federal judge.
   The ruling Monday by U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin was regarded
as at least a temporary victory for Campeau, which has been
pursuing the Cincinnati-based retailing giant with a takeover offer
valued at $5.4 billion.
   Rubin granted Campeau's request for a preliminary injunction
against the new statute, which was passed as an addition to the
state's existing takeover law. He said the new measure
unconstitutionally discriminated against certain businesses and was
an improper regulation of interstate commerce.
   Mike Webb, a spokesman for the Ohio attorney general's office,
said state officials had not decided whether to appeal the ruling.
A Federated spokesman declined comment.
   Federated stock rose 50 cents a share Monday to $60.75 in active
New York Stock Exchange trading.
   The ruling removed one legal obstacle to Campeau's efforts to
acquire Federated, which has been spurning the Canadian concern's
offers.
   Campeau has a pending $61 a share hostile tender offer, totaling
about $5.4 billion. It also has made an alternative offer to
acquire the retailer for $66 a share, about $5.8 billion, in a
definitive merger agreement.
   The Toronto-based company had indicated the anti-takeover law
could prove to be an impediment in arranging financing for the
acquisition.
   Campeau also has challenged another recently passed
anti-takeover law in Delaware, where Federated is incorporated.
   Rubin said Ohio's law violated federal measures aimed at
avoiding inconsistent regulation of commerce among states.
   The judge said the Ohio law is ``discriminatory on its face''
because it regulates only takeovers by certain businesses organized
in foreign countries. He said federal law prohibits such
discriminatory legislation by states.
   The judge agreed with Campeau attorneys that the Canadian
corporation could suffer irreparable injury because of the law.
   Federated's board of directors on Friday rejected Campeau's $66
a share proposal, saying they were not convinced that Campeau had
solid financing for the deal.
   Federated operates department and mass-merchandising stores in
36 states and had sales of more than $11 billion last year. Its
divisions include Abraham & Straus and Bloomingdale's of New York,
Bullock's and I. Magnin in California, Rich's in Atlanta, Filene's
of Boston and Burdines of Florida.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SantaFe Bjt   02-23 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Santa Fe, Bjt,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henley Proposes Santa Fe Scrap Part of Restructuring, Sell It More
Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. is
pondering a proposal from Henley Group Inc. to scrap part of the
railroad-energy giant's restructuring and sell $780 million in new
stock to the dissident investor.
   The move, which would boost Henley's stake in Chicago-based
Santa Fe to 34.3 percent from 15.7 percent, was announced Monday
and faced an uncertain reaction from Santa Fe, which has been
fending off Henley's unwanted overtures since mid-1987.
   Santa Fe spokesman Robert Gehrt said the proposal would be taken
up at Santa Fe's regularly scheduled board meeting later today but
would not comment further.
   Henley's proposal called for Santa Fe to stop the planned
payment of $5 per share in high-yield ``junk bonds'' for each of
its 157.3 million shares on March 1. Santa Fe already has made a
$25-per-share cash payout.
   Henley has claimed persistently that the pay-in-kind debentures
would leave shareholders with a large tax liability because of the
way they are structured.
   Instead, Henley proposed that Santa Fe sell Henley $780 million
worth of new stock at $17.50 per share. Proceeds from that deal
would be used to make a onetime $5-per-share cash payout to all
current shareholders.
   The proposed deal would mean 44.6 million new shares for Henley
and would boost Santa Fe's total shares outstanding to 201.9
million. But Henley said the proposal was dependent on Santa Fe's
annulment of a ``poison pill'' takeover defense that would make a
hostile acquisition prohibitely expensive.
   Under the measure, if any hostile suitor exceeds 20 percent
ownership in Santa Fe's stock, other Santa Fe shareholders would be
permitted to buy new stock at half price.
   Henley now owns 24.6 million shares, or 15.7 percent, of Santa
Fe, a railroad, land and natural resources concern that has been
attempting to restructure because of federal regulatory rulings
forcing it to sell one of its two railroads, either the Santa Fe
line or Southern Pacific line.
   Together, those lines constitute the nation's third-larges rail
system extending over of 26,000 miles of main track.
   Henley repeatedly has criticized Santa Fe's adoption of the
``poison pill,'' saying the measure restricted the ability of major
holders to maneuver.
   In another development Monday concerning Santa Fe, Denver-based
Rio Grande Industries Inc. filed an application with the Interstate
Commerce Commission to acquire the Southern Pacific line for $1
billion.
   The ICC already has approved an expedited schedule for the
application, with a final decision expected in six months, Rio
Grande said.
   Rio Grande's action threw into question Kansas City Southern
Industries Inc.'s rival bid of more than $1.25 billion for the
Southern Pacific.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BrokerageMerger Bjt   02-23 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brokerage Merger, Bjt,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas Financial Service Company Absorbing Venerable Brokerage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.F. Rothschild Holdings Inc., a venerable
investment firm that once served wealthy clients, later became
dangerously diversified and was devastated by the October stock
market crash, is selling itself to a Kansas company despite earlier
vows to remain independent.
   The announcement on Monday signaled the latest casualty from the
stock collapse and the first major Wall Street firm to be acquired
by a savings and loan company. It also marked the end of an era for
the 89-year-old brokerage, which had been hemorrhaging even before
Black Monday, Oct. 19.
   Since then, several small firms have been forced out of
business, and E.F. Hutton Group Inc., one of the nation's largest
investment firms, agreed in December to be acquired by Shearson
Lehman Brothers Inc.
   Rothschild, which also announced a $128.8 million loss for the
final quarter of 1987, previously had sold virtually all its retail
stock brokerage operations, cut staff by more than 40 percent and
undertaken several other austerity moves.
   The firm said it would merge with Stern Brothers & Co., an
investment bank in Kansas City, Mo. wholly owned by Franklin
Financial Services Inc., which in turn is owned by Franklin Savings
of Ottawa, Kan.
   The purchase price still was subject to adjustment, but
estimated at about $4.40 in cash and securities for each of
Rothschild's 15.1 million shares, or about $66.4 million.
   Franklin's major subsidiary is Franklin Savings Institution,
which had $9 billion in assets at the end of 1987. It also has
brokerage, insurance, mortgage banking and financial consulting
operations.
   ``The merger ... will form a unique investment banking
combination,'' said Ernest Fleischer, chairman of Franklin Savings,
who along with his wife owns just over half of the company's stock.
``It brings together the advantages of a New York trading desk and
regional distribution.''
   ``Our Stern Brothers clients will receive expanded underwriting
and distribution capabilities. For L.F. Rothschild's clients, we
will provide risk management and solid financial backing,'' he said.
   Franklin Financial will provide a 2{-year, $30 million loan to
L.F. Rothschild & Co., the broker-dealer subsidiary of L.F.
Rothschild Holdings, the announcement said
   In a separate announcement, Rothschild Holdings reported severe
losses for both the fourth quarter and all of 1987, reflecting both
the impact of the stock market crash and other troubles.
   Rothschild lost $128.8 million on revenues of $32.5 million in
the quarter, compared with a net loss of $15.4 million on revenues
of $92.4 million in the same period of 1986.
   For the full year, it lost $129.1 million on $461.4 million in
revenues, compared with an after-tax profit of $498,000, or 3 cents
per share, on $401.1 million in revenues in 1986.
   It said approximately $56 million of the losses resulted from
arbitrage and over-the-counter trading positions held during the
stock market's collapse. An additional $15 million in losses
stemmed from the post-crash bankruptcy of Haas Securities, a
correspondent firm of Rothchild's broker-dealer subsidiary.
   In addition, Rothchild said quarterly and annual losses
reflected at least $28 million in charges related to cutbacks in
staff and offices and the sale of its retail brokerage business.
   Once considered a specialty investment banking house that
serviced extremely wealthy clients, Rothschild later evolved into a
publicly held firm that expanded into government bonds, mutual
funds, arbitrage and other areas.
   The company encountered trouble in late 1987, when a management
dispute surfaced over whether the company was becoming excessively
diversified. Two Rothschild principals who opposed diversification
abruptly quit and the firm foundered thereafter.
   Andrew L. Berger, Rothschild's president, had said in a
statement to the press on Dec. 7 that the firm intended to remain
independent, ``get our house in order and as quickly as possible
return this business to profitability.''
   The company has scrapped its public finance and municipal bond
activities and agreed to sell its securities brokerage operations
in New York, Boston, and Tampa, Fla.
   It is in the process of closing offices in San Francisco,
Switzerland and Liechtenstein and is trimming its activities in
London.
</TEXT>
