<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices started the week by moving lower in
aimless trading.
   ``We're really trading on no new news,'' said John H. O'Connell,
an analyst at Refco Inc. Commodities, on Monday. ``Its just a
roller-coaster. Up and down. But I don't think we're falling apart
here.''
   At the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for March
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S.crude,
closed at $16.62 per 42-gallon barrel, down 8 cents from Friday.
   Among March contracts for refined products, wholesale heating
oil settled at 45.79 cents a gallon, down 0.01 cent, while unleaded
gasoline closed down 0.11 cent at 46.32 cents per gallon.
   O'Connell said the market had been rife with stories about
overproduction and other problems within the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries. But he said none of the stories have
been considered reliable.
</TEXT>
