CORRECT to 2.59 trillion yen sted 259 trillion yen. Picks up 5th
graf pvs, Dentsu said ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Money Spent By Japanese Firms On Advertising Increases in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese companies spent 3.945 trillion yen, or
about $30.34 billion, on advertising in 1987, up 8.1 percent from
the previous year and the highest increase in six years, a report
released Tuesday said.
   Dentsu Inc., the country's largest advertising agency, said the
increase reflected the recovery of the Japanese economy led by
rising domestic demand, and Japanese firms' efforts to expand their
doemstic business activities.
   The previous highest annual increase was 8.2 percent in 1981,
although the standard for the survey was modifieid in 1985 by
eliminating advertising for promoting exports, Dentsu said.
   Corporate spending on advertisements in newspapers and magazines
and on radio and television was 259 trillion yen, or about $19.95
billion, up 7.7 percent from 1986, Dentsu said. That accounted for
65.7 percent of total advertising expenses.
   Dentsu said advertising through direct mail, outdoor ad
services, inserts and exhibitions was 1.344 trillion yen, or $10.3
billion.
</TEXT>
