<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Kodak-Sterling     02-23 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak-Sterling,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Completes Acquisition of Sterling Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. completed its effort to
buy Sterling Drug Co. today by acquiring more than 96 percent of
Sterling's stock during the 20-day tender offer, a Kodak spokesman
said.
   Kodak acquired about 54.5 million shares of Sterling stock by
the midnight Monday deadline and will now complete the merger ``in
the matter of a few days,'' said Kodak spokesman Ron Roberts.
   The acquisition, the largest in Kodak history, has attracted a
great deal of criticism from stock analysts who said Kodak was
paying too much for the drug and household products company.
   Kodak had agreed to pay $89.50 a share for the 57 million
outstanding shares of Sterling stock, which is more than $34 higher
than the stock was selling for at the end of 1987. The total value
of the deal is expected to be $5.1 billion.
   Sterling, based in New York, has 22,000 employees and has annual
sales of about $2 billion.
   Kodak, based in Rochester, has 124,000 employees and annual
sales of about $13 billion a year.
   The acquisition will help Kodak move into the $110 billion
pharmaceutical industry and give the company an established
pipeline to get drugs to market, said Kodak spokesman Charles Smith.
   But analysts have cast a wary eye on the deal with several no
longer recommending the purchase of Kodak stock.
   On Monday, Kodak's bond rating was downgraded by Moody's
Investor's Service from A2 to Aa2 largely because of the impending
$5.1 billion loan the company is going to have to take on to pay
for Sterling.
   Sterling's bond rating was also downgraded from A2 to Aa1.
   With the acquisition, Kodak gets a business featuring such
familiar brand names as Bayer aspirin, Panadol non-aspirin pain
reliever, Lysol disinfectant, d-Con rat killer, and Phillips Milk
of Magnesia.
   Kodak officials have said they do not plan to sell any parts of
Sterling and will keep the company's organization intact.
</TEXT>
