<HEAD>Matsushita To Open New U.S. Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Corp., one of the
world's largest consumer electronics manufacturers, has announced
plans to set up a new firm in the United States in April for sales
and maintainance of factory automation machines, a Japanese news
report said.
   The new firm, Panasonic Factory Automation Co., a division of
Matsushita Electric Corp. of America, will pave the way for
Matsushita's further expansion of factory automation business in
North America and localization of the development of computer
software used for factory automation, Kyodo News Service said
Tuesday.
   Matsushita officials did not answer repeated telephone calls to
their offices Tuesday night.
   Sales of factory automation equipment have been handled by
Panasonic Industrial Co., but the rapid growth of the factory
automation market in North America led the parent company to set up
a new firm dedicated solely to that purpose, Kyodo said.
   Panansonic Factory Automation Co., which will sell industrial
robots and installation devices for electronics parts, aims to
boost its sales of 6.5 billion yen, or $58 million, in the fiscal
year ending March 31, 1988 _ and by five times within five years,
Kyodo said.
