<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were narrowly mixed this morning
after pushing to their highest levels in six weeks in the previous
session.
   Trading was more active than in Monday's session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which jumped 25.70
points on Monday to its highest level since Jan. 7, backed off 1.33
to 2,038.96 after 90 minutes of trading.
   But advancing issues took a slight lead over losers in the
overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 639
up, 584 down and 512 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 81.94 million shares as of 11
a.m. on Wall Street compared with 52.26 million shares at the same
point on Monday.
   The stock market has benefited recently from indications that
the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some
analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate
profits.
   But there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects.
   In a new report today, the government said orders to U.S.
factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in January, the
biggest decline in a year.
   But that statistic has been volatile, and many analysts expected
a decline in January because it had risen by an unusually large 4.1
percent in December.
   Stock traders were also looking to today's congressional
testimony by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   Greenspan said the country faces ``formidable challenges'' in
keeping the economic recovery alive, urged further progress on
reducing the federal deficit and cautioned Congress against passing
protectionist trade legislation.
