<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Brokers-NYSE     02-23 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brokers-NYSE,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Specialists Surrender Market-Making Roles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two stock specialist firms have agreed to give
up their roles as market-makers in three stocks, the New York Stock
Exchange said.
   The moves are part of a review of the performance of specialists
during the October stock market crash, the exchange said in a press
release Monday.
   The Big Board said that Lawrence, O'Donnell & Co. would
surrender its market-making role in Neiman-Marcus Group Inc. common
stock next week. La Branche & Co. will give up its rights to market
E.F. Hutton Group Inc. and A.G. Edwards Inc. on March 3.
   The franchises in the affected issues will be reallocated by the
exchange, NYSE officials said. In the case of E.F. Hutton, a large
securities firm due to be merged with Shearson Lehman Brothers
Holdings Inc., the stock is expected to be delisted by the exchange
around March 24.
   The exchange's 53 specialist firms each control lucrative
franchises to market certain stocks and are required to maintain
orderly trading in those issues by setting opening prices and
covering trades when there are too few buyers or sellers.
   Following the crash, the exchange launched investigations into
the volatile behavior of some issues and the specialists assigned
to them. The activity of market specialists also was criticized by
a presidential task force and the Securities and Exchange
Commission in their separate probes of the October collapse.
   The NYSE said the agreements with Lawrence, O'Donnell and
LaBranche were reached voluntarily after discussions with the firms.
   In the case of LaBranche, the exchange's review centered on the
firm's handling of Hutton stock, but because of the imminent
delisting of that issue, the firm also agreed to accept the
withdrawal of its Edwards franchise as a penalty, the exchange
indicated.
   The exchange did not disclose the results of its investigations
into the trading of Hutton and Neiman-Marcus stock, but extreme
volatility appeared to have prompted the inquiries.
   The NYSE has taken action in four situations since the crash.
Previously, Spear, Leeds & Kellogg surrendered its franchise in
J.P. Morgan & Co. stock and J.J. Meehan & Co. withdrew its rights
to Gould Inc.
   Exchange officials would not say whether its inquiries into the
activity of specialists were continuing, but NYSE Chairman John
Phelan has told congressional investigators that reallocations of
stock franchises was one means of repairing the damage caused by
the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880223-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-23 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean futures succumbed to follow-through selling from
Monday's weak close and to reports of improved growing conditions
for the South American crop, analysts said.
   Wheat prices fell in reaction to the Agriculture Department's
announcement that it plans more auctions of surplus wheat in
addition to the weekly auctions that have been a fixture since
November, analysts said.
   The auctions increase the supply of wheat on the open market,
which tends to depress prices.
   Corn futures prices retreated on a lack of bullish fundamentals
and on lower-than-expected exports last week, said Jerry Gidel, an
analyst for G.H. Miller & Co.
   Last week's wheat exports also were lower than expected, while
soybean shipments were above expectations, Gidel said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.21 a bushel; corn was } cent
to 2 cents lower with March $1.98{ a bushel; oats were \ cent 1}
cents lower with March at $1.90{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to
4{ cents lower with March at $6.25 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .22 cent to .55 cent lower with April at 72.27
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .92 cent lower with
March at 81.60 cents a pound; hogs were .17 cent to .45 cent lower
with April at 43.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40
cent to .57 cent lower with March at 53.15 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed lower Monday while pork futures advanced.
</TEXT>
