<HEAD>Stock Prices Pull Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back this morning, as the
market ran into resistance in active trading after pushing to its
highest levels in six weeks in the previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which jumped 25.70
points on Monday to its highest level since Jan. 7, was off 12.60
at 2,027.69 at noon on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of nearly 3 to 2
in the overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
558 up, 802 down and 480 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 112.65 million shares as of
noontime compared with 52.26 million shares at the same point on
Monday.
   The stock market has benefited recently from indications that
the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some
analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate
profits.
   But there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects.
   In a new report today, the government said orders to U.S.
factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in January, the
biggest decline in a year.
   Many analysts had expected a decline in January, however,
because orders had risen by an unusually large 4.1 percent in
December.
   Stock traders were also looking to today's congressional
testimony by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who told a
House subcommittee that the country faces ``formidable challenges''
in keeping the economic recovery alive.
   Charles Jensen, a technical market analyst for MKI Securities
Corp., said the market's decline was ``a reflex reaction after
pretty good runup'' over the past two weeks.
   ``The market is in a mature rallying phase subject to these
short bouts of profit-taking,'' Jensen said, adding that he felt
the market ``could regroup and work its way higher'' later.
   Among the most active issues on the NYSE, Philadelphia Electric
was unchanged at 19~, Eastman Kodak was down \ at 40{, Polaroid was
up 1\ at 31\ and International Business Machines was off \ at 115.
   Texaco was unchanged at 42{ after saying it had agreed to pay
the government $1.25 billion to settle an oil pricing dispute.
Other opil stocks were lower, with Amoco off 1\ at 76, Atlantic
Richfield down ] at 78| and Mobil was down } at 44\.
   Moore McCormick climbed 10~ to 34} after Southdown disclosed it
was offering $31 a share for the company.
   IU International rose 1] to 21\. The company said it received a
buyout offer of $21.50 a share, topping an earlier $20 a share
offer that the company had called inadequate.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.98 at 147.98. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index fell 0.89 to 282.12.
</TEXT>
