<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NBC-TBS     02-23 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NBC-TBS,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Not Likely To Sell Programming To TBS' Proposed Cable Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the NBC television network
indicated NBC is unlikely to sell programming to Turner
Broadcasting System Inc.'s proposed new cable network, unless NBC
owned a portion of the parent company.
   Last year, NBC and TBS discussed the possibility of NBC taking
part ownership of Atlanta-based TBS. But the companies announced in
mid-January that the talks had been halted.
   NBC President Robert Wright said Monday the network would be
interested in helping program the proposed Turner Network
Television only if it owned a piece of TBS.
   ``We could be very interested in selling programming to it, but
I just don't see that happening,'' Wright said after speaking to a
civic group in Atlanta. ``The problem with TNT is that it is very
much involved in the organizational, ownership issues'' that
blocked NBC's attempt to buy an interest in TBS last year, he added.
   NBC reportedly had attempted for the second time in three years
to purchase up to 25 percent of TBS for $400 million.
   TBS is hoping to launch the new cable network in July. TNT is
proposed as a super cable channel that would compete with the
networks by offering first-run mini-series, award shows and major
sporting events.
</TEXT>
