<1ST_LINE>s f BC-JapaneseBuyers-Prices Adv28   02-23 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japanese Buyers-Prices, Adv 28,0540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Feb 28 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Real Estate Investors Evoke Smiles, Groans From Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Japanese Buyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese who invest in U.S. real estate evoke
mixed emotions on this continent, angering Americans competing to
buy the same properties but pleasing sellers.
   ``They have come into the market with a tremendous new source of
capital, and prices have gone up on the very small, upper-tier of
properties they're interested in,'' said Jon Minikes, a managing
director at Jones, Lang, Wootton USA, an international real estate
firm headquartered in New York.
   Among those ``upper-tier'' properties are New York's Exxon
building, which was sold to Mitsui Fudosan for $610 million; the
Arco Towers in Los Angeles, which sold for $620 million to Shuwa
Investments Corp.; and the Equitable building in Dallas, for which
Nissei Realty paid $250 million.
   ``Whenever more money is chasing a good product, prices have to
go up. It's very simple economics,'' he said.
   But Americans who expected to pay less for quality commercial
property in major cities ``are upset with the Japanese,'' said
David Shulman, director of real estate research at Salomon Brothers
Inc., while ``building sellers are very happy.''
   Shulman estimated that prices for quality office buildings could
drop by as much as 10 percent to 15 percent if the Japanese ceased
buying property or became less aggressive in their purchases.
   Japanese can afford to pay more because they are guaranteed to
reap far greater yields in the United States than at home.
   For example, a $100 million investment in Japan would probably
yield 1 or 2 percent a year, said Jim Montinari, senior vice
president of Cushman & Wakefield, a national commercial real estate
firm. Yield is what investors earn after they subtract expenses
from rent collected.
   But the yield on the same $100 million investment in U.S. real
estate ``is certain to be 6 to 9 percent. Comparing oppportunity to
Japan versus the United States is anywhere from triple to more,''
he said.
   In Japan, high-quality commercial real estate appreciated
between 50 percent and 60 percent in price from 1985 to 1986,
shutting out potential investors from their domestic market and
turning their attention to the United States, where prices for
comparable properties rose about 15 percent, Shulman said.
   The fall in the value of the dollar against the yen also has
lured Japanese investors, but a cheaper dollar can be ``a
double-edged sword,'' Minikes said.
   ``Most Japanese investors are looking at the rise in value of
the yen as a way to make the purchase cheaper, but you realize that
if the yen keeps rising, their investment _ which is generating
U.S. dollars _ will show a lower yield, he explained.
   While some Americans are miffed at the cash-rich Japanese
companies that are snapping up top properties at top dollar, real
estate companies have adapted to serve a new market.
   ``We constantly have groups coming through who want us to tell
them about U.S. real estate,'' Minikes said. ``We regard them as a
continuing source of profitable business.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Feb 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
