<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BritishBank     02-23 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-British Bank,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Westminster Bank's 1987 Profit Plummets 30.1 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Westminster Bank PLC, Britain's largest
bank, said Tuesday its profit sank 30.1 percent last year, mainly
as a result of higher provisions against loans to Latin American
countries and heavy losses at its investment bank.
   The bank said its 1987 earnings totaled 429 million pounds, or
$759 million, down from 614 million pounds, or $1.09 billion in
1986. On a per-share basis, that worked out to 57 pence, or $1 per
share in 1987, compared with 94 pence, or $1.66 in 1986.
   The bank said its provisions against loans to lesser developed
countries, including Brazil, Mexico and other Latin American
countries, now total 810 million pounds, or $1.43 billion _ 33
percent of its total exposure of 2.47 billion pounds, or $4.37
billion.
   Natwest raised its provisions against loans to lesser developed
countries to 30 percent last summer, and later by another 3
percent, to keep it within guidelines set up by the Bank of England.
   Natwest's international banking unit swung to a loss of 339
million pounds, or $600 million, from a profit of 223 million
pounds, or $395 million, because of the increased provisions and
the lower dollar.
   The group's investment banking division widened its loss to 116
million pounds, or $205 million last year, from 38 million pounds,
or $67 million in 1986. Natwest blamed continuing development costs
and the effects of the October stock market's crash.
   National Westminster Bank USA had a loss of 95 million pounds,
or $168 million, after increasing its provision for loans to lesser
developed countries to 35 percent. That loss compared with a profit
of 68 million pounds, or $120 million, in 1986.
   Natwest said its results were encouraging in the light of the
experience of banks worldwide in 1987.
</TEXT>
