<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Europe-Takeover 1stLd-Writethru f0095 02-23 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Takeover, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0095,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Met Acting Belgian Prime Minister</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with meeting with economics
minister</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti
and Belgium's economics minister on Tuesday called for a truce in
the battle for control of Societe Generale de Belgique S.A., the
country's biggest holding company.
   ``Representative shareholders have to sit down at the table to
discuss clear-cut principles: an industrial plan, the modalities of
efficient management and a revitalization of the company,'' De
Benedetti said in a statement.
   De Benedetti, the largest independent stockholder, claims to own
43 percent of Societe Generale's 28.2 million shares outstanding.
He has launched a bid for another 15 percent, but the stock price
has since exceeded his offer of about 4,000 Belgian francs.
   Societe Generale hit a new record Tuesday, closing at 5,350
francs, or $152.80, up about $7.15 from Monday.
   De Benedetti held meetings Tuesday with several top government
officials, including Minister of Economy Philippe Maystadt,
caretaker Prime Minister Wilfried Martens and Vice-Premiers Guy
Verhofstadt and Philippe Maystadt.
   De Benedetti wants to create a pan-European holding company, but
the Belgian government has maintained it wants Societe Generale to
remain firmly anchored in Belgium. The 166-year-old company
controls about half of Belgium's top 50 companies and has interests
in more that 1,200 companies worldwide.
   As speculation mounts as to whether a brittle alliance of
Belgian and French financial groups could fend off De Benedetti,
the Italian financier called for a truce.
   ``As the most important shareholder by a wide margin, I want to
make an appeal to reason,'' De Benedetti said. ``There have been
enough maneuvers in the corridors, enough artificial coalitions,
enough unrealistic share counts, enough projects inspired only on
the basis of personal interest.''
   Maystadt also said that it would be ``desirable that all
concerned parties without exception at last sit down around the
same table.''
   The French Cie Financiere de Suez and about 18 Belgian companies
claim to hold more than 50 percent of Societe Generale's shares,
but they have not officially agreed to form an alliance.
   Societe Generale management has supported a Franco-Belgian
alliance.
</TEXT>
