<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1502EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0014 02-23 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with trading activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher in London Tuesday, but
were down sharply from their best levels in concert with weak early
trading on Wall Street.
   Trading volume picked up from its recent slack pace as some good
institutional buying interest emerged, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished at
1,757.9, 10.7 points or 0.6 percent higher, just 1.2 points above
its lowest level for the day. The index rose as much as 25 points
in early trading, bolstered by strong gains overnight in the New
York and Tokyo stock markets.
   The strong tone was reinforced by news that Britain's real gross
domestic product rose 1 percent in the fourth quarter of 1987 from
the third quarter and was up 5.3 percent from a year earlier.
   Share prices showed little reaction to the GDP news, but dealers
said the figures should help sustain a cautious optimism among
market participants.
   Dealers said another factor boosting the market was expectations
that substantial tax cuts would be included in the budget to be
presented next month by the Thatcher government.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said the government has
agreed to give up its golden share in Britoil PLC, clearing the way
for the independent company's takeover by British Petroleum Co.
PLC. Britoil shares rose 1 penny to 499 pence, while BP was
unchanged at 248 pence.
</TEXT>
