<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-23 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed
moderately lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures declined in reaction to the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Monday that it would replace its
weekly auctions of surplus wheat with three weekly auctions
beginning March 2, analysts said.
   Sales from the Friday auctions have declined in recent weeks,
with last week's total of 11 million bushels falling far short of
the target of 25 million bushels.
   The USDA set initial targets of 10 million bushels for each of
the three new auctions, which will be held on Tuesdays, Wednesdays
and Fridays.
   Traders fear that the new auctions could put as much as 30
million additional bushels of wheat onto the open market, which
would tend to depress prices, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst for G.H.
Miller & Co.
   Soybean prices retreated in response to improved growing
conditions for the South American soybean crop, Gidel said. Corn
futures drifted lower due to a lack of fresh supportive news, he
said.
   At the close, wheat was 4} cents to 5\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.17 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 3{ cents lower with March at $1.96 a bushel; oats were 1 cent
lower to \ cent higher with March at $1.90\ a bushel; soybeans were
3{ cents to 8{ cents lower with March at $6.20 a bushel.
</TEXT>
