<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AppleLeak     02-23 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apple Leak,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Reveals Details of Long-Awaited Apple Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer magazine has published a
story providing confidential details of a long-awaited Apple
computer still under development.
   The article appearing in this week's edition of Macintosh Today
was based on a 160-page confidential in-house document given to a
free-lance writer by an Apple employee, the San Francisco Examiner
said Tuesday.
   The article details the size, appearance and technical
specifications of Apple Computer Inc.'s Laguna laptop model, which
it said would be available in 1989.
   Apple has been hard hit by information leaks before, and even
hired a private detective two years ago to find out who was
releasing information. The investigator found leaks at firms
developing software and accessories for Apple products, according
to company spokeswoman Barbara Krause.
   Ms. Krause declined to comment on the magazine report.
   The article describes a 12-pound laptop capable of running
Macintosh software. It said the computer would have 1 megabyte of
internal memory, the same as the Macintosh SE. It said the computer
would have a flat-panel screen and be powered by a five-pound
lead-acid battery that will last up to 10 hours before recharging.
</TEXT>
