<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0732EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-EEC-ForeignMinisters     02-23 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Foreign Ministers,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministers Formally Adopted Summit Budget Accords</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of the European
Economic Community on Monday formally adopted decisions taken at
last week's EEC summit on limiting farm subsidies and overhauling
the group's finances.
   Britain and the Netherlands had made their acceptance of the
summit agreement conditional on settlement of a relatively minor
issue raised by France in the final stages of the Feb. 11-12
meeting.
   Officials said the French foreign minister, Jean-Bernard
Raimond, told Monday's meeting that his government remained unhappy
with proposals for placing new controls on EEC subsidies to growers
of such products as tobacco and wine.
   But Raimond said Paris would allow the proposals to go forward
without further debate. That cleared the way for the foreign
ministers to formally adopt the overall summit agreement.
   By satisfying British and Dutch demands for strict limits on
farm spending, the summit accords marked a breakthrough in the
EEC's budget crisis. The 12-nation group has been operating without
a formal budget since the start of the year and faced possible
bankruptcy by late summer.
   EEC budget ministers are scheduled to meet Tuesday to adopt a
draft 1988 budget. The spending plan then must be approved by the
European Parliament.
   Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the West German foreign minister and
chairman of Monday's meeting, told reporters that adoption of the
summit agreement was ``an important step forward in the history of
the European Community.''
   Genscher said he and Chancellor Helmut Kohl told U.S. officials
during a visit to Washington last week that the summit agreement
will ``strengthen the economic vitality of Europe'' by permitting
faster removal of trade barriers between EEC member countries and
by giving more financial aid to the relatively poorer members in
southern Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
