<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     02-23 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0199</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market marked time today, finishing
narrowly mixed as its recent rally ran into some resistance.
   Analysts said the market had paused after a two-week rally that
had driven some major indicators to their highest levels in six
weeks.
   They said traders also appeared hesitant to make a major move
while Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan was outlining for a
congressional panel the central bank's monetary goals and his view
of the economy.
   The analysts found little in Greenspan's remarks to encourage
them to bid stocks in either direction.
   The stock market has benefited recently from indications that
the economy may be stronger than had been expected, leading some
analysts to take an optimistic view of the outlook for corporate
profits.
   But there is plenty of uncertainty about the economy's prospects.
   In a new report today, the government said orders to U.S.
factories for durable goods plunged 2.8 percent in January, the
biggest decline in a year.
   But a decline had been expected in the wake of an unusually
sharp 4.1 percent rise in December.
</TEXT>
