<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0734EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-Nissan     02-23 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nissan,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan Asked To Expand Production At Tennessee Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at the Nissan Motor Co. plant
in Smyrna are recommending expanded production at the plant that
could include a second passenger car line, the company stated
Monday.
   However, the plant is not among the sites under consideration
for a proposed joint venture with Ford Motor Co. to build a new
vehicle, company officials said.
   Nissan Motor Co. announced that it would undertake a second
phase of a study on the proposed joint venture and that a proposal
would be made for top management review in May.
   A study committee indicated a site had not been selected yet but
the Smyrna facility _ which makes light trucks and Sentra cars, was
not among those being considered.
   ``The joint venture project with Ford is looking at building a
type of vehicle that is very different from the cars and trucks we
build at Smyrna,'' said Jerry Benefield, president and chief
executive officer of the Smyrna plant.
   But officials said plant production may be expanded anyhow
because of a proposed addition of a second passenger car line, and
parts production may be increased.
   Benefield said he was recommending that the plant begin making
three components: Sentra engines, truck axles, and front and rear
bumpers for the Sentra. The new production would not require any
new employees, officials said.
   The company also is considering adding a second passenger car
line at the plant, which would require a larger work force.
   The company's board of directors will review the proposals at an
April meeting.
</TEXT>
