<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 0636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Firestone     02-23 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Firestone,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 27 Percent Decline in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. reported a 27 percent
drop in first-quarter earnings Monday, but noted results for the
year-earlier period were inflated by a $20 million gain from
discontinued operations.
   Firestone reported earnings of $30 million or 94 cents a share,
on sales of $976 million for the three months ended Jan. 31,
compared with earnings of $41 million or $1.07 a share on sales of
$846 million during the same period a year ago.
   Excluding a one-time gain of $20 million from the December 1986
sale of its North American wheel and rim business, Firestone's
first-quarter earnings were up 40 percent from a year earlier.
   The results reflected improved automotive parts and service
sales, increased income from credit-card operations, and larger
profits from the company's diverisified-products operations due to
higher natural-rubber prices and improved building-products sales,
Firestone said in a news release.
   During the quarter, Firestone repurchased 3.6 million shares of
its outstanding stock for $116 million.
   Firestone, which moved its headquarters from Akron, Ohio, to
Chicago during the quarter, announced last week it would sell a 75
percent interest in its tire-manufacturing operations to
Bridgestone Corp. for $1.25 billion.
</TEXT>
