<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   02-23 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0493</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. and the union representing 4,500
ground employees in 14 cities deadlocked following the breakup of
their talks as a Teamsters official threatened ``guerrilla
warfare.''
   William Genoese, director of the Teamsters' airline division,
threatened Monday that employees meanwhile would deliberately
misdirect baggage and cargo and cancel passengers' reservations.
   Talks in which management was seeking $35 million in concessions
from the union broke down Sunday afternoon following expiration of
the contract. No talks were held Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flight attendants at Northwest Airlines have
voted overwhelmingly to strike the airline this weekend if a
contract dispute over wages and benefits is not resolved, a union
official says.
   Disclosure of the strike vote came Monday as the two sides
readied to resume negotiations for the first time since last month.
   Jeff Musto, a Teamsters spokesman, said 94.4 percent of the more
than 5,000 attendants participating voted to strike.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.F. Rothschild Holdings Inc., an investment
firm staggered by October's stock market crash, will merge with a
subsidiary of Franklin Savings Corp., a financial services company
based in Ottawa, Kan.
   Rothschild, which also announced a $128.8 million loss for the
final quarter of 1987, previously had sold virtually all of its
retail stock brokerage operations and slashed its payroll.
   The purchase price, still subject to adjustment, was about $66.4
million, Rothschild said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp. has run full-page
advertisements in local newspapers blaming shrinking deposits on
seasonal factors and foreign withdrawals and repeating denials that
it was involved in merger or bailout negotiations.
   The bank's actions Monday were designed to allay depositors'
fears raised by its report last month of a $656.8 million annual
loss. It said news reports on its financial condition were wrong or
misleading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident investor Henley Group Inc. has
proposed that Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. scrap part of its
financial restructuring and instead sell $780 million in new stock
to Henley.
   The move Monday, which would boost Henley's stake in
Chicago-based Santa Fe to 34.3 percent from 15.7 percent, was
expected to receive a cool reaction from Santa Fe, which has been
fending off Henley's unwanted overtures since mid-1987.
   Santa Fe directors will take up the plan at a regularly
scheduled board meeting Tuesday, spokesman Robert Gehrt said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rio Grande Industries Inc. has filed an
application with the Interstate Commerce Commission to acquire
Southern Pacific Transportation Co. for $1 billion from Santa Fe
Southern Pacific Corp.
   Rio Grande's action Monday will affect Kansas City Southern
Industries Inc.'s rival bid of more than $1.25 billion for the
Southern Pacific.
   The ICC is expected to decide on the application in six months,
Rio Grande said.
</TEXT>
