<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   02-23 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0473</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has blocked as
unconstitutional an Ohio takeover statute aimed at thwarting
Campeau Corp.'s attempted hostile takeover of Federated Department
Stores Inc.
   Toronto-based Campeau has a hostile $5.4 billion offer pending
for Cincinnati-based Federated. Campeau is offering $5.8 billion if
Federated agrees to a friendly merger.
   State officials have not decided whether to appeal Monday's
ruling, a spokesman said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government posted a rare $16.09
billion surplus last month, primarily because Social Security
checks for January were mailed early, the Treasury Department says.
   The early payment inflated government spending in December and
lowered spending in January, the department said Monday. The
December deficit was $24.22 billion.
   For all of 1988, the Reagan administration is projecting the
budget deficit will fall to $146.74 billion, down 2.5 percent from
last year's deficit of $150.4 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has confirmed it is
investigating allegations that a U.S. computer system which could
help determine optimal targets for nuclear missiles had been
illegally shipped to the Soviet Union.
   According to a report in Monday editions of the Washington
Times, Essex Marketing Co. of Los Angeles is under investigation
for an alleged shipment Dec. 21 of the computer to an engineering
college in Zagreb, Yugoslovia.
   The computer was diverted and wound up in the Soviet Union
instead, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has upheld a ruling that
sharply curtails the power of communities to regulate cable
television.
   The high court turned away an appeal by Palo Alto and Atherton,
Calif., which wanted to enforce public access and other rules
challenged by cable operator Century Federal Inc.
   But the court's action apparently was based on narrow procedural
grounds and leaves open the possibility of a subsequent appeal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of 226 large and medium-sized
American companies found 70 percent have restricted or are prepared
to limit smoking in the workplace.
   ``I was really surprised at the extent to which this had
surfaced as a personnel issue,'' Victor Lindquist, author of the
Northwestern University Lindquist-Endicott Report, said Monday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained broadly Monday, extending its recent
rally in a mood of increasing optimism about the economic outlook.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.70 to 2,040.29.
   Bond prices finished modestly higher. The yield on the
Treasury's closely watched 30-year issue, which moves inversely to
its price, slipped to 8.41 percent from 8.43 percent late Friday.
   The dollar drifted lower. Gold prices were narrowly mixed.
   Cotton futures prices collapsed; grains and soybeans were mostly
lower; and livestock and meat were mixed.
</TEXT>
