<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1843EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Kodak 1stLd-Writethru   02-23 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak, 1st Ld-Writethru,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Completes Purchase of Sterling Drug</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, In the ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with stock
prices, specify that judge's ruling was Monday; picks up 5th graf
pvs, The suit ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has issued a temporary
injunction blocking Eastman Kodak Co.'s deal to merge its
photofinishing operations with those of Fuqua Industries Inc., and
the company continues to face questions about its $5.1 billion
acquisition of Sterling Drug Inc.
   Kodak announced Tuesday that it had been tendered more than 96
percent of Sterling shares during the offering period that expired
Monday, and said it expected to complete the acquisition in a few
days.
   The company has scheduled a meeting with analysts Thursday in
New York in an effort to convince them of the merits of the
Sterling deal.
   Kodak's stock rose 50 cents a shre to $41.25 a share Tuesday in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. Fuqua's stock fell 50
cents a share to $28.50.
   In the Fuqua dispute, U.S. District Judge Eldon Mahon in Fort
Worth, Texas, issued his ruling Monday in response to a suit filed
in December by Phototron Corp., a San Bernardino, Calif., wholesale
photofinishing company.
   The suit contended that if the proposed merger went through,
Kodak and Fuqua would control 50 percent of the wholesale
photofinishing industry and 80 percent of the total market for
photo-related paper and chemicals, said Brenda Landry, an analyst
for Morgan Stanley and Co.
   The injunction will remain in effect pending a trial on the
merits of the case.
   Fuqua spokeswoman Donna Browning, in arguments supporting the
merger, said the merger would result in a new company controlling
only 25 percent of the total photofinishing market in the United
States.
   The Federal Trade Commission and the U.S. Department of Justice
antitrust division approved the proposed merger in December and
said their investigation did not show any evidence that federal
antitrust laws would be violated.
   On Dec. 7, Kodak announced plans to merge its wholesale
photoprocessing laboratories with Fuqua's Raleigh, N.C.-based
subsidiary, Colorcraft Corp.
   Several financial analysts have lowered their opinions of Kodak
in recent weeks on grounds that the company overpaid for Sterling.
   ``Obviously there are pros and cons to this,'' said Michael
Ellmann, a stock analyst with Wertheim Schroeder & Co. ``But I want
to hear what management has to say.''
   Kodak will pay $89.50 for 54.5 million of the 57 million
outstanding shares of Sterling stock, more than $34 higher than the
stock was selling for at the end of 1987. The company will acquire
the 2.5 million shares that weren't offered for sale for the same
price after the deal is final, Roberts said.
   The total value of the deal is expected to be $5.1 billion.
   Sterling, based in New York, has 22,000 employees and has annual
sales of about $2 billion.
   Kodak, based in Rochester, has 124,000 employees and annual
sales of about $13 billion a year.
   The acquisition will help Kodak move into the $110 billion
pharmaceutical industry and give the company an established
pipeline to get drugs to market, said Kodak spokesman Charles Smith.
   On Monday, Kodak's bond ratings were downgraded by Moody's
Investors Service from A2 to Aa2 largely because of the heavy
borrowing needed to pay for Sterling.
   Sterling's bond rating was also downgraded from A2 to Aa1.
   With the acquisition, Kodak will immediately realize its
ambition of being a billion-dollar-a-year drug company through
Bayer aspirin, Panadol non-aspirin pain reliever, and Demerol.
   Kodak will also get a billion-dollar-a-year household products
business with such products as Lysol disinfectant, d-Con rat
killer, and Phillips Milk of Magnesia.
   Kodak officials have said they do not plan to sell any parts of
Sterling and will keep the company's organization intact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
