<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2330EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-NewsCorp     02-23 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-News Corp,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Corp. Posts 45 Percent Profit Gain in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News Corp. Ltd., the worldwide media company
controlled by Rupert Murdoch, said Tuesday its profit climbed 45
percent in its second fiscal quarter as its revenue rose 33 percent.
   The company, based in Sydney, Australia, cited strong
performances by its newspaper division in Britain and its magazine
division in Australia and the Pacific Basin, including results from
acquisitions.
   It said profits declined in the United States, reflecting a soft
advertising market for its seven television stations, disappointing
results from the newspaper division including the New York Post and
lower results from Twentieth Century Fox Films.
   News Corp. said its profit rose to $127 million, or 79 cents per
American Depositary Receipt, in the three months ended Dec. 31
compared with $87.6 million, or 64 cents per ADR, a year earlier.
   The ADRs are traded on the New York Stock Exchange and each ADR
represents two of the company's common shares.
   Revenue for the quarter rose to $1.11 billion from $837 million
a year earlier.
   For the first six months, profit nearly doubled to $231.2
million, or $1.42 per ADR, from $120 million, or 88 cents per ADR,
a year earlier.
   Revenue for the first six months rose 26 percent, to $2.09
billion from $1.66 billion in 1986.
   Six-month results were helped by foreign-exchange trading gains
and acquisitions in Australia and the Pacific Basin.
   Last weekend, Murdoch won concessions from the New York Post's
labor unions that cleared the way for the sale of the ailing
newspaper to real estate developer Peter Kalikow for $37 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
