<DOCNO> AP880223-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2347EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-IceCreamSuit     02-23 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ice Cream Suit,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kraft To Pay $8.5 Million To Settle Ice Cream Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. will pay Ambrit Inc. $8.5 million to
settle a trademark battle over similar ice cream bars made by the
two companies, Kraft announced Tuesday.
   The 6-year-old case stemmed from Kraft's Polar B'ar ice cream
bars, which Ambrit contended were packaged in a manner that
infringed on the trademark of its own Klondike bar.
   The Supreme Court last May let stand a lower court ruling
prohibiting Polar B'ar from using a wrapper resembling the Klondike
package and denying Polar B'ar exclusive trademark rights to that
name.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals had ruled in December
1986 that Polar B'ars may not have images of polar bears on their
wrappers in imitation of the Klondike design.
   The appeals court also said Polar B'ars may have the color royal
blue on their silver foil wrappers only if it did not make them
``confusingly similar'' to the Klondike wrapper.
   The appeals court also had ordered a federal judge to determine
what damages if any Kraft must pay Ambrit, which is based in
Clearwater, Fla., for imitating the Klondike wrapper.
   Kraft said from its Glenview, Ill., headquarters that the
settlement was ``significantly less'' than the amount sought by
Ambrit but declined to comment further, citing agreements by both
parties not to discuss specifics of the case.
   The appeals court had canceled Kraft's Polar B'ar trademark
because the company had abandoned the name from 1932, when it
stopped making a like-named ice cream novelty, until it began
marketing a new ice cream bar in 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
