<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   02-23 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0189</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the Japanese yen in
foreign exchange dealings in Tokyo Wednesday after a sharp decline
the previous day, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
were mixed.
   The dollar opened at 128.90 yen, up 0.40 yen from Tuesday's
close of 128.50 yen. In midmorning dealings, the U.S. currency
traded between 128.65 and 128.90 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which rose Tuesday for the ninth consecutive
trading day, took on an additional 0.09 points to end Wednesday's
morning session at 24,949.54.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the market didn't respond to
comments by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who told
a U.S. congressional committee Tuesday that there were no signs of
a recession in the United States.
   Stock trading was described as mixed by traders, who said buyers
were not as aggressive after nine straight days of solid gains in
the market.
   The morning volume was estimated at 700 million shares, a level
approaching Tuesday's all-day volume of 850 million shares.
</TEXT>
